<FIRST>r a AM-ClerkIndicted     04-20 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clerk Indicted,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blount County Clerk Indicted On Embezzlement Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARYVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A county clerk honored last year as
Tennessee's Clerk of the Year was arrested following his indictment
on charges he embezzled nearly $34,000 in public funds.
   Blount County Clerk Milburn Waters, 61, and Chief Deputy Clerk
Margaret Blair, 40, were arrested following their indictment by a
county grand jury Monday. They were released from the county jail
after posting bonds of $3,000 each.
   Waters has been clerk for 18 years in this eastern Tennessee
city near the Smoky Mountains, and often opens the day at his
office with a prayer and a Bible reading for employees. He is in
charge of collecting money and handling paperwork on business
taxes, marriage licenses and other matters.
   Eight counts in the indictment allege he stole $33,689 from the
county, and three counts accuse him of failing to deposit money
within the three days allowed by law. The charges cover September
1985 through June 1988.
   Blair, Waters' secretary until her promotion three weeks ago,
was indicted on one charge of embezzlement.
   If convicted, Waters faces up to 10 years in jail and Blair up
to five.
   News reports that Waters often took county money for his own
use, leaving IOUs, triggered an investigation by the state Bureau
of Investigation investigated. Waters denied any wrongdoing.
   Last year, Waters received the Clerk of the Year award from the
County Officials Association of Tennessee.
   Waters' award won't be rescinded, said Mahalia Hughes, Sumner
County Circuit Court clerk and secretary-treasurer for the
association.
   ``Once you get them you've got them,'' she said of the annual
awards. ``Waters has been an outstanding clerk as far as I know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
