<FIRST>r a AM-BosketSentencing 1stLd-Writethru a0682 04-20 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bosket Sentencing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmate Receives Additional 39{ To Life For Stabbing Guard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to CORRECT that maximum additional prison
term is 25 years, sted 39{, because new sentences will run concurrently;
picks up 4th graf: ``I think ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XKIN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE ZGANJAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Wednesday added at least 25
years to the prison term of an inmate whose incarceration began
with reform school at age 9 and who admitted murdering two men at
age 15 ``for the experience.''
   Willie Bosket, 26, was sentenced for the April 1988 stabbing of
a prison guard. He is already serving 28 years to life for assault,
arson and being a persistent felon.
   Ulster County Court Judge Francis Vogt sentenced Bosket to 25
years to life for first-degree attempted murder, 7{ to 15 years for
attempted assault, 3{ to 7 years for weapons possession, and 3{ to
7 years for promoting prison contraband. Those sentences will run
concurrently.
   ``I think you thrive on attention,'' Vogt said. ``Why else would
you plunge an 11-inch knife into the chest of a young man who did
you no harm, who you didn't even know?''
   ``You should never be turned loose on society,'' Vogt said,
adding that Bosket would remain a threat even while imprisoned.
   ``I'm sending an innocent person to death, because I'm sure
you'll kill someone (in prison).''
   Bosket has proved to be a security problem while in prison and
recently was charged with assaulting a guard. On his way into court
Wednesday, Bosket tried to kick a corrections officer who was
removing a leg manacle that bolted Bosket to the van.
   In court, Bosket began a rambling statement before the judge cut
him off.
   ``This sentence means nothing. I spit on this court,'' Bosket
said.
   ``I laugh at this court ... and the entire ... system. I'll
haunt this system. I am what this system created,'' he said.
   Vogt ordered that Bosket be removed from the courtroom
immediately after the sentencing when Bosket began to quote Russian
novelist Feodor Dostoevski.
   As he was being led out of the courthouse a reporter asked
Bosket if he would kill again. Bosket replied: ``Next time I will
not try, I'll succeed.''
   At his trial in February, Bosket said his only regret was that
he didn't succeed in killing guard Earl Porter with a handmade
knife.
   Bosket is held in solitary confinement in a specially
constructed cell.
   Bosket first gained notoriety in 1978 when he murdered two men
during robberies in New York City. The case was a catalyst for
change in New York state law regarding juveniles who commit murder.
</TEXT>
