<FIRST>r i PM-Drive-InOpera     04-20 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drive-In Opera,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Divas at the Drive-in: Norway Trying High Notes for Low Brows</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Norwegian National Opera wants to reach
a wider audience, so it's staging ``The Barber of Seville'' as a
drive-in movie, where motorists can toot for the tenor and feast on
burgers and fries 'til the fat lady sings.
   ``We were inspired by American drive-in movies,'' said opera
spokesman Terje Baskerud. ``It started as a wild idea, but we're
going to try it.''
   The state opera hopes to convert downtown Oslo's Youngstorget
open market into a drive-in for 200-300 cars with a live broadcast
on a giant TV screen of its Sept. 23 premiere of ``The Barber of
Seville,'' Baskerud said in an interview.
   ``We are arranging with local restaurants to serve food on trays
that hang from car windows, hopefully by waitresses on roller
skates,'' he said.
   There won't be tinny in-car speakers typical of U.S. drive-in
movies, ``but the music will be so loud that I don't think anyone
in the area will have trouble hearing the performance,'' he said.
They also hope to set up a 24-square-yard screen.
   Police, merchants and officials are intrigued by the notion of
marrying 19th century opera to 1950s Americana, but Olso residents
are skeptical, he said.
   ``Unfortunately, we first announced it on April 1 on local
radio. Everyone thought it was an April Fool's joke,'' he said.
Norwegians are wary of April 1 news because of the media's penchant
for tricking them.
   The state opera hopes the drive-in will be free, although its
budget will not cover the costly performance without sponsors.
   ``We haven't worked out all the details yet,'' said Petter
Martin Tanberg of the Drammen advertising agency Andersen and
Holter, which was hired by the opera to handle sponsors and
technical details.
   ``It's hard to say how much it will cost,'' he said, and reponse
from sponsors has yet to be measured. ``Of course, opera is a
favorable thing for businesses to be associated with.''
   People think opera is a grim forum for tales of murder and
betrayal, Baskerud said. ``We want them to see that `The Barber of
Seville' is not a serious piece. It's lively and funny,'' he said.
   The opera's 200 regular performances a year, held in a cramped
former movie theater, already average 90 percent bookings. But
manager Bjoern Simensen, who is known for his unconventional
approach to opera, sees the one-night drive-in scheme as an
investment in the future.
   ``It's great for us to be seen and heard outside our traditional
arena. It would be deadly for us to isolate ourselves in our
private fine arts ghetto,'' he said.
   The Italian-language performance of Rossini's `Barber of
Seville,' first sung in 1816, will be directed by Michail Hampe, a
Cologne Opera specialist in the works of Rossini, and conducted by
Italian Carlo Felice Cillareo, Simensen said.
   Iziar Martinez Galdos will sing the female lead Rosina and the
Scottish Opera's Neill Archer will sing Almaviva, with support from
the Norwegian opera's 26 singers, 42-member chorus and 75-piece
orchestra, Baskerud said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
