<FIRST>u a AM-WinerySlayings-Funeral 2ndLd-Writethru a0402 04-20 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings-Funeral, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0402,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Victims In Winery Rampage Buried</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Five Sonoma ..., to CORRECT cartoonist's name
to Charles M., sted George, Schulz.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Winery Slayings</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XNOV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PETALUMA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six of the seven people slain in a
bloody rampage were laid to rest Wednesday on a quiet, green
hillside in California's wine country and residents learned the
prime suspect had been arrested in Mexico.
   ``This is a day of relief for Sonoma County,'' Sheriff Dick
Michaelsen said after Ramon Salcido Bojorquez' arrest early
Wednesday in Sinaloa state about 850 miles north of Mexico City.
   U.S. authorities hope to extradite Salcido, 28, who had been
sought in an international manhunt since last Friday's killing
spree.
   Salcido is accused of killing his wife, two daughters,
mother-in-law, two sisters-in-law and a winery co-worker.
   Five Sonoma County detectives flew Wednesday afternoon to Mexico
in a Lear jet owned by ``Peanuts'' cartoonist Charles M. Schulz,
who lives in the county, and piloted by his son, Craig, Michaelsen
said.
   Salcido is accused of killing his wife, two daughters,
mother-in-law, two sisters-in-law and a winery co-worker.
   He told Mexican police that he killed his wife, Angela, and
co-worker Tracy Toovey because he suspected they were having an
affair, Deputy Attorney General Javier Coello Tracy said in Mexico.
   Salcido's arrest was reported Wednesday morning as about 100
people attended private funeral services for Mrs. Salcido, her
daughters Sofia, 4, and Teresa, 1; her mother, Marian Louise
Richards, 47; and her two young daughters, Ruth, 12, and Marie, 8.
   The Rev. Kenneth Cabral of Oakland, a retired Roman Catholic
priest who is a longtime friend of the Richards, officiated at
services preceding burial in a large gravesite at Calvary Catholic
Cemetery.
   Cabral told mourners guarded by 20 sheriff's deputies, ``Death
isn't the end. ... After you die, there are all kinds of beautiful
things awaiting,'' said Judith Kelly, who was among the mourners.
   One by one, white caskets containing the children's bodies and
gray caskets with those of the adults were taken from a cemetery
mausoleum to the burial site and lowered into the ground along with
metal crucifixes and flowers.
   Immediately after the service ended, Angela Salcido's father,
Bob Richards, was told of Salcido's arrest, Undersheriff Gene Fahy
said.
   Richards then went to Petaluma Valley Hospital to visit Carmina
Salcido, 2. Carmina and her sisters' throats were cut, and they
were abandoned at a dump.
   Kelly said the three Richards sons who attended the funeral
agreed they want Carmina to live with a family member when she
recovers.
   The investigators on Shultz' plane were going to Mexico to
discuss extradition and other aspects of the case with Mexican
authorities.
   Although Salcido became a permanent U.S. resident in 1986 after
marrying his wife, he remains a Mexican citizen, said David
Ilchert, district director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service in San Francisco.
   That could help him avoid trial in the United States and a
possible death sentence if convicted.
   Mexico's penal code provides that Mexican citizens can be tried
there for crimes committed elsewhere, but that country does not
have a death penalty.
   FBI agent Mike Dooher said he was confident Salcido would be
returned to the United States regardless of his status.
   But Sonoma County District Attorney Gene Tunney said he had
tried unsuccessfully on two previous occasions to extradite Mexican
citizens on county murder charges.
   ``Of course, we'd rather prosecute him (Salcido) here,'' said
Tunney. ``If there was ever a death penalty case, this is it.
   ``But I would rather have him prosecuted in Mexico under their
law instead of having him go free.''
</TEXT>
