<FIRST>r a PM-CaponeHouse     04-20 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capone House,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Drops Fight To Have Capone's House Listed On National Register</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An amateur historian says he is yielding to
pressure from Italian-American groups and dropping efforts to have
gangster Al Capone's old house listed on the National Register of
Historic Places.
   ``I still think the house has tremendous historical interest,
but I have no intention of offending anyone, and some people left
me no doubt that they quite clearly are offended by it,'' Mark
Levell said Wednesday.
   Levell, a computer repairman, took up the cause of having the
privately owned house placed on the register in January, after
requests from others were rejected by the Chicago Landmarks
Commission and the Illinois Historic Sites Council.
   His appeal of those rejections went all the way to the National
Register.
   On the way, however, Levell's appeal drew the wrath of the Joint
Civic Committee of Italian-Americans and the Chicago Sun-Times, as
well as the Park Manor Neighborhood Council, which represents
residents of the South Side neighborhood where the house is located.
   The neighborhood council complained that placing the modest
two-story brick house on the register might draw additional
unwanted tourism to Park Manor, which is already visited on a
regular basis by gangster-theme bus tours.
   The newspaper complained that emphasizing 1920s gangster lore
does little for the city's image, and the Italian-American group
objected to continuation of the Italian gangster stereotype.
   ``They complained that I was trying to honor a notorious
criminal, but I never said anything about `honor,''' Levell said.
``The Prohibition gangsters were part of this city's history _
that's all. They were colorful men, but I never suggested them as
role models for anyone.''
   Levell's decision to withdraw the appeal was hailed by Robert
Allegrini, executive director of the Italian-American committee,
who said he was glad Levell had come to understand the sensitivity
of law-abiding Italian-Americans to depiction of their ethnic group
as mobsters.
   ``I'm half Italian myself,'' said Levell. ``The Italian half of
me says one thing, but the historian half of me says, `This is
history.'''
   Levell said Capone lived in the house from 1920 to 1928, but
later moved into the Lexington Hotel for security reasons. He said
Capone's mother and several of his brothers remained in the house
after ``Scarface'' moved out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
