<FIRST>r a PM-QueenCity     04-20 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Queen City,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Want To Change Town's Queen City Nickname</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARQUETTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Municipal leaders want to change their
town's ``Queen City'' nickname to ``Superior Location'' because
they think the current moniker might be misinterpreted.
   ``It has come to my attention that there has been a resurgence
of the use of the phrase `Queen City' to describe the city of
Marquette,'' City Manager David Svanda said in a recent letter to
community leaders.
   ``The term's negative connotations conjured by many people do
not give justice to all that the Marquette area has to offer.''
   Visitors might think Queen City refers to homosexuals, said
Mayor Robert Berube.
   Marquette historian Fred Rydholm, who is writing a history of
the Lake Superior port of 23,280 people, said that was silly.
Svanda's request is ``the most ridiculous thing I've ever heard,''
Rydholm said.
   The Queen City nickname originated after a 1868 fire, when an
ordinance required all buildings in the center city area to be
rebuilt with stone or masonry, he said.
   Visitors expecting to see the wood construction of other Upper
Peninsula towns in Michigan instead were greeted with tall spires
of stone.
   ``There was nothing from Seattle to Buffalo like it in the
north, and it was also the best port on Lake Superior, so it was
called the Queen City of the North,'' Rydholm said.
</TEXT>
