<FIRST>r w PM-Iran-Contra     04-20 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Concedes Committee Missed Some Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration says the congressional
Iran-Contra committees never saw two recently-released politically
sensitive documents but denies there were any efforts to conceal
them, according to a published report.
   An unnamed administration official told The Washington Post the
documents were in an archive whose contents were available to the
committees if they specifically requested them. But the panels
never asked to see the documents, the official said.
   One document refers to then-Vice President George Bush's secret
involvement in a deal to reward Honduras for aiding the Nicaraguan
Contras, the newspaper reported in today's editions.
   The paper said the official's account left open the possibility
the committees would not have known the contents of the documents
in question and would not have known to request them.
   Key members of the Iran-Contra panels have raised the
possibility that several important White House documents on former
President Reagan and Bush's role in efforts to reward those aiding
the Contras were withheld from the House and Senate panels.
   Bush has said twice that the documents, which were released
during the trial of former White House aide Oliver North, were
``available'' to the Iran-Contra committees.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Wednesday night the
documents in North's National Security Council office were
immediately seized by the FBI and sealed up on the late November
1986 weekend during the initial inquiry into the Iran-Contra affair
by then Attorney General Edwin Meese.
   He added that the documents had been in the joint custody of the
White House and the FBI and said the White House had at least
partial custody because many of the documents were classified.
   He said the White House had ``some say'' in the way the
documents were dispersed, but he insisted that at no time were they
off-limits to the committees.
</TEXT>
