<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-20 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen, Share Prices Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar finished higher Thursday against
the Japanese yen in Tokyo, while share prices declined.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which closed at a record high of 33,363.83 on
Wednesday, shed 178.68 points, or 0.54 percent, to finish trading
at 33,185.15.
   The dollar ended the day at 132.28 yen, up 0.40 yen from
Wednesday's closing of 131.88 yen. The U.S. currency opened at
132.40 yen and ranged from 132.10 to 132.47 yen during the day.
   Traders said the dollar-yen trading moved in a narrow range as
players continued to make position adjustments in the wake of the
Tuesday release of the March U.S. consumer price index. The figure,
a 0.5-percent increase, slightly up from February's 0.4 percent,
indicated a slowdown in the U.S. economy.
   Toshio Kiri of the Bank of Tokyo attributed the dollar'shigher
opening in Tokyo to similar trends on overseas markets in the wake
of higher oil prices.
   But the U.S. currency gradually eased due to dollar-selling by
export companies, he said.
   The majority of Japanese investors, however, made only minor
technical adjustments, Kiri said.
   ``Even though investors start selling the dollar, it is unlikely
to fall further because the currency's still quite strong,'' he
said.
   On the stock market, a rise in oil prices, triggered by a North
Sea gas explosion, discouraged participants and resulted in the
index's decline in Tokyo, said an analyst with Nomura Securities.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May price of West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose $1.10 to
$22.61 a barrel, the highest level since Jan. 17, 1986.
   ``A rise in oil prices discourages market players because they
expect it would lead to lower yen, inflation and interest rate
hikes,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``But I believe the Japanese economy has become strong enough to
remain stable against such external factors,'' the analyst added.
</TEXT>
