<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Coalition Announces Plans for Huge October Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing activists are predicting hundreds of
thousands of people will march on the nation's capital Oct. 7 to
demand more federal housing assistance for the nation's homeless.
   More than 60 organizations, including the AFL-CIO, the U.S.
Conference of Mayors, the National Organization for Women and the
National Urban League, are cooperating on the march under the
banner ``Housing Now!''
   ``This isn't a march so much as it is a calling forth of the
human spirit,'' Valerie Harper, the actress and longtime homeless
activist, said at a press conference on Wednesday. ``It's an
expression of who we are as human beings.''
   Barry Zigas, a principal organizer of the march and president of
the National Low-Income Housing Coalition, predicted that
``hundreds of thousands'' of people would participate.
   Since 1981, budget authority for all federal housing assistance
programs has been cut by more than 75 percent _ from $32 billion to
less than $8 billion a year, according to the new coalition.
