<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>HHS Official Says Computer System Could Guard Against Drug</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Reactions
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is mounting a prescription drug
benefit program for Medicare beneficiaries that officials say will
help guard against adverse reactions that hospitalize at least
200,000 elderly people a year.
   Richard Kusserow, inspector general for the Department of Health
and Human Services, told a House panel on Wednesday the Medicare
computer system would link the nation's pharmacies so a pharmacist
would be able to tell on the spot whether the patient is taking
another drug that could react with the new one.
   He said time is needed to establish the system, saying it would
be ``stupid'' for Congress to be so insistent on enforcing an
arbitrary deadline for setting up a computer-based billing system
that it closes off the possibility of building in the safeguards.
   Kusserow was called before the subcommittee of the Select
Committee on Aging to elaborate on a study that has found the
Medicare program paid at least $500 million in 1987 for hospital
admissions that were related to an adverse prescription drug
reaction or an overdose.
