<NOTE>Trade Friction Could Upset Democracy, Minister Warns</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Targeting South Korea for sanctions under
America's tough new trade law could produce a severe backlash there
and even destabilize the country's fledgling democracy, warns the
South Korean trade minister.
   Minister Han Seung-soo summarized to reporters Wednesday the
message he brought to U.S. government and congressional leaders
this week -- South Korea has been a responsive and responsible U.S.
trade partner and branding it as an unfair trader could have highly
adverse results at home.
   ``Our democracy is only about one year old and much more fragile
than the Philippines','' he said, comparing South Korea to another
U.S. ally. ``It would be advisable not to destabilize our
democratization program.''
   Under a 1988 law, the U.S. government has until the end of next
month to designate countries with persistent surpluses with America
for investigation of unfair trade practices and potential
sanctions. South Korea is a candidate for such targeting.
