<FIRST>r i PM-CallGirl'sStory     04-20 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Call Girl's Story,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Speaker Wright Pictured With Former Call Girl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Pamella is correct first name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright and self-described former
call girl Pamella Bordes, a one-time researcher in Parliament, are
pictured together in a 1983 photograph printed today by the British
newspaper the Daily Mail.
   Wright is currently under investigation for alleged unethical
conduct. Ms. Bordes, 26, is a former Miss India whose sex and
scandal memoirs involving rich and powerful men around the world
are being serialized by the London tabloid.
   The paper reported today in the second installment of her
memoirs that the picture of her and Wright was taken in Wright's
office on Capitol Hill before he became House speaker.
   In its copyrighted story, the paper said that at the time Ms.
Bordes was working for the Indian mystic and businessman Chandra
Swami. The meeting was arranged by the Swami, who had business
connections in Washington, the paper reported.
   It continued: ``Among the things discussed, according to those
close to the Swami, was the possibility of obtaining a `green card'
permit for Pamella officially to become an American resident.
   ``Unknown to Jim Wright, this was at a time when she was, in her
own words, working as `sex bait' for the Swami's international
business deals. At the meeting, the Swami presented Mr. Wright with
some ceremonial gifts and pleaded with him to help Pamella ...
   ``His (Wright's) staff sent a copy of this picture to Pamella
signed with his best wishes. She and the Swami left the country in
a hurry after a business deal began to go legally sour.
   ``A spokesman for Mr. Wright said last night (Wednesday) that
they remembered the meeting with the Swami and his party, of which
Pamella Singh (as she was then known) was a member, but they did
not recall doing anything to help her obtain a green card.''
   Wright was cited Monday by the House ethics committee for 69
violations of House rules, including allegations he improperly
accepted nearly $145,000 in gifts and that his wife was paid
$72,000 for work she didn't do.
   He has denied charges he violated any House rules, including the
alleged use of book sales to duck a speech-fee limit.
   The Daily Mail has bought the rights to Ms. Bordes' story.
   Today's installment told how she met Chandra Swami after
arriving in New York in 1982 as the reigning Miss India.
   It said the Swami offered her a job as a public relations
executive that it described as ``a euphemism for sexual bait.''
   The first installment Wednesday contained lurid tales of sex
with financier Adnan Khashoggi, now in a Swiss prison, with a Saudi
prince and with Libyan Ahmed Gadaff Al Diam.
   The Daily Mail identified Al Diam as a cousin of Libyan leader
Col. Moammar Gadhafi, second-in-command of Libyan intelligence and
Libya's top arms buyer in Europe.
   She was quoted in Wednesday's installment as saying she got
money from Al Diam and stayed in touch with him until shortly
before she got a job last year as a researcher in the British
Parliament.
   It was that job that led to the British press's discovery of her
background and raised questions about whether national security was
compromised by allowing free movement in the House of Commons to a
woman with high-level Libyan connections.
   Ms. Bordes fled to Bali, was tracked down by British reporters,
and offered her story to the highest bidder.
   Khashoggi, 54, was arrested Tuesday in Switzerland on a U.S.
warrant charging that he helped hide assets that deposed
Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos and his wife Imelda
allegedly stole from their country.
   The tabloid said her ``sexual availability was a hard currency
used to smooth contacts between ruthless arms dealers and nations.''
</TEXT>
