<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Bomb     04-20 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Bomb,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government: May Be Link Between Jailed Palestinians, Flight 103</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says the discovery of a
third bomb, this one hidden in a television set, by police probing
the case of two jailed Palestinians indicates they may be linked to
the downing of Flight 103.
   According to the government's Today in Parliament news service,
police found the bomb in the same apartment in the Duesseldorf
suburb of Neuss where two other explosive devices, hidden in radio
tuners, were seized last week.
   One booby-trapped tuner exploded Monday at federal police
headquarters in Wiesbaden when experts tried to disarm it, killing
Hans-Juergen Sonntag, 35, and wounding a 29-year-old colleague.
   In a followup search of the apartment, investigators found the
third bomb, Alexander Prechtel, spokesman for the federal
prosecutor's office in Karlsruhe, said Wednesday.
   British investigators looking into the Dec. 21 Pan Am crash have
said the plane was blown out of the sky over Scotland by plastic
explosives hidden in a radio-cassette player.
   The imprisoned Palestinians _ Hafez Kassem Dalkamoni and Abdul
Fattah Ghandanfar _ are suspected of forming terrorist cells in
West Germany, illegal possession of weapons and two bomb attacks on
U.S. military trains, Prechtel said. The train attacks in August
1987 and April 1988 caused no injuries.
   Prechtel confirmed details of the parliamentary report, but said
again that no solid evidence has emerged to link the Palestinian
case with the disaster over Lockerbie that killed 259 people on the
plane and 11 on the ground.
   The news service informs federal officials of matters discussed
in parliamentary committees. Wednesday's report was based on
information brought to the body's internal affairs committee. No
sources were cited.
   ``There is a possible connection between the bomb found
(Thursday) and the crash of the jet over the Scottish city of
Lockerbie on Dec. 21,'' it said.
   Prechtel disputed the suggestion that the probe of the two
Palestinians, suspected of being agents of the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, turned up indications
the two were involved with Lockerbie.
   ``I know about that being said, but that is nothing but
speculation,'' he said. ``They can't say it's not connected, so
they speculate that it is. But we have no evidence that it is
connected to Lockerbie _ only the theoretical possibility exists.''
   The two Palestinians were arrested in October after what police
said was the biggest seizure of illegal weapons in West Germany's
history.
   Authorities refused to describe the three bombs found last week
in detail or say whether they were armed with plastic explosives
similar to those found in the October raids.
   A radio-cassette player bomb containing the same type of
Czechoslovak-made plastic explosives as used in the Pan Am bombing
was among the weapons seized in October.
   Police arrested 14 suspects in the October raids but only
Dalkamoni and Ghandanfar remain in custody.
   Prechtel said Tuesday that authorities expect to file charges
against the two within a few months and bring them to trial this
year.
</TEXT>
