<FIRST>r a PM-SergeantAcquitted     04-20 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sergeant Acquitted,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Sergeant Acquitted Of Murder Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army sergeant who was sentenced to
death for the murders of a woman and two of her children was
acquitted in a retrial and will return to his military post.
   Timothy Hennis was to report today to Fort Bragg and then
transfer to Fort Knox, Ky., where he is still assigned to the
personnel control facility. He retained his rank throughout the
trial and appeal.
   Hennis, 31, was acquitted Wednesday and jumped when the verdict
was read. He then broke into tears.
   ``I missed my wife, and I missed my daughter, especially my
daughter,'' he said, calling the last four years a nightmare.
   In May 1985, Hennis was charged with murder in the deaths of
Kathryn Eastburn, 32, her daughters Kara, 5, and Erin, 3. He also
was charged with raping Mrs. Eastburn.
   ``I personally didn't feel at any time that he was proven
guilty,'' said New Hanover County Superior Court juror Kenneth
Wells. ``For a lot of us, it was a pretty quick decision to make.''
   The jury deliberated a little more than two hours. Some jurors
remained in the courthouse to hug Hennis, his family and attorneys.
   One juror said a key to the acquittal was the prosecution's
failure to prove that Hennis was inside the Eastburn house on the
night of the slayings.
   The second trial included testimony from a new witness who said
he often took walks at night in clothing similar to what a witness
in the original trial said he saw Hennis wearing that night.
   Juror Debbie McDowell said the jury believed the original
witness was mistaken when he identified the man in the Eastburn's
driveway late one night as Hennis.
   Hennis told police when he was arrested that he had been at the
Eastburn's house earlier in the day in response to an advertisement
they had placed in the newspaper seeking a home for their dog. But
he denied he was there later that night when the killings were
believed to have taken place.
   He was convicted in 1986, but the state Supreme Court ordered a
new trial because of graphic photos of the crime scene that were
shown to jurors.
   Air Force Capt. Gary Eastburn, the victim's husband, called the
retrial a mistake and said there was no basis for the Supreme
Court's decision.
   ``I was shocked at first, surprised, disappointed,'' Eastburn
said.
   He said he planned to return to England, where he and a
surviving daughter now live.
</TEXT>
