<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 0545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-20 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Fall, Dollar Edges Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index fell and the
dollar edged up against the Japanese yen today as a rise in oil
prices encouraged dollar buying and discouraged stock purchases,
traders said.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 178.68 points, or 0.54
percent, closing at 33,185.15. The index had gained 42.17 points to
a record 33,363.83 close Wednesday.
   The dollar ended trading at 132.28 yen, up 0.40 yen from the
previous day's 131.88-yen finish. It opened at 132.40 yen and
ranged between 132.10 yen and 132.47 yen.
   Traders said the dollar's higher opening in Tokyo followed a
rise on overseas markets after a sharp rise in oil prices,
triggered by a North Sea gas explosion.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May price of West Texas
intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose $1.10 to
$22.61 a barrel, the highest since Jan. 17, 1986.
   After opening higher, however, the dollar gradually fell as
export companies and small trading houses sold dollars from their
overseas revenues, said an analyst with a commercial bank in Tokyo,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``Then a rumor about a possible Japanese interest rate hike
spread in the market and inspired yen buying,'' he said, adding
that he could not confirm the rumor.
   The analyst added that dollar buying also dropped off because of
a comment by Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita that the
dollar's further climb would be harmful for Japanese prices.
   At a meeting with credit bank officials today, Sumita said:
``The dollar's excessive rise can be a big roadblock for our
efforts to keep Japanese prices stable and ensure a smooth
adjustment process in major nations.''
   He predicted the dollar is ``unlikely to climb persistently''
now because economic fundamentals affecting it remain more or less
unchanged.
   On the stock market, dealers said the oil price increase largely
discouraged investors.
   The price of Tokyo Electric Power Co. stock, directly affected
by the higher oil price, dropped 40 yen and closed at 5,790 yen,
its lowest this year.
   A Nomura Securities dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said investors' biggest concern is a possible interest rate hike in
Japan.
   Higher oil prices could lead to a lower yen and inflation, and
then interest rate hikes aimed at curbing the inflation.
   ``Concerns over an interest rate hike are much greater than
concerns over political instability,'' the dealer said.
   ``The release of the Japanese consumer price index figure next
week already has been making players reluctant to make major moves
because the CPI is an important indicator of economic growth,'' he
added.
   Volume on the first section of trading was estimated at 900
million shares, down from Wednesday's 1.4 billion.
</TEXT>
