<HEAD>Mother Arrested After Teddy Bear With Drug Gear Brought to School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASTRO VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman was arrested after her
daughter brought a teddy bear stuffed with drug paraphernalia to
school for ``share day,'' authorities said.
   Alicia Tapia, 42, was arrested at her parole officer's office
Wednesday on a charge of misdemeanor child endangerment, said
Alameda County Sheriff's Sgt. Dale Toussaint.
   The 8-year-old daughter, blind since birth, brought the teddy
bear called ``Ticklebear'' to school Tuesday to show her classmates
at Castro Valley Elementary School in the east San Francisco Bay
area, near Oakland.
   The girl told teacher's aide Diane Oxford that Ticklebear used
to laugh when it was hugged, but that the battery operated voice
box inside no longer worked, according to the sheriff's report.
   In an effort to fix the voice box, Oxford unzipped the back of
the toy and found a plastic bag containing a syringe, a bottle cap
fashioned into a homemade drug ``cooker'' and residue from an
unidentified drug, said Toussaint. The aide brought the bear to the
principal, who called deputies.
   The children were taken into protective custody and Tapia was
booked in lieu of $10,000 bail. She had served a jail term in 1985
for petty theft, according to court records.
