<FIRST>u i PM-WinerySlayings     04-20 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Winery Slayings,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect Confesses To California Winery Slayings</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A winery worker captured at a roadblock has
confessed to killing seven people in California, including his wife
and two of his daughters, in what Mexican police said was a frenzy
of jealousy over her.
   Authorities prepared for extradition proceedings they said could
take months because the suspect, Ramon Salcido Bojorquez, is a
Mexican citizen.
   ``I'm guilty,'' the 28-year-old Salcido said in a television
interview with the private Televisa network Wednesday night in
Mazatlan. ``I did the killings in the United States and I expect to
be judged there.
   ``I came to Mexico to see my parents for the last time,'' he
said in the interview. He refused to discuss his motives for the
crimes, but said, ``I came to Mexico to see my parents for the last
time.''
   Salcido was arrested off a bus before dawn Wednesday at a
roadblock set up by anti-drug agents outside the northwestern
village of Guasave, officials said. The village is near Salcido's
hometown of Los Mochis.
   The attorney general's office said in a news release that
Salcido told Mexican police he killed ``motivated by jealousy,
after he suspected that his wife was linked to (co-worker) Tracy
Toovey.''
   Salcido is suspected of killing his wife, Toovey, two of his
daughters, his mother-in-law and two young sisters-in-law in a
rampage in Sonoma County, Calif. last weekend.
   He has been charged with four of the killings and was being
sought on a federal warrant for flight to avoid prosecution.
Salcido was a forklift operator who worked with Toovey at the Grand
Cru Vineyards.
   Fernando Arias, spokesman for the attorney general's office,
said police would escort Salcido to Mexico City on a Mexicana
flight due to arrive at 3:15 p.m. today (5:15 p.m. EDT).
   In the Mexican capital, Salcido was to undergo more questioning
as well as extradition proceedings. Officials said he had crossed
the U.S. border at Calexico.
   The attorney general's office said Salcido told police under
questioning he had lived in California for nine years and acquired
American citizenship.
   But U.S. authorities say Salcido apparently never applied for
U.S. naturalization papers and remains a Mexican citizen, meaning
the extradition process could take months. Arias said the process
could be completed in as little as a day or so.
   Salcido could face the death penalty under California law.
Mexico has no capital punishment.
   He was arrested the same day services were held in Petaluma,
Calif., for the six members of Salcido's family who were killed.
   Salcido's wife, mother-in-law, two sisters-in-law, and Toovey
were butchered and shot to death Friday. The next day, three of
Salcido's daughters were found with their throats cut, two of them
dead.
   The only survivor, 2-year-old Carmina, is recovering in Petaluma
Valley Hospital. She told investigators her father cut her and her
sisters.
   Salcido's friends told the San Francisco Examiner that he had a
frenzied, cocaine-fueled night of drinking and dancing before the
killings.
   The friends said the binge began the night of April 12, a day
after Salcido had been served with Fresno County, Calif., court
papers ordering him to pay $511 a month support for a 4{-year-old
daughter from another marriage, plus nearly $6,000 to the county
for back payments.
   In San Francisco, affidavits filed against Salcido in U.S.
District Court this week disclosed he left a note asking God's
mercy and blaming the law for the slayings, apparently referring to
the court order in the child-support case.
   Under a 1973 treaty, Mexico is obliged to honor any U.S.
extradition request, but the procedure is cumbersome and can take
months.
   A U.S. court has to request the extradition, detailing the
evidence, through the Department of Justice and the State
Department, which in turn petitions the Mexican Department of
Foreign Affairs.
   The department has to approve it, then turn it over to the
Mexican attorney general's office, which also has to approve it.
The petition then goes to the federal judge holding the suspect,
who next issues a warrant ordering the suspect to be surrendered to
U.S. authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
