<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Rising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held steady in light European trading
today as the market apparently lacked interest in pushing the U.S.
currency in either direction. Gold prices rose in Europe.
   Dealers said the dollar remained in a narrow range and trading
was light and lethargic.
   ``It is very quiet and very boring, and it has been for a few
days now,'' said a trader in Milan. He said the narrowing of an
interest rate differential between the German mark and the dollar
had largely removed any incentive to rally the dollar.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7105 today, cheaper for
buyers than late Wednesday's $1.7113.
   Other rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Wednesday's
late rates:
   _1.8603 West German marks, down from 1.8615
   _1.6305 Swiss francs, down from 1.6360
   _6.2965 French francs, down from 6.3025
   _2.0992 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0985
   _1,364.50 Italian lire, up from 1,363.75
   _1.1850 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1865
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 132.28 Japanese yen, up
from 131.88. In London, the dollar traded at 132.15 yen.
   In London, gold bullion opened at a bid $383.25 a troy ounce,
down from $383.95 late Wednesday. At midmorning, London's gold
dealers fixed a recommended price of $383.90.
   Zurich gold was quoted at a bid price of $383.60 a troy ounce,
higher than late Wednesday's $383.50.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $385.45, up from $384.25.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.78 a troy
ounce, down from $5.79.
