<FIRST>r a PM-EspionageSentence     04-20 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Espionage Sentence,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Analyst Sentenced For Supplying Information to South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who admitted giving more than 200
documents to the South African government has been sentenced to 10
years in a federal prison and fined $5,000.
   ``Communicating vital classified information to agents of a
foreign power is despicable,'' U.S. District Court Judge Herbert F.
Murray told Joseph Dolce of Havre de Grace as he imposed the
maximum sentence Wednesday.
   Dolce, a former weapons analyst at Aberdeen Proving Ground,
pleaded guilty Oct. 11 to one count of espionage as part of a plea
bargain with federal prosecutors.
   ``I have failed my country, my family and myself,'' Dolce said.
``I can only hope that with time I can demonstrate to my children
that their father is an honorable man.''
   The 215 pieces of information the civilian analyst relayed from
1979 to 1983 were only moderately damaging or of little threat to
national security, assistant U.S. attorney Gary Jordan said. Dolce,
49, terminated his relationship with the South Africans in 1983,
apparently because of a personality clash with a new defense
attache.
   Jordan said Dolce provided South Africans with classified
information about U.S. and Soviet conventional weapons systems,
``their capabilities and their frailties.''
   Harold I. Glaser, Dolce's attorney, said the civilian analyst
did not intend to harm the United States but saw himself as helping
the United States by aiding an ally. Dolce said he did not get any
money for the information, which he passed on at the South African
Embassy in Washington and at missions in London and Los Angeles.
   Dolce was intent on assisting South Africa its war in Angola
against Soviet-backed Cuban and Marxist Angolan troops, Glaser said.
   Dolce resigned Sept. 30 from his $34,000-a-year job as a
research analyst for the Army Material Systems Analyst Activity, an
agency that evaluates weapons systems. He had a midlevel security
clearance.
</TEXT>
