<FIRST>r a PM-LucilleBall     04-20 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lucille Ball,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lucy Showered With Affection From Fans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flowers and get-well wishes from fans around
the world deluged the hospital where Lucille Ball was in critical
condition today recuperating from emergency heart surgery.
   Miss Ball's husband, Gary Morton, said the TV actress was ``in
great spirits.''
   Doctors replaced the 77-year-old comedian's main heart artery,
or aorta, and aortic valve Tuesday with organ tissue taken from the
body of an unidentified 27-year-old man. Her condition was listed
as critical, primarily because of the seriousness of the surgery,
said Ron Wise, spokesman at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center.
   ``She continues to show steady progress,'' Wise said late
Wednesday. Doctors were optimistic Miss Ball would make a full
recovery, he added.
   The hospital received hundreds of messages and inquiries from
fans and the media worldwide, Wise said.
   ``Before it's over the hospital will look like a combination of
the U.S. post office and the botanical gardens,'' he said.
   One fan donated blood in Miss Ball's name. Another brought
poetry. Celebrity well-wishers who called her husband included pop
singer Michael Jackson, actress Eva Gabor and publisher Malcolm
Forbes.
   ``We laughed a lot and had some fun,'' Morton said after
visiting his wife Wednesday. ``She's just in great spirits _ a
little pain, but she's doing nicely, thank you.''
   Morton said Miss Ball wanted to know ``How's the dog?'' and told
him to ``Go home, go home, go home.''
   Fans tacked dozens of cards to the door of the couple's Beverly
Hills home, Morton said.
   Miss Ball married Morton, who has been her executive producer,
in 1961.
   The redheaded entertainer is best known for the zany character
she portrayed opposite her late ex-husband, Desi Arnaz, in the ``I
Love Lucy Show.'' The program, one of the most popular in
television history, aired from 1951 to 1957 and is still seen
throughout the world in reruns.
</TEXT>
