<FIRST>r a PM-CruseSentencing     04-20 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cruse Sentencing,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shopping Center Killer Gets Death Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has recommended that a former
librarian be sent to the electric chair for killing six people and
trying to kill 24 others in a 1987 shopping-center death spree.
   A videotape showing a composed and articulate William Cruse, 61,
hours after the rampage was the prosecutors' best weapon, jurors
said.
   ``We all felt the same _ he knew what he was doing,'' juror
Edward Cook said Wednesday after the Polk County panel brought in
the death penalty recommendation for the murders of two young
college students, a 67-year-old grandmother, an engineer and two
police officers.
   The same jury rejected an insanity plea and convicted Cruse on
April 5 of 32 counts of murder, attempted murder and kidnapping in
the April 23, 1987, melee at two shopping centers in Palm Bay,
about 30 miles south of Cape Canaveral on Florida's east coast.
   ``Cruse declared war on the community of Palm Bay,'' said State
Attorney Norm Wolfinger. ``The jury verdicts were very appropriate.
... Without that tape, the jury would have had to guess. They saw
the real Cruse on that tape.''
   ``It was the tape,'' said jury foreman Wayne Hogan. ``The tape
had a lot to do with it.''
   Circuit Judge John Antoon set sentencing for July 28, when he
can sentence Cruse either to death or to life in prison with the
possibility of parole in 25 years.
   The videotape shown during the five-week trial showed an
apparently relaxed Cruse answering questions about the shootings.
   He expressed surprise that he had shot anyone but said he was
``trying to get back'' at people who taunted him and thought he was
a homosexual. He said he was ``drunk and crazy.''
</TEXT>
