<FIRST>r w PM-Coverdell     04-20 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coverdell,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Confirms Georgian As Peace Corps Director</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has confirmed President Bush's
nomination of Georgia state Sen. Paul Coverdell to head the Peace
Corps.
   The Senate acted on a voice vote late Wednesday, one day after
the Foreign Relations Committee had recommended approval of
Coverdell, who was the Republican leader of the Georgia Senate.
   Coverdell, 50, is a former chairman of the Georgia Republican
Party and an active supporter of President Bush since 1979. He was
chairman of Bush's Georgia campaign committee during his
unsuccessful 1980 presidential race and chairman of his Southern
steering committee during the 1988 campaign.
   Coverdell, owner of an insurance business in Atlanta, succeeds
Loret Miller Ruppe, who has been director of the Peace Corps since
1981, the longest tenure of any director since the agency was
founded in 1961 by President John F. Kennedy.
   Coverdell told the Foreign Relations Committee last week that he
supports the congressional mandate for an increase in the number of
Peace Corps volunteers to 10,000, from the current level of 7,000.
   He said he also wants to increase the number of minority
volunteers in the corps, which now is 93 percent white, and to
expand the Peace Corps' domestic role of promoting a better
understanding by Americans of people from other countries.
</TEXT>
