<FIRST>r i PM-Pope-Walesa     04-20 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Walesa,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Meets Walesa, Prays For Success of Political Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II today embraced fellow Pole
Lech Walesa and told the Solidarity leader he is praying for the
success of the new political reforms in their homeland.
   ``My batteries are recharged, and now I am ready to lift any
weight,'' Walesa said after a 30-minute private audience.
   The charismatic Polish labor leader, who said he had come to
seek the pope's blessing for the changes in Poland, briefed the
pope on the recent accords with the communist government restoring
the legality of the Soviet bloc's first independent trade union
after nearly eight years of repression.
   Earlier today, Walesa visited the hospital where the pope was
treated after being shot by a Turkish gunman in 1981 and said:
``Here the life of Solidarity was saved because here the life of a
great Pole, the holy father, was saved.''
   Walesa received the pope's warm endorsement of Solidarity during
a visit to the Vatican in January 1981. During today's audience,
Walesa said Solidarity had its roots in the social doctrine of the
Roman Catholic Church, according to a brief account of the meeting
by Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro.
   The church is a major force in Poland, and church
representatives participated in the negotiations that produced the
reforms.
   Navarro quoted the pope as saying he prays that ``the country
has a new possibility and that the transformations in the social,
political and economic life of the entire society can take place.''
   When Walesa arrived at the pope's private library, he knelt at
John Paul's feet. The pope pulled him up and embraced him, saying:
``We have to show how you greet the pope and how I greet you.''
   ``I greet you with all my heart,'' Walesa said.
   The half-hour audience was considered long by Vatican standards,
especially since no time was taken up by translation between the
two countrymen.
   After the private discussions, the two men were joined in the
library by Walesa's wife, Danuta, and five Solidarity aides and the
bishop of Gdansk, where the shipyard technician lives.
   It was the fourth meeting between the pope and Walesa. They also
met during pilgrimages by the pope to his homeland in 1983, the
year Walesa won the Nobel Peace Prize, and again in 1987.
   When the pope presented Walesa with a mosiac of the Madonna, he
said: ``This is a remembrance for Lech Walesa and for Solidarity
which has been reborn.'' Walesa gave the pope an album entitled
``The Birth of Solidarity.''
   Walesa, invited to Rome by Italy's trade union leaders, has said
he would seek Western help for Poland's economic crisis. He will
meet with top Italian officials on Friday.
   During his visit to the Gemelli Hospital, he blamed the
communist government for Poland's ``economic disaster'' but said he
is ready to work with the government to overcome the difficulties.
</TEXT>
