<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--JailedJuror     04-20 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Jailed Juror,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Potential Juror Jailed For Remark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard C. Dobbins Jr. came to court as
a potential juror and left in handcuffs for jail after he yelled
``Guilty!'' and forced court officials to send other potential
jurors home.
   Superior Judge Maxwell J. Heiman found the Watertown resident in
contempt, sentenced him to 10 days in jail and fined him $100 for
causing 66 others in the jury pool to be disqualified from the
triple-murder trial of Donald Couture.
   When the court clerk called the roll Wednesday, each potential
juror answered ``Here,'' except Dobbins. After Dobbins yelled,
``Guilty!'' instead, the stunned judge ordered sheriff's deputies
to handcuff and remove him, then disqualified the rest of the
prospective jurors and apologized to the defendant.
   Couture is charged with the murder of three guards during a $2
million robbery of Purolator Security Inc. in 1979.
   Couture and co-defendant Lawrence Pelletier of Waterbury were
convicted on the charges in a 1982 trial, but the convictions were
overturned because a judge found that a prosecutor's had acted
improperly.
</TEXT>
