<FIRST>r a PM-Military-Lesbians 1stLd-Writethru a0426 04-20 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Military-Lesbians, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civilian Adviser Defends Military Handling of Homosexuality</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to CORRECT and say statement made by chairman of group,
rather than by group. Picks up 2nd graf pvs, Being charged.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces fairly treat allegations
of homosexuality against female members, says the chairman of a
civilian advisory group, despite testimony that claims of
lesbianism are being used to harass women.
   ``Being charged with anything is not harassment,'' Connie Lee,
head of the Defense Advisory Committee on Women in the Services,
said Wednesday after a day of testimony from present and former
servicewomen, some who said they were homosexual.
   ``If someone is charged with this, they have the opportunity, as
any person does in any court of law when they are accused of
something, of saying, I am or I am not,'' Lee said at the spring
meeting of the committee.
   Lee would not predict what, if anything, the committee would
recommend to the defense secretary as a result of the hearing,
although she said the committee opposes harassment in any form. The
committee, composed of 33 appointed civilians, advises the
secretary on the recruitment and retention of servicewomen.
   Four witnesses, two of whom were discharged from the service for
admitting their lesbianism and two of whom are fighting allegations
of homosexuality, asked the committee Wednesday to tackle the use
of such allegations for sexual harassment.
   ``It is time to call attention to institutionalized sexual
harassment in the form of witchhunts that are out of control,''
said Mary Elizabeth Harrison, a first class personnelman in the
Navy. ``An underlying, dangerously tolerant attitude exists
throughout the military structure which places women at a
significant disadvantage in the armed forces in all aspects, from
advancement to morale to retention.''
   Harrison had been assigned to the USS Grapple, a salvage ship
based in Little Creek, Va., when a male crewman last year accused
her and another woman sailor of being homosexual. Harrison said she
wanted to file a grievance but ``I was told that the commanding
officer did not want an investigation on his ship because of how it
might appear,'' so she declined to file.
   Months later, Harrison said, she was summoned before the Naval
Investigative Service and told she and several other woman sailors
were under investigation for alleged homosexuality.
   ``We were told various lies _ that we would be protected if we
turned the others in, that the others had already confessed, that
they had conclusive evidence of our guilt,'' she said.
   In the five months since, Harrison said she has been reassigned
to shore duty, received bad evaluations, had her car vandalized in
the barracks parking lot and ``become the gossip of the
waterfront.''
   ``I am beginning to understand how women simply become exhausted
fighting a no-win battle and admit anything in order to leave the
abuse and humiliation of the military behind,'' she added.
   Darlene Chamberlin, a former airman first class in the U.S. Air
Force who was discharged for admitting her homosexuality to an
investigations panel, said some servicewomen ``are accused of
lesbianism because they refuse advances from male personnel, or are
strong and athletic, or for choosing to socialize with other
females.''
   According to the Defense Department, from 1985 to 1987, women
were three times as likely as men to be discharged for
homosexuality. Five of every 10,000 men and 16 of every 10,000
women on active duty were discharged annually for suspected
homosexuality, DOD found.
   Some witnesses touched on the situation at the Marine boot camp
in Parris Island, S.C., where three women were jailed and more than
a dozen were forced out of the service last year after being
charged with homosexuality.
</TEXT>
