<FIRST>r i PM-HospitalKillings     04-20 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital Killings,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurse's Aide Now Says She Only Killed 22 Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nurse's aide who had told police she
killed at least 39 elderly hospital patients now says she killed
22, a police investigator said today.
   Max Edelbacher told The Associated Press that Waltraud Wagner, a
30-year-old nurse's aide at Vienna's Lainz hospital, last week
withdrew her earlier confession of 39 killings.
   State prosecutors refused then to give details. But Edelbacher
said Ms. Wagner now had identified by name 11 people she killed.
She said she killed 11 more whose names she could not provide, he
said.
   Police showed Ms. Wagner photographs of possible victims today
to try to jog her memory, Edelbacher said.
   Ms. Wagner was arrested April 7 along with two other nurse's
aides, Irene Leidolf, 27, and Maria Gruber, 26. A fourth aide,
Stefanie Mayer, 49, was detained two days later.
   Police said then that the four women had admitted to killing at
least 49 patients at Lainz since 1982. They said they doubted the
motive was mercy killing because the victims had water forced into
their lungs or died from lethal doses of medicine.
   In questioning today, Ms. Leidolf stuck to her confession of
killing three patients, Edelbacher said.
   Edelbacher said Ms. Gruber and Ms. Mayer would be interrogated
Friday, along with Dr. Franz Pesendorfer, the suspended head of the
hospital department where the nurse's aides worked.
   None of the women has been charged, but all are in custody.
   The killings have prompted a nationwide debate about the
standard of health care, particularly in Vienna's overtaxed
hospitals.
   Alois Stacher, the doctor in charge of the capital's health
department, today announced eight ``emergency measures'' to try to
relieve the overworked doctors, nurses and other personnel at
Vienna's hospitals.
   They included an undefined reorganization of hospital
management, measures to move convalescing patients out of needed
hospital beds, and new teamwork among doctors, nurses and aides in
hospital wards.
   Stacher also mandated a new one-year ``trial period'' for
doctors of Pesendorfer's rank who head departments, and new
regulations laying down exact working hours for them.
   Several such senior doctors maintain private practices outside
the hospitals where they work.
   Pesendorfer has been severely criticized in Austrian media for
failing to tell police investigating rumors of mass killings at his
department a year ago the name of the doctor who had heard the
speculation.
   There also has been widespread criticism of the violation of
regulations barring aides from administering injections to patients.
   Under Austrian law, doctors are only allowed to hand that task
to qualified nurses if absolutely necessary.
</TEXT>
