<FIRST>r a PM-UnionVote     04-20 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Union Vote,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vermont Newspaper Votes To Unionize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees at The Burlington Free Press,
Vermont's largest daily newspaper, have voted overwhelmingly to
unionize, results tallied today show.
   The vote was 77-47 to join the Graphic Communications
International Union.
   The election pitted the 150,000-member union against the $3.3
billion Gannett Co., which historically has fought hard against
unions at its 88 newspapers. It was the first time in five years
that Gannett has lost a union election.
   The Free Press will be the only unionized newspaper in the state.
   Publisher Donna Donovan said, ``Burlington Free Press employees
have chosen to be represented by a union and we fully respect their
choice.''
   ``We are elated,'' said copy editor Paul Beique, a union
supporter. ``Now we can begin preparing to negotiate a contract.''
   Workers at the Free Press had complained of low wages, unpaid
overtime, and recent reductions in health benefits. They alleged
Gannett has taken profits from the Free Press and other newspapers
to support other enterprises, notably USA Today, its nationally
circulated newspaper.
   Donovan countered that salaries have improved during her three
years at the paper, that she has added new staff to the newsroom
recently, and that workers would lose more than they would gain by
joining a union.
   About 140 employees were eligible to vote in the election.
Fourteen votes were challenged, either by the company, the union or
the National Labor Relations Board and are not contained in the
124-vote total.
   The next step for the union is to hold elections in the various
departments to name representatives to the union's negotiating
committee.
   Unions represent about 20 percent of the 37,000 Gannett Co.
workers.
   The Free Press has a daily circulation of 55,000 and a Sunday
circulation of 60,000. Gannett bought the 162-year-old paper in
1971.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
