<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IvoryBan     04-20 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ivory Ban,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sotheby's Curbs Ivory Sales After Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sotheby's auction house says it hopes its
decision to stop selling elephant tusks or ivory jewelry, furniture
or artworks less than 50 years old will help stop the slaughter of
elephants.
   The auction house announced the decision Wednesday, saying the
new policy would apply to Sotheby's 17 auction centers and 44
offices worldwide.
   ``This is very much of a corporate statement that we support the
groups that are trying to stop this slaughter and this atrocity,''
said Michael Ainslie, Sotheby's president and chief executive
officer.
   The move followed a large advertisement placed in The New York
Times by Friends of Animals, of Norwalk, Conn., decrying the
scheduled auction Friday of two African elephant tusks for an
estimated $12,000 to $16,000.
   The ad, which ran Wednesday, said nearly 1 million elephants, or
three-fourths of Africa's wild elephant population, have been wiped
out since 1979.
   The tusks in question were legally acquired before 1976, said
Ainslie.
   ``Nonetheless, we are very much aware that, laws
notwithstanding, the visibility of such a sale does have the
potential to induce more destruction,'' said Ainslie. ``The seller
has decided on our strong recommendation to remove them from the
sale.''
   Later Wednesday, Sotheby's bought the tusks from the
unidentified seller for an undisclosed sum. They will be donated
``to an appropriate institution or museum,'' said a spokeswoman,
Diana Levitt.
   ``We're thrilled,'' said Priscilla Feral, president of Friends
of Animals. ``Now, we're going to ask them to firm up the decision
by refusing to deal in any ivory regardless of the age.''
   Ainslie said Sotheby's consulted with the African Wildlife
Foundation before making its decision, which will affect a very
small portion of its profits.
   Ms. Feral said her group also would ask the competing Christie's
auction house to follow Sotheby's example.
   Christie's spokeswoman Roberta Meneker said, ``Generally
speaking, we do not intend to sell ivory. But we can't make a
categorical statement.''
   She said a distinction should be drawn between modern ivory
pieces and ``an 18th-century tusk that comes from England or
France.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
