<FIRST>u i PM-Jordan-Riots 1stLd-Writethru   04-20 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jordan-Riots, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0485,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Dead In Jordan Riots, Maan Under Curfew</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with one dead today, new riots.
Pickup 7th graf, ``The price...'' Edits thereafter to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mourners rioted today during the funeral of
a boy slain during an earlier demonstration against price
increases, and soldiers killed at least one person, sources said.
   Unrest was reported in villages near Kerak and south of the Dead
Sea, the latest violence in a wave of rioting that has left at
least seven people dead.
   A local reporter said he saw soldiers fatally shoot at least one
person and wound two people in Mazar, eight miles south of Kerak,
when demostrations occurred during a funeral today for a youth
slain on Wednesday.
   Family members identified the person killed today as Yacoub
Katawneh, a cousin of the slain youth, 13-year-old Ibrahim Katawneh.
   The reporter said a local official in Mazar on Wednesday shot
the youth and an air force major as a demonstration passed the
official's house. But authorities in Amman suggested the shooting
might have been a personal matter unrelated to the current unrest.
   The two deaths near Kerak, 50 miles south of Amman, were in
addition to five deaths reported Wednesday in Ma`an, 120 miles
south of Amman.
   Ma`an, where the disturbances first broke out Tuesday, remained
under curfew and was blockaded by the army, residents said.
   Other riots were reported in villages north of Kerak and at Ghor
Es-Safi south of the Dead Sea. There were no confirmed reports of
casualties.
   The government deployed troops on roads around population
centers throughout southern Jordan.
   Information Minister Hani Khasawneh told The Associated Press
today the riots were ``not a serious security threat,'' and said
the government had acted ``in full realization of the patriotism of
our people.''
   He said security agencies ``have been inquiring into these
incidents, especially the looting and setting fire to government
buildings, and the false phone contacts ... with foreign press
agencies.''
   The disturbances that broke out Tuesday in Ma`an apparently were
triggered by government-imposed increases in the prices of
gasoline, cigarettes and other items. The increases were announced
Sunday as part of an agreement with the International Monetary Fund.
   The price increases came on the heels of an economic slide that
has sent per capita income tumbling to about $1,200 a year from
nearly $2,000 in the mid-1980s.
   In Washington, King Hussein told reporters Wednesday, ``I
believe everything is under control.''
   The official Jordan News Agency reported today that Crown Prince
Hassan, the king's brother, responded to the incidents by calling
for a conference to study the country's development needs.
   Yousef Azem, who represented maan in Jordan's now-suspended
Parliament, said leaders of the Maan region met in Amman on
Wednesday. He said they decided to seek calm in the region and to
prepare a list of demands to give the government.
   Hussein said the disturbances resulted from ``measures that had
to be taken as a result of the defaulting of several Arab states in
helping us'' _ a reference to the failure of Arab oil states to
meet a $1 billion yearly commitment to the kingdom agreed upon in
1978. We had to take some measures and obviously people feel them.''
   The price increases announced Sunday raised gasoline prices by
25 percent to $1.65 a gallon, and raised the cost of cigarettes,
telephone calls, heating oil and cooking gas by 10 percent to 50
percent.
   Prices of other commodities also have risen sharply the past
year because of a devaluation of the Jordanian dinar on world
markets.
   But local incomes have remained stable, often at about $175 to
$275 monthly. An economic slowdown has caused unemployment to rise
to as high as 20 percent by some estimates.
   Rioters in Ma`an, Kerak and other cities have stoned police,
burned official cars and attacked banks, government offices and
shops with stones and fire.
</TEXT>
