<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     04-20 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Clerics Challenge Israeli Ban of Worshipers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem clerics today urged Palestinians to defy
an Israeli order barring some worshipers from Jerusalem's Al Aqsa
mosque, one of Islam's holiest sites. Ten Palestinians were
reported wounded in clashes in the Gaza Strip.
   Sheikh Mohammed Al Jamal, a leading preacher at Al Aqsa, called
on Moslems throughout the occupied territories to attend noon
prayers at the mosque Friday to challenge the ban.
   The order was enacted after Palestinians stoned police in the
mosque compound following prayers on April 7, the first Friday of
the Moslem holy month of Ramadan.
   The mosque compound, known as Haram Al Sharif or Noble Enclosure
in Arabic, is the third-holiest site of Islam after Mecca and
Medina in Saudi Arabia.
   ``We call on Moslems to perform Friday prayers at Al Aqsa
mosque,'' Al Jamal told reporters at a news conference.
   ``If the Israeli authorities prevent them from entering the
mosque, they are to pray in the Old City of Jerusalem. If they are
barred from entering the city, they are to pray on the roads
leading to Jerusalem,'' he said.
   Hassan Tahboub, a former administrator of Al Aqsa, said the
Israeli order, which permits police to bar Palestinians at random
from the mosque, amounted to punishing all Moslem worshipers.
   ``This is not acceptable at all. The authorities must rescind
their decision,'' Tahboub said.
   Al Jamal challenged Israeli claims that during the April 7 riot
Palestinian protesters aimed rocks at Jews praying at the adjacent
Western Wall, Judaism's holiest site.
   ``Moslems did not throw rocks intentionally at the Western Wall.
They were throwing stones at police in response to their firing
tear gas and rubber bullets at worshipers,'' and some stones fell
on the nearby Jewish shrine, Al Jamal said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, meanwhile, Israeli troops shot and
wounded six Palestinians during clashes in the village of Beit
Hanoun, the Nuseirat, Shati and Khan Yunis refugee camps, and the
town of Rafah, Arab doctors said.
   They said the wounded included a 10-year-old boy and three
14-year-old boys. Doctors also said the wounded included a
40-year-old Beit Hanoun woman was treated after soldiers beat her
and broke her left arm.
   An army official confirmed one of the casualties reported by
Arab doctors. He also said two people were injured in the village
of Bani Suheila and two more were injured in Rafah.
   Since the December 1987 start of the Palestinian uprising, 439
Palestinians and eighteen Israelis have been killed.
   In the occupied West Bank, doctors from Hebron's Alia Hospital
said a 14-year-old boy from the nearby village of Yatta was
hospitalized late Wednesday with third-degree burns after an
explosive device went off in his hands.
   At least two Palestinians have been killed and a dozen wounded
by unidentified exploding objects in the West Bank. The army has
said the devices may be unexploded flares dropped by army aircraft
during training flights.
</TEXT>
