<FIRST>r a PM-NursingHomeDeaths     04-20 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Home Deaths,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Nurse's Aide to Stand Trial In Deaths of Elderly Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALKER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nurse's aide was ordered to stand
trial on charges of killing five nursing home patients after her
one-time lover and co-worker testified that she claimed the
suffocations helped relieve stress.
   Gwendolyn Graham, 25, was bound over for trial on five counts of
murder and one count of conspiracy to commit murder after a
District Court hearing Wednesday.
   ``She was always happy when one of them died,'' said her former
lesbian lover, Catherine Wood, who was also charged in the
killings. Wood testified that Graham tried or plotted to kill at
least five other patients, but was foiled when some of the elderly
men and women fought back.
   The two counts of murder pending against Wood will be dropped in
exchange for her testimony, according to a plea bargain announced
earlier. She has agreed to plead guilty to one count of
second-degree murder and one count of conspiracy to commit murder.
   Wood lived with Graham in the first half of 1987, when Wood
testified that they attempted to kill enough patients to spell the
word ``murder'' with the victims' initials.
   ``I asked her why and she told me it relieved her tension,''
said Wood, who wept as she testified.
   Defense attorney James Piazza contended there was no proof that
any of the patients at Alpine Manor Nursing Home died of unnatural
causes, and said that Wood was trying to take revenge on Graham for
leaving Wood for another woman.
   However, District Judge Sherwin Venema ruled there was
sufficient evidence for Graham to stand trial. She could face life
in prison without parole if convicted.
   Wood, 27, said she was upset after witnessing the suffocation of
the first victim, 60-year-old Marguerite Chambers, in January 1987.
Graham promised her the killing would stop, she said.
   But when another female patient died after struggling with
Graham, Wood said Graham took that as a sign ``that it was supposed
to go on.'' Graham took a souvenir from each victim, including
earrings, anklets and handkerchiefs, Wood testified.
   Wood said she went along with the killings because ``I thought
Gwen was the first person to ever love me, and I didn't want her to
leave me.''
   Police began investigating the deaths after Wood's ex-husband
reported alleged confessions by his former wife. Both women remain
jailed without bond.
</TEXT>
