<FIRST>r a PM-HelicopterCrash     04-20 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helicopter Crash,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed When Ultralight Copter Crashes In Shopping Center Lot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ultralight helicopter crashed and
burned in a shopping center parking lot before dawn today, killing
both people aboard, a Fire Department spokesman said.
   There were no injuries on the ground, but parts of the aircraft
struck and caved in the roof over some businesses, Inspector Marty
Galindo said.
   The Federal Aviation Administratin was called to investigate the
crash in this city 75 miles east of San Francisco.
   Officials had not detemined the sex or identities of the victims
because their bodies were burned beyond recognition, Galindo added.
It also was unclear where the copter was traveling.
   ``Nobody knows where it came from,'' Galindo said. ``That small
an aircraft typically doesn't have a radio.''
   A power line was found severed at the scene.
   ``Whether or not the helicopter was in trouble before it hit the
line or hitting the line contributed to the accident remains to be
determined,'' Galindo said.
   Ultralight aircraft typically are powered by small engines that
allow them to fly only 100 feet or so above the ground. Pilots and
passengers normally are in an exposed cockpit.
</TEXT>
