<FIRST>r w PM-StateDepartment-Bias 1stLdWritethru a0444 04-20 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-State Department-Bias, 1st Ld Writethru, a0444,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Sends Notice on Discrimination Against Women</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to include confirmation from attorney, adds quotes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has sent cables to U.S.
embassies around the world and posted notifications acknowledging a
district court finding of discrimination against female Foreign
Service officers between 1976 and 1985, an attorney involved in the
case said today.
   The agency also has informed about 600 women working in the
Foreign Service that they may be entitled to court-ordered relief.
   The actions stem from a suit filed in 1976 by Alison Palmer, a
now-retired Foreign Service officer who claimed the department
discriminated against women in hiring and promotion, said Ms.
Palmer's attorney, Monica Wagner.
   However, Ms. Wagner said her client will not be a direct
beneficiary of the court order because she has retired from the
foreign service. Only those women who are part of the class-action
suit and are still working for the Foreign Service are affected.
   ``The benefit for her is in seeing the State Department take
action with respect to the sex discrimination found by the court,''
Ms. Wagner said.
   The State Department had won the Palmer lawsuit in a lower court
but was reversed three months ago by the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the District of Columbia. The State Department has informed the
court it is planning to appeal that decision.
   Ms. Palmer charged in her suit that the department discriminated
against women by hiring more men, giving men the better career
assignments and more career-advancing honors.
   The agency also has announced that it has postponed the Foreign
Service examination this year.
   The test has been challenged because men pass the general
background section at twice the rate of women.
</TEXT>
