<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Defense 1stLd-Writethru a0493 04-20 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Defense, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan May Develop Anti-Aircraft Missile On Its Own</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th pvs, ``The missile...'' with 1 graf to CLARIFY that
Japan plans to deploy Patriot to replace Nike-J. Pickup 8th, ``One Patriot...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan may develop its own surface-to-air missile in
a $7.5 billion project, a news report said today.
   It would be the first anti-aircraft missile Japan developed
using its own technology, the leading economic newspaper Nihon
Keizai Shimbun said.
   The report comes as Tokyo and Washington remain mired in
disagreement over a proposal to jointly develop a new fighter jet.
   An official in the Finance Ministry's Budget Bureau confirmed
$30 million were earmarked in the budget for fiscal year 1989 for
``study expenses'' for the missile but refused to elaborate.
   Japan's budget for the current fiscal year, which began April 1,
has not been approved by Parliament because of an opposition
boycott tied to a bribery scandal. Instead, the government is
operating on a 50-day provisional budget.
   The newspaper said the Defense Agency plans three years of
research into areas such as radar and infrared sensors and guidance
systems before beginning development of the new missile.
   The missile would replace the Patriot, which Japan produces
under license from the United States under a 1985 agreement. Japan
plans to deploy 26 Japanese-made Patriot systems over the next 10
years to replace its aging Nike-J missiles.
   One Patriot system is estimated to cost $521 million and is made
up of 20 Patriot missiles, a launcher, and radar and firing control
equipment. It is capable of attacking multiple airborne targets
within a range of 100 miles.
   The newspaper said the plan to use Japanese technology to
develop the new missile system might bring a negative reaction from
the United States, which has provided Japan with much of its main
defense technology.
   The United States may propose joint development of the new
missile system, as in the case of Japan's controversial
next-generation jet fighter, the FSX, it said. Last year, Japan and
the United States agreed that private companies from the two
countries will jointly develop and produce a new jet fighter for
Japan in a project worth more than $8 billion.
   The move was a compromise after Washington wanted Japan to buy
U.S.-built planes while Tokyo wanted to develop its own aircraft.
   But the two countries are currently reviewing the agreement
because of opposition from some U.S. congressmen who charge that
the project would be a ``giveaway'' of U.S. aviation technology.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
