<SECOND>AM-BRF--Subway Strike,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second 24-Hour Strike Idles London Subways</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of subway train drivers on Thursday
staged their second 24-hour strike this month to protest
cost-cutting measures, bringing the system to a near-standstill.
   Buses and roads were crowded during the morning rush-hour with 3
million subway commuters trying to find other ways to enter the
city during the worst of the two unofficial strikes on the
126-year-old London Underground.
   Only three of the 10 subway lines were operating, but services
were reduced to about one-third or half of normal, a transit
spokesman said.
   In the April 5 strike, three lines operated fully and others
offered partial services.
   Denis Tunnicliffe, managing director of the Underground, said
the striking drivers were ignoring union advice to keep working.
   Drivers on strike were demanding more money for working on
trains that eventually will be operated alone after the phasing out
of conductors who open and close doors.
   The subway employs 2,400 drivers.
