<SECOND>PM-Campus Protest,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Occupy College of Wooster Administration Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOOSTER, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at the College of Wooster occupied
the campus administration building today, locking out
administrators and staff to press for a stronger black studies
program and other changes.
   The takeover of Galpin Hall occurred about 6 a.m. as the
building was opened, college spokesman Jeff Hanna said. He said
about 20 black and white students appeared to be involved.
   ``I don't think it is any one group,'' Hanna said. ``It's just
students; student leaders from a number of groups are involved.''
   Students were at each of the four entrances to the building and
were denying access to administrators and staff, although some
faculty members had entered, Hanna said. The takeover continued
late this morning.
   The private, liberal arts college in northeast Ohio has an
enrollement of 1,800, and about 5 percent of the students are
black, Hanna said.
   College President Henry Copeland met with the students for about
45 minutes on the back steps of the building and intended to meet
with them again, Hanna said.
   The students have listed several demands, including a black
studies requirement; hiring of more black faculty and advisers; and
the selling off of stock in companies that do business in South
Africa.
   ``These are all issues the college has been addressing and will
continue to address,'' Hanna said. ``We've been having discussions
on these concerns for maybe three weeks.''
   In Detroit, about 100 students at Wayne State University are in
the second week of a protest also calling for more minority studies
and minority hiring. The students have occupied a building housing
registration and student loan offices since April 12.
</TEXT>
