<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Stalin-Daughter     04-20 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stalin-Daughter,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives Say Stalin's Daughter Wanted Her Own Son Exiled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Svetlana Alliluyeva, daughter of dictator Josef
Stalin, scandalized her relatives during her stay in the Soviet
Union and demanded her son be exiled to a remote Pacific island, an
article published Thursday said.
   Alliluyeva's son, Josef, was quoted in the newspaper Soviet
Culture as saying his mother wrote his superiors demanding he be
kicked out of the Communist Party, stripped of his academic degree
and ``the funniest of all _ she's demanding that after all that I
be sent to Sakhalin!''
   The newspaper's article, which contained revelations about a
leader's family life still rare in the Soviet press, was part of a
wave of public re-examination of all aspects of Josef Stalin's long
rule of terror.
   Alliluyeva defected from the Soviet Union in 1967 and returned
in 1984 at age 58, saying she wanted to be reunited with her
family. A year and a half later, she wrote a letter to Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev asking permission to leave, citing poor
relations with relatives.
   She has returned to her former home in Wisconsin.
   In an interview soon after her second departure, she said that
despite the special treatment she received in the Soviet Union, she
felt estranged from her son and his wife and other relatives whom
she later joined in Soviet Georgia, her father's birthplace.
   N.V. Stalina, Alliluyeva's niece, said she created ``most
disgusting scenes'' while on vacation with a cousin. ``For her, it
meant nothing to humiliate another person,'' she told Maj. A.
Kolesnik, who wrote the article based on newly opened archives and
personal interviews.
   In a letter to Kolesnik, Alliliuyeva's nephew, Y. Dzhugashvili,
furnished the quotes on Sakhalin, a former prison colony off
Eastern Siberia, from his conversations with Iosif Alliluyev, and
said Svetlana seemed unwilling at first to meet with her son.
   In the 1986 interview, Alliluyeva said that her son had changed
unrecognizably in the 17 years since she had seen him, and that she
thought he had been instructed to invite her back to the Soviet
Union, perhaps by the KGB.
   Alliluyeva brought her 13-year-old American-born daughter, Olga
Peters, with her when she came back to the Soviet Union in 1984.
   In both Moscow and the Georgian capital of Tbilisi, she was
given special privileges including the use of a car and a luxury
apartment.
   ``I'm sure she always felt a crown on her head, despite her
modest clothing, and often gave orders, and she repeatedly insulted
her daughter,'' Dzhugashvili told Soviet Culture.
   ``When she left Tbililsi, she announced that `she was tired of
living among savages,''' Dzhugashvili said.
   Alliluyeva's move to Moscow and back to the West were acclaimed
as propaganda coups, but she maintained that her reasons for the
moves were purely personal.
   When she returned to the United States, she vowed she would
never again return to the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
