<FIRST>r i AM-SatanicVerses     04-20 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rushdie Supporters Urge Boycott of Iran Book Fair</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 7 p.m. EDT _ Time Set by Source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of Salman Rushdie, the novelist under
an Iranian death sentence, voiced dismay Thursday at plans by
British and other Western publishers to exhibit at next month's
Tehran Book Fair.
   ``We are concerned that participation by publishers in this
event will be interpreted by the Iranian government and others as
an acceptance of the death threat,'' said a statement by the
International Committee for the Defense of Salman Rusdhie and His
Publishers.
   Rushdie has been in hiding for two months since Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini said the Bombay-born British writer's novel,
``The Satanic Verses,'' blasphemed Islam and sentenced him to death.
   The committee said the May 7-19 book fair, specializing in
scientific, technical and medical books, is being run by the
Iranian Ministry of Islamic Culture.
   It said the Iranians had withdrawn an invitation to Viking
Penguin, Rushdie's publishers, but said other publishers from
around the world, including Britain, would participate.
   The statement urged them to make clear to Iran their
condemnation of the death threat, and to show support for
international efforts to have it withdrawn.
   The Rushdie committee was set up to organize protests by
free-speech groups, and collected signatures from more than 1,000
writers worldwide on a petition that was published free of charge
in newspapers in more than 20 countries March 2.
   The Oxford University Press is one of the publishers exhibiting
at the fair. Simon Wratten, sales director for the academic
division, said: ``We deliberated about it quite deeply but felt
that it certainly wasn't in our interests, or Iran's as a whole,''
to stay away.
   Nor, he said, would an exhibition of books on scientific
subjects ``be seen in any way as supporting the ayatollah's
decision,'' he said.
   In an interview, Wratten said the books already had been shipped
to Tehran, but the company had decided against sending
representatives, fearing they might face danger and be put in ``in
a very difficult position, whereby they would have to make some
sort of statement.''
   He said the decision was ``in line with other publishers,''
adding that American publishers also were planning to exhibit.
   After the death sentence was announced, The Bookseller, a trade
journal, reported that publishers were going ahead with exhibits
but would not send representatives, fearing for their safety.
   It quoted John Hudson, international sales manager for
scientific publisher Butterworth, as saying: ``As publishers, our
responsibilities are to individuals who want to read books, not to
governments. To send books to book fairs does not imply approval
for a regime, otherwise there would be many bookfairs we did not
participate in.''
   Hudson was not available for comment Thursday, but his office
said it was going ahead with its exhibit.
</TEXT>
