<FIRST>u a PM-Battleship-Families 2ndLd-Writethru a050ki</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Battleship-Families, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0504,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>For USS Iowa Crewmen's Relatives, Agony Is In The Waiting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 3rd graf pvs to UPDATE memorial service
planned, other comment from commander. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Journalists
were...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the relatives of the USS Iowa's crew,
agony was not knowing their loved ones' fates, though some gained
strength from each other at the ship's home base, a chaplain said.
   About 200 relatives spent Wednesday night in a Norfolk Naval
Station gym, knowing that 47 of the 1,600 crewmen died when a blast
Wednesday ripped through one of the Norfolk-based battleship's
three-gun turrets.
   ``There is a lot of support within the group. I saw
relationships develop right before my eyes, as women would put
their arms around those who were having troubles,'' Navy Chaplain
Barry Brimhall said Wednesday night.
   Rear Adm. Jimmy Pappas, commander of the Norfolk Naval base,
said early this afternoon that a memorial service for the sailors
killed on the USS Iowa will be held at the base Monday.
   The victims included one officer and 46 enlisted men, he said,
and 12 of the dead are from the Hampton Roads area in Virginia.
   ``Its the greatest tragedy any of us can suffer,'' Pappas said.
   The commander spent most of the night in the base gym waiting
for identification of victims with family members.
   ``Its the most difficult thing you have to do,'' to tell someone
who has lost a relative, he said. Those who found out a relative
survived the tragedy were ``overjoyed with tears'' he said.
   Journalists were kept away from the gym at the families' request.
   Most of the relatives left the gym by daybreak, having heard
about the fate of their own loved ones, said Master Chief Petty
Officer Billy Kinder, a spokesman for the base. The Navy continued
to notify other relatives across the country.
   By Navy policy, relatives are notified in person when a loved
one dies.
   In Temple, Texas, Lorene Barron said all she could do was pray
for her son, Monte Barron, and hope she would hear from the Navy by
telephone.
   ``They told me if he was among the deceased, they would
personally visit us,'' Mrs. Barron said. ``But I believe
everything's going to be OK. And I'm praying for all the mothers
who are waiting just like I am.''
   In Columbus, Ga., the father of Bruce Morgan Jr., said that
waiting to learn his son's fate ``is hell.''
   Bruce Morgan Sr. said his 19-year-old son had told the family he
was to be assigned to a gun crew on the Iowa in March.
   ``There are those who are really struggling, and those who are
really stoic,'' Brimhall said. ``Right now, for some of these
families, they would rather have bad news than no news at all.''
   As the families waited in the gymnasium, area residents swamped
Navy Family Services with offers of help. The area is home to the
world's largest naval facility and many military retirees, and its
economy depends heavily on the military.
   ``It's been fantastic how everyone has pulled together _ both
civilian and military,'' said Cathy Stokoe, deputy director of
family services on the base.
   The Navy has a contingency plan for such disasters and it starts
with taking care of the families, said Kinder.
   ``The first thing we did was establish a place for them to
gather. We provide a place for them to be. The chaplains, social
workers, Red Cross and others are there to help them in anyway
possible,'' he said.
   Ms. Stokoe said merchants brought groceries to the families.
   ``Local stores are providing baby food and diapers at the gym,
and lots and lots of food,'' she said. ``The Red Cross has pulled
out all the stops. There are cots and blankets for those family
members who are staying the night.''
   Kinder said that the families are updated frequently on news
from the ship.
   Officials said the surviving members of the crew had no serious
injuries.
   Brimhall and his colleagues offer what he calls a ``ministry of
presence'' for the families. He said the primary purpose is to let
the families know they have someone to talk to and to reassure them.
   But, Brimhall said, he still must be honest with them.
   ``Some are going to lose a loved one,'' he said.
</TEXT>
