<HEAD>Oil Spill Threatens Coast of Greek Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Efforts were under way to keep a giant oil
slick, apparently caused by a passing ship, from reaching the
shores of an island in southern Greece, the Ministry of Merchant
Marine said Thursday.
   Pools of oil and tar about 200 yards wide were spread along
seven to eight miles off Kithira island, said spokesman Kostas
Stamatis.
   The oil slick was discovered Tuesday, and officials hired three
ships to contain and dissolve the oil with chemicals, Stamatis
said. In addition, dozens of volunteers in small boats were helping
out.
   Sea currents were bringing some of the oil to the eastern part
of Kithira, he added.
   The coast guard, supported by the local authorities and
volunteers, was rushing to clean up the polluted area before it
spread further, he said.
   ``We think that a passing ship might be responsible for the
spill, but the ministry is still investigating the cause,'' said
Stamatis.
