<FIRST>u a PM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0462 04-20 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0462,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Soviet Ship Comes To The Rescue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with ship leaving port, Lujan
leaving Anchorage en route to spill site, other detail. Picks up 11th graf
pvs, `The Vaidogubsky...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEWARD, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet oil-skimmer joined the battle
today to clean crude-blackened Alaska waters just six months after
a similar superpower cooperative effort helped free two whales
trapped in ice.
   Soviet Capt. Serge Rekin piloted the ultramodern oil-skimmer
Vaidogubsky toward the mouth of Resurrection Bay on the Gulf of
Alaska to help in the cleanup of the gooey sludge left by the wreck
of the Exxon Valdez. Last October, the icebreaker Vladimir Arseniev
smashed through ice near Barrow, helping to free California gray
whales.
   ``We really appreciated your being here, captain,'' Exxon
spokesman Don Cornett told Rekin through an interpreter on
Wednesday. ``This is the second time people from your country have
come to the aid of the people of Alaska, and we thank you.''
   Rekin said he had little information about the task he faced but
that he wanted to begin work as quickly as possible. The 425-foot
Soviet skimmer is far bigger than any of the 20 or so skimmers that
Exxon has used so far.
   As immigration and customs officials worked Wednesday to approve
the vessel, children on the dock happily swapped candy with Soviet
crew members. Jackie Phillips and a few of her friends stretched on
tiptoes to hand cookies to the Soviets. ``It's just a friendly
gesture,'' she said.
   Officials are hoping the Vaidogubsky can vacuum up much of the
10.1 million gallons of crude oil dumped into Prince William Sound
on March 24, when the Exxon Valdez slammed aground on Bligh Reef
outside Valdez.
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan arrived in Anchorage on
Wednesday, and left this morning for the spill site. From an
airplane, he planned to review oil-sodden beaches, blackened rocks
and dying birds and animals in what once was one of the nation's
most untarnished wild areas.
   The Vaidogubsky, because it is designed to work on the high
seas, will be working initially on the gulf rather than the more
sheltered waters of the sound.
   Ribbons of oil have traveled 300 miles along Alaska's coast,
including into spectacularly scenic Resurrection Bay, where oil has
washed up on a beach at Seward.
   Now the oil in the water is thickening and becoming more
difficult to work with. Two Coast Guard skimmers were knocked out
of action when the sludge fouled up their pumps.
   ``We don't know how it's going to work in this oil, the kind of
oil we've been skimming,'' said Coast Guard Capt. Rene Roussel.
This will be first time the ship actually has worked on an oil
spill, said Jim Kross, an environmental consultant hired to arrange
for the ship's services.
   The Vaidogubsky will ply Alaska's waters for at least 30 days.
Exxon will pay for its services, estimated at $15,000 a day, plus
expenses, said James Kross, whose company works for VECO, Exxon's
contractor.
   ``Fifteen thousand a day _ that's not much if it's effective,''
said Cornett.
   The 3-year-old Soviet vessel is a dredge, firefighting platform
and oil skimmer, Kross said. ``It makes its money from dredging.
That's its primary function,'' he said. ``It's a commercial boat.''
   The ship was built in Finland and is stationed at Sahaklin
Island. Its specifications indicate it can skim 200,000 gallons of
crude from the high seas each hour. It has a 2 million-gallon
capacity, and will be accompanied by a barge to take off the oil
when its tanks fills.
   To skim the oil, the vessel swings out a long pole on each side.
An oil-gathering boom is attached to the poles and corrals oil as
the vessel moves through the water, Kross said. Floating suction
pumps are lowered into the captured oil and it is sucked into the
vessel's tanks.
   Jim Simpson, assistant to Coast Guard Commandant Paul Yost, said
Congress has been reluctant to pay for such a ship that might be
used only once every 20 years.
   ``I would suspect that after this incident, the answer will be
different,'' he said.
   Seward is named for former Secretary of State William Seward,
the man who bought yet-unexplored Alaska from Russia for $7.2
million in 1867. Doubters dubbed it ``Seward's Folly.''
</TEXT>
