<FIRST>r w AM-SocialSecurity-Hardy     04-20 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Security-Hardy,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>47 House Members Ask Bush to Keep Commissioner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-seven House members have asked President
Bush to reappoint Dorcas Hardy as Social Security commissioner ``to
maintain a sense of stability in this critical program.''
   Hardy has not been told whether she will be retained by Bush,
but sources in the administration and on Capitol Hill said last
week that the president is seriously considering replacing her.
   A letter supporting Hardy was circulated among House members by
Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y., and sent to Bush last week. It was
signed by 45 Republicans and two Democrats, including Rep. Andy
Jacobs, D-Ind., chairman of the House Ways and Means Social
Security subcommittee, said Hank Price, a spokesman for Boehlert.
   The lawmakers praised Hardy's initiatives in using toll-free 800
numbers to get information to recipients and in distributing
earnings and benefit estimate statements to participants.
   The legislators that ``there are other service improvements and
initiatives in the works that we don't want to see slowed or
halted, as would inevitably be the case with a change at the Social
Security's helm.''
   ``In view of the need to maintain a sense of stability in this
critical program, as well as the opportunity to continue moving
boldly into the future, we ask that she be given the opportunity to
continue her fine work,'' the letter concluded.
   Hardy had no comment on the letter, said Social Security
spokesman Phil Gambino.
   Hardy, who was named to head the Social Security Administration
in 1986 by then-President Reagan, has been criticized recently by
members of Congress who say people calling the toll-free numbers
often get only busy signals. The critics also say the plan has
required transferring staff from field offices to handle such
calls, leaving offices shorthanded.
   A House Governmental Operations subcommittee wants to look at
Hardy's travel records to see whether she combined business trips
with vacations. Last December, House Democrats charged she had
failed to implement a law requiring the administration to help
homeless people receive benefit checks.
   Bush is considering replacing Hardy with Gwendolyn King, a
former legislative aide to Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., who later headed
the Washington office of Dick Thornburgh when Thornburgh, now the
attorney general, was governor of Pennsylvania, according to
administration and Capitol Hill sources who spoke on the condition
of anonymity.
   King has declined to discuss the Social Security post, but last
week said, ``I will be pleased to serve wherever the president
needs me.''
</TEXT>
