<FIRST>r i AM-Ambassador-Body     04-20 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ambassador-Body,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Body of Spanish Envoy Returned to Spain for Burial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez led
officials in a solemn ceremony Thursday as the body of Ambassador
Pedro Manuel Aristegui was returned to Spain from the Middle East.
   Aristegui, 61, was killed Sunday when a mortar round, believed
to have been fired by a Syrian gunner, struck his villa in the
Christian suburb of Hadath during weekend artillery barrages in
Beirut.
   A Spanish air force jet bearing the envoy's body from Larnaca,
Cyprus, landed at Madrid's Barajas airport.
   Gonzalez, Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez and other
officials and stood by at the airport as soldiers rendered military
honors.
   Airmen bore the casket draped with a red and gold Spanish flag
to a nearby hearse. The body will lie in state at the Foreign
Ministry until Friday.
   Ministry officials accompanied the envoy's children, 3-year-old
Diego and 1-year-old Alejandra, who returned from Beirut on the
same plane.
   Burial will be in the northern Basque town of Irun, Aristegui's
birthplace.
   Killed with Aristegui was his father-in-law, Tewfic Youssef
Awwad, a noted Lebanese poet; Awwad's other daughter, Samia; and a
Lebanese bodyguard.
   The ambassador's wife was seriously wounded. Diego suffered
facial cuts and Alejandra was unhurt.
   Aristegui had served as ambassador to Nicaragua from 1977-80.
Before that, he held diplomatic posts in West Germany, the United
States and Argentina.
   Spanish officials have said they have no intention of closing
the nation's embassy in Beirut because of the incident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
