<FIRST>r i AM-India-Missile     04-20 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Missile,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Launch of India's First Intermediate-Range Missile Postponed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIPUR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India failed to launch its first
intermediate-range ballistic missile Thursday after the ignition
system of the 7{-ton rocket developed a last-minute technical
hitch, military sources said.
   The Agni missile, with a range of 1,550 miles, was scheduled to
be launched from a remote seaside site in the eastern state of
Orissa, where villagers were angered because they had to be
evacuated from their homes.
   ``We had to postpone the launch at the last stage,'' said a
senior military official at the Chandipur launch site, 745 miles
southeast of New Delhi. ``The countdown had started but the
computer reading showed a snag in the ignition system. So we had to
postpone the launching.''
   Another military official said the postponement ``came as a
shock.''
   ``We were depending on the scientists but at the last minute we
were told that the launching would have been disastrous,'' he said.
   Both officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   They said more than 200 scientists would work on the ignition
system to prepare for a launch Friday.
   ``The Agni is a demon,'' said Sarala Das, who said she would
blow a conch shell during the launch. ``We do not want a demon to
be anywhere near us.''
   Hindus believe the sound of a conch shell can drive out evil
spirits.
   Villagers residing within a half-mile radius of the launch site
said they were forcibly evacuated before the scheduled launch.
   ``Police came to our house at dawn and told us to get out,''
said Sideshwar Jana, a 40-year-old farmer. He said he did not want
to leave his home but was forced out after police threatened to
arrest him and his relatives.
   About 400 villagers, leading their goats and carrying their
chickens, walked to a relief center they had set up, ignoring a
government camp that offered free food and movies.
   Late Thursday evening, dozens of policemen visited the area to
ensure it was evacuated.
   Arun Dey, a former legislator spearheading protests of the
launch, said he feared the villagers would react violently if they
weren't allowed to return home at night.
   ``For a villager not to be in his home is like a turtle out of
water,'' Dey said. ``A fish out of water is dead but a turtle out
of water is confused and lost.''
   A successful launch of the missile, named ``Agni'' or ``Fire,''
will rank India along with the United States, the Soviet Union,
Britain, France and China in ballistic missile capabilities. It
also will enhance the power of India's 1.36 million army and its
geo-political influence in the region, military experts say.
   Since April 1987, India has successfully tested three types of
surface-to-air and surface-to-surface missiles, with ranges varying
from 5{ miles to 155 miles.
   Military test-firing is nothing new in Chandipur, where the
colonial British set up an arms and ammunition test range 95 years
ago. The area was chosen because of a rare geographical phenomenon:
during low tide water recedes by two miles, which helps to retrieve
the fired shells.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890420-0107 </DOCNO>
