<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Jordan 2ndLd-Writethru a0553 04-20 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Jordan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0553,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hussein Meets with Baker; Pledges Support for US Efforts</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top six grafs new with Hussein comments after meeting. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs, I think.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan's King Hussein offered qualified
support today for an Israeli proposal for Palestinian elections in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip as a first step toward ending the
Arab-Israeli impasse.
   After two hours of talks with Secretary of State James A. Baker,
Hussein told reporters at the State Department the idea of an
election ``might be worth looking at'' in the context of a
comprehensive peace process.
   He added that elections cannot be an end in themselves.
   Hussein's carefully chosen words appeared to be his most
positive statement about the Israeli proposal since it was outlined
here two weeks ago during a visit by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Shamir proposed that Palestinians elect ``interlocutors'' to
represent them in negotiations with Israel for limited
self-government.
   Hussein said he was optimistic about the prospects for peace, a
sentiment he shared at a White House dinner Wednesday night with
Baker, President Bush and National Security adviser Brent Scowcroft.
   ``I think there is a better chance for peace,'' Hussein told
reporters after a sumptuous dinner of salmon, duckling and other
delicacies.
   Moments earlier, Bush said in a toast to his guest: ``We can
sense an urgency to the quest for peace now. Our task is to use
that urgency to seize the moment.''
   In his toast, Hussein pleased his hosts by pledging to cooperate
closely with the United States to achieve a ``just, durable and
comprehensive peace settlement.''
   ``We will support you in all your endeavors to achieve a
comprehensive just and lasting peace,'' he told Bush.
   Because of Jordan's proximity to the West Bank, the
administration regards Hussein's support for any peace process as
essential for its success.
   Administration officials seemed pleased with Hussein's backing.
He had seemed content to play a more peripheral role in Middle East
diplomacy last summer when he severed Jordan's ties with West Bank
Palestinians.
   Baker said that the ``beginning of a process'' is under way as a
result of the talks with Hussein and earlier visits here by both
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzak Shamir and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak.
   ``It is important to do what he can to advance that process,''
Baker said.
   Shamir's election proposal is the newest element in the process,
and Baker left the clear impression that the administration has
carefully examined the kinds of issues that such an arrangement
would entail.
   Left unanswered thus far, he said, are such questions as who
would supervise elections in the territories, who would be entitled
to vote and would voting rights be extended to Palestinians living
outside the two areas.
   Although Hussein did not give an outright endorsement to the
proposal for elections, Baker said he was pleased with the
responses of both Hussein and Mubarak to Shamir's proposal.
   Scowcroft, also present at the dinner, said, ``We have come a
long way.''
</TEXT>
