<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--AffectionateStudents     04-20 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Affectionate Students,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>High School Students Protest Physical Contact Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAVILION, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 high school students were
suspended after a sit-in to protest a rule that prohibits hugging
and kissing on school property, administrators said.
   The Pavillion Central School students will not be allowed to
return until they agree, during a visit to the school with their
parents, to obey the rule, said Principal Larry Graham.
   The suspended students were part of a group of 65 students who
left the school Wednesday morning to protest enforcement of a
3-year-old Student Council-approved code of discipline that forbids
``overt displays of affection beyond handholding.''
   Graham said the crackdown came in response to an increasing
number of students hugging and kissing in the halls. The behavior
had become an embarrassment to faculty and other students, he said.
   The protesters complained they would not be allowed to hug each
other after a sports victory or in times of grief. Graham said the
rule does not apply in those cases. Students violating the rule
receive detention.
</TEXT>
