<FIRST>r i AM-NATO     04-20 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Ministers Give Mild Backing to Modernization Plan; Cheney Satisfied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO defense ministers Thursday gave
only limited support to an American plan to upgrade nuclear arms in
Europe, again putting off tough decisions on the politically
charged issue.
   But Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said he was satisfied with the
endorsement by ministers attending a two-day nuclear strategy
session of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   He predicted the support, voiced in a carefully crafted
statement, would enable the Defense Department to win congressional
approval for more money to develop the new generation
surface-to-surface missile.
   ``I am reluctant to make hard and fast predictions about what
Congress will or won't require,'' he said on the flight back to
Washington.
   ``But I will take the language that we've got and do the best I
can to garner the necessary support,'' he said. ``And I'm
reasonably confident that that will work.''
   In advance of the meeting, U.S. officials had said privately
they wanted a stronger signal from allies to continue the
development program. But the lukewarm backing was virtually the
same as that given at last fall's nuclear strategy meeting in the
Netherlands.
   The statement said NATO's strategy will continue to require
``for the foreseeable future'' a mix of conventional and nuclear
arms.
   ``At this meeting, we again expressed our determination to
ensure that NATO possesses diversified, survivable and
operationally flexible nuclear forces across the entire spectrum,''
the ministers said.
   ``These forces must be kept up-to-date where necessary,'' they
said.
   George Younger, Britain's secretary of state for defense, said
the statement ``paves the way ... for decisions to be taken as they
become necessary in the future.''
   ``What it hasn't done is to step back in any way from the
general NATO strategy,'' he told reporters.
   President Bush and other NATO leaders will meet May 29-30 in
Brussels to consider, among other things, the Comprehensive
Concept, a blueprint to guide the allies' future strategy for arms
control and force planning.
   NATO officials were expected to spend the weeks leading up to
the summit trying to find language that will bridge the differences
over the modernization question.
   With warming East-West ties, the idea of upgrading the Lance has
become increasingly unpopular, especially in West Germany where
most of the weapons would be based.
   The Lance missile, which was introduced in 1972, will become
obsolete in 1995, military analysts say.
   It has a range of a little more than 60 miles. The upgraded
missile would have a range of about 250 miles.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl wants to delay the decision
on modernization until 1991 or 1992 _ after important elections in
his country.
   ``By 1991 or 1992, obviously, we would hope to have been able to
arrive at specific decisions with respect to what (new nuclear)
systems would be deployed,'' Cheney told a news conference at NATO
headquarters.
   ``We clearly are not there yet. It's not required yet. So for
that reason, I'm comfortable with what we have in this
communique,'' he said.
   Belgium and some other European nations would like the alliance
to enter into early negotiations with the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact on
reducing short-range nuclear weapons in Europe.
   The United States and Britain strongly oppose such a move,
saying emphasis should be placed on current East-West bargaining to
reduce conventional, or non-nuclear, arms in Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
