<DOCNO> AP890420-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1508EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     04-20 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Food Shipments to Rebel-Held Region Planned For Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations will send another
convoy of food to starving masses in southern Sudan, this time
along a different route than the treacherous path traveled by an
earlier convoy, a spokesman said Thursday.
   The convoy will be the second initiated by the United Nations
since launching Operation Lifeline Sudan on April 1. Seven people
died when the first convoy to the rebel-held region was attacked
Tuesday.
   The new 47-truck convoy is to carry 1,100 tons of maize from
Uganda's capital, Kampala, on the two-day trip to the Sudanese city
of Nimule, U.N. spokesman Paul Mitchell said. Nimule is just across
the border from Uganda.
   The relief effort aims to avert 100,000 famine deaths by
stocking more than 110,000 tons of food in southern Sudan before
heavy rains begin in mid-May.
   But the operation has been plagued with delays caused by
political difficulties, bad weather and equipment shortages. U.N.
officials concede they are unlikely to meet their goal before the
rainy season, which lasts through October.
   Mitchell said the United Nations hoped the convoy would leave
Friday, but that delays were possible.
   ``There are so many variables in this part of the world that we
don't like to say until it actually goes,'' said Mitchell.
   He said the northern Ugandan area through which the convoy would
travel is ``somewhat insecure,'' but U.N. officials did not
anticipate any problems.
   The first U.N. convoy carried 110 tons of food and supplies from
the northern Kenyan town of Lokichoggio through the Sudan People's
Liberation Army's rebel base at Kapoeta.
   It was heading to the rebel-held town of Torit when it was
attacked. Seven rebel escorts died and the lead truck in the
14-vehicle convoy was destroyed.
   U.N. officials have suspended the overland route to Torit
indefinitely due to the attack, but say an airlift to the
rebel-held town may begin Friday from the Ugandan city of Entebbe.
   Officials Thursday still had not assessed blame for Tuesday's
attack, but speculation centered on nomadic tribal warriors,
government troops or government militias operating against the
rebel group.
   The Sudan People's Liberation Army took up arms against Sudan's
Moslem-dominated government in Khartoum in 1983 seeking greater
autonomy and more economic development for the predominantly
Christian and animist south.
</TEXT>
