<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     04-20 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Announces Special Force to Combat Death Squads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco said Thursday
he is creating a 1,000-man force to wipe out right-wing death
squads run by drug traffickers.
   The death squads have killed about 1,500 people in Colombia in
the last five years. Most victims have been leftist sympathizers.
   Barco announced the new squad in a televised address Wednesday
night and released details Thursday.
   Barco said the squads are threatening democracy and sabotaging
talks between the government and leftist guerrillas.
   ``These groups are not just common criminals,'' Barco said.
``They are real terrorist organizations supported and financed
mainly by drug traffickers.''
   ``The criminal acts are carried on a pretext of anti-communism
and the fight against the guerrillas,'' he said. ``In reality, the
majority of the people who have been victims of these terrorist
acts are not guerrillas.
   ``They are men, women and even children who have not taken up
weapons against the government. They are peaceful Colombians.''
   Colombia asked the United States, Britain, Israel and Italy to
help train anti-terrorist troops, Justice Minister Guillermo Plazas
said last week after a trip to Washington.
   In the last year, death squads have attacked entire villages a
dozen times, shooting at random.
   The worst such attack came Nov. 11 when a death squad firing
submachine guns killed 43 people in the northwest town of Segovia.
   Barco said the special force will draw from all government
security forces and will be directed by the head of the national
police. The national police force is part of the armed forces.
   Barco said he also will create a national commission to take
even more measures to combat the death squads.
   The president said 23 of the estimated 150 death squads in
Colombia have been dismantled and 50 of their gunmen have been
arrested so far this year.
   It was not until after the massacre in Segovia that the
government began to act against the death squads.
   Since then, government reports have shown that the death squads
are run by drug traffickers with the help of cattlemen and other
land owners and policemen and soldiers acting on their own.
   About 30 members of the national police and the army face
charges this year for allegedly helping death squads.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
