<FIRST>r a AM-ContraCommander     04-20 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contra Commander,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contras Deny Stalling on Convicted Torturer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders Thursday denied delaying the
dismissal of a commander convicted of human rights violations, and
accused the United States of unfairly threatening to cut off aid to
the Nicaraguan rebels.
   The issue arose when the rebels agreed to suspend the head of
Contra intelligence, Jose Benito Bravo Centeno _ known as
Commandante Mack _ after a military tribunal convicted him of
torturing and killing suspected infiltrators from the country's
leftist Sandinista government.
   Mack was supposed to be relieved of duty while appealing the
conviction, but reporters recently saw him at a Contra camp in
Honduras and spotted his car outside the headquarters of the
intelligence unit.
   On Tuesday a spokesman for the State Department warned that the
United States could cut off the Nicaraguan rebels' $50 million aid,
which Congress granted only for non-lethal purposes, if they did
not carry out the sentence as agreed.
   ``I think that's unfair,'' Contra director Roberto Ferrey
responded Thursday at the rebels' Miami headquarters. ``We are
saying that human rights should be respected, and the accused also
has human rights. In the U.S., the accused has the right of appeal
_ there is nothing tricky going on.''
   Ferrey said under Contra procedures, Mack's appeal has to go
before the seven civilian directors. He added that the directorate
was trying to expedite the case, and hoped for a final decision on
Mack's punishment or expulsion by the end of April.
   The director denied Mack was continuing to work while suspended,
but acknowledged he remains at the camp in Honduras.
   ``The person has been separated from his daily duties, but he
can still be at the camp _ he doesn't have anyplace else to go,''
Ferrey said.
   Several members of Congress have made the Mack issue central to
their support for continuing the $50 million aid package signed
Tuesday by President Bush. Under the law, Congress must certify
that the Contras are respecting human rights and honoring truce
agreements reached as part of a Central American peace plan.
   Ferrey said Mack's was the only major human rights violation
case working its way through the Contra appeal procedure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
