<FIRST>r w AM-Hussein-Baker     04-20 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hussein-Baker,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hussein Backs Palestinian Elections with Conditions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein of Jordan said Thursday an
Israeli proposal for Palestinian elections in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip could advance peace in the Middle East if it is part of
a broader negotiating effort.
   Standing with Secretary of State James A. Baker III after two
hours of talks at the State Department, Hussein appeared to be more
positive about the election proposal than he had been previously
but he stopped short of a full endorsement.
   ``It is not an end in itself,'' he told reporters.
   But, he said, ``the idea of election might be worth looking at
within the context of the whole process that hopefully will come
together to get us from where we are now to a final settlement.
Otherwise, the idea is out of context.''
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir made the proposal during a
visit here two weeks ago, suggesting that Palestinians in the
occupied territories choose ``interlocutors'' to represent them in
talks with Israel on limited self-government. The territories have
been wracked by violence for almost a year and a half.
   The Bush administration has said elections would be appropriate
so long as they lead to negotiations to determine the final status
of the territories.
   Hussein's visit caps two weeks of intensive negotiations that
have included visits by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak as well as
Shamir.
   Hussein said he is more optimistic as a result of his current
visit than he has been in ``many, many years.'' His upbeat mood is
shared by top administration officials, based on comments offered
Wednesday night at a White House dinner in Hussein's honor.
   President Bush said in a toast to Hussein, ``We can sense an
urgency to the quest for peace now. Our task is to use that urgency
to seize the moment.''
   In his toast, Hussein pleased his hosts by pledging to cooperate
closely with the United States to achieve a ``just, durable and
comprehensive peace settlement.''
   ``We will support you in all your endeavors to achieve a
comprehensive just and lasting peace,'' he told Bush.
   Because of Jordan's proximity to the West Bank, the
administration regards Hussein's support for any peace process as
essential for its success.
   Administration officials appeared delighted with Hussein's
backing. He had seemed content to play a more peripheral role in
Middle East diplomacy last summer when he severed Jordan's ties
with West Bank Palestinians.
   Baker said Wednesday night that the ``beginning of a process''
is under way as a result of this month's discussions.
   ``It is important to do what he can to advance that process,''
Baker said.
   Shamir's election proposal is the newest element in the process,
and Baker left the clear impression that the administration has
carefully examined the kinds of issues that such an arrangement
would entail.
   Left unanswered thus far, he said, are such questions as who
would supervise elections in the territories, who would be entitled
to vote and whether voting rights should be extended to
Palestinians living outside the two areas.
</TEXT>
