<FIRST>r a AM-ParamedicsCalendar 1stLd-Writethru a0616 04-20 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paramedics Calendar, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0616,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charity Groups Turn Down `Sexist' Fund-Raising Calendar</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd with Roderick declining to name charities
who rejected calendar.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When paramedic Kim Roderick went looking
for a charity to take the proceeds from sales of a calendar
featuring ``Paramedics Women of the Bay Area,'' she expected a warm
welcome.
   But she said at least a half-dozen organizations gave her a cold
shoulder and called it sexist when she raised the idea almost two
years ago.
   ``One said they didn't think it would generate enough money, but
they were really concerned about the exploitation of females,'' she
said Wednesday. ``I didn't believe I couldn't even give my money
away.''
   Roderick declined to identify the charities that turned her down.
   The full-color calendar depicts 12 female paramedics at work and
at play, including a shot of Roderick as Ms. May getting ready for
a night out.
   ``We didn't want to go out and do an exploitive number with
lingerie and garter belts,'' Roderick said. ``I made an effort not
to do that.''
   Finally, administrators at the Ronald McDonald House for
critically ill children and their families in Palo Alto, about 20
miles south of San Francisco, agreed to endorse the project.
   But Roderick, 26, laments that sales were slow until a national
television magazine show featured the calendar earlier this week.
   ``Men wanted more skin and some women were a little upset,'' she
said.
   The calendars, 10,000 of which were printed, have been available
since November, but only about 3,000 were sold before the price was
cut from $10 to $5 this month, said to Marti Hirsch, a spokeswoman
for Ronald McDonald House.
   Poses include uniformed paramedics relaxing in the back of an
ambulance and talking on the radio, a paramedic in a bathing suit
and tank top posing as a lifeguard and another in a bodysuit
working out in a gym.
   Frank McMahan, who supervises about 80 full-time members of the
San Francisco paramedic team, said he thought the calendar ``gives
females a bad image.''
   A paramedic brought a calendar to the office, but McMahan said
he kept it in a drawer. ``The women in the unit have not even seen
'em, and we don't want them to see 'em. In fact, the one in the
drawer was probably thrown away.''
   Roderick defended the project as an attempt to highlight
under-publicized paramedics in addition to raising money for
charity.
</TEXT>
