<FIRST>r a AM-CDC-SpinaBifida     04-20 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC-Spina Bifida,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC Projects High Costs For Caring For Spina Bifida Kids</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 6 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The birth defect spina bifida will leave 13,000
children born in this decade struggling with its effects at an
annual cost of $100 million, federal health researchers predicted
Thursday.
   Each year, about 1,500 children are born in the United States
with spina bifida, the incomplete closing of the bony structure
surrounding the spinal cord. More than 1,000 survive into
childhood, often at tremendous medical expense, the national
Centers for Disease Control said in its weekly report Thursday.
   An estimated 9,800 children born with spina bifida from 1980 to
1987 were still alive in 1987, the CDC reported. By the end of
1990, that number is expected to grow to an estimated 13,000.
   ``In 1990, the average annual cost for medical and surgical care
for all surviving children born (with spina bifida) since 1980 will
approach $100 million,'' the Atlanta-based CDC reported.
   Further, the number of surviving spina bifida patients born
before 1980 is ``as large as those born after 1980 ... it is likely
that their costs would equal or exceed those of the post-1980
(patients),'' the CDC said.
   Spina bifida often strikes along with anencephaly, the absence
of major parts of the brain; in that case, most patients die a few
hours after birth.
   For the spina bifida patients who do survive, life is expensive.
   ``Infants with spina bifida routinely receive vigorous medical
therapy and undergo repeated surgical procedures to survive and
reach their maximum functional capacity,'' the CDC said. The
lifetime costs for such a patient can reach $250,000, according to
a 1985 North Carolina study cited by the federal researchers.
   The cause of spina bifida is unknown, but the disease rate is
decreasing _ from a rate of 5.2 cases per 10,000 births in 1980 to
4.3 in 1987.
   ``Nobody really knows why; it's really quite incredible,'' said
Dr. David Erickson, a CDC birth defects specialist. Some of the
decrease is due to new high-technology prenatal testing which gives
more mothers the option of terminating problem pregnancies, ``but
that doesn't explain all of it,'' he said.
   A previous CDC study found 50 percent fewer spina bifida cases
among women who took multivitamins during pregnancy, but
researchers haven't yet determined if that was the cause, or if
those women had other characteristics reducing their children's
risk.
   The CDC has declined to recommend widespread multivitamin
treatments for pregnant women ``without firmly knowing that it's
going to do something ... that's not good policy,'' Erickson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
