<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0629 04-20 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Frustrated by Lack of Leverage in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 8 grafs after 6th graf bgng: ``The problem ... to UPDATE
with State Department comments, background. Picks up 7th graf pvs bgng:
Secretary of ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush expressed frustration Thursday
over inability to end violence in war-ravaged Lebanon but said he
and other world leaders ``can't give up on it.''
   Discussing the violence during a question-and-answer session
with a group of reporters, Bush said, ``I wish there was a
short-term answer to stop the killing in Lebanon.''
   He said he discussed the problem by telephone earlier this week
with French President Francois Mitterrand but knew of ``no dramatic
plan in which the players in the area could agree to.''
   And Bush said the United States has little power to bring about
change.
   ``That's the problem, we don't have great influence in Lebanon
with the factions that are fighting,'' the president said.
   ``The problem, the short-run of it, how you stop this firing,
the shelling, how you get factions to stop warring, has certainly
in recent times defied solution,'' he said. ``But we can't give up
on it. We simply are not going to.''
   The State Department, meanwhile, said it welcomed a call by 23
Christian members of the Lebanese parliament urging a cease-fire
between the Syrian army and Lebanese armed forces.
   ``We strongly support their appeal for a political dialogue,''
said Richard Boucher, a department spokesman. ``It is a recognition
that Lebanon's current crisis can only be resolved through
consultation and reconciliation.''
   Boucher said the statement by the Lebanese parliamentarians
reflected the desires of ``the vast majority'' of both Christian
and Moslem Lebanese ``to seek a peaceful resolution to Lebanon's
political problems.''
   ``It underscores the critical importance of Lebanon's parliament
as a legitimate representative body and the crucial role it must
play in restoring a central government to the country,'' Boucher
said.
   ``We urge all sides, including Syria and General (Michel) Auoun,
to accept this call for a cease-fire and seek ways to resume a
political dialogue,'' he added.
   The battles started March 8 after Aoun, the army commander and
head of the Christian Cabinet in Lebanon's divided government,
imposed a naval blockade on ports run by independent militias.
   Moslem militias then shelled Christian neigbhorhoods. Syria,
which has 40,000 troops in Lebanon, joined the Moslems.
   ``We've been in touch with everybody we can find in Lebanon and
in the region to talk about this and to try to bring about a
solution,'' Boucher said.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, testifying earlier in the
week before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, called Lebanon
``a great tragedy that is very, very intractable. It does not lend
itself to an easy solution.''
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush's
discussion with Mitterrand touched on ways the United Nations might
act to calm the situation.
   ``Both presidents stressed their concern about the loss of life,
injuries, and deterioration of the situation in Beirut,'' Fitzwater
said.
   Mitterrand, who is scheduled to visit Bush at the U.S.
president's vacation home at Kennebunkport, Maine, next month, also
has contacted British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and several
other world leaders, soliciting their help in ending the war.
   During his talk with reporters along the colonnade leading to
the Oval Office, Bush did say he felt that U.S. standing with
``moderate Arab nations'' had improved, saying relations were ``as
good today as any time in recent history.''
   He said he felt the United States had ``restored some prestige
by the way we acted'' in policing the Persian Gulf waterway during
the latter stages of the Iran-Iraq war.
   ``We have, I think, much better communication now with Jordan,''
he said. Bush also said that ``we've kept good cooperation and
coordination with the Egyptians. The Israelis themselves attest to
the fact that they have great confidence in our administration.''
   ``We have some differences with all three of those,'' Bush added.
</TEXT>
