<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Media     04-20 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Media,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Accuses East Bloc Countries of Nazi-style Media Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada on Thursday accused four communist
countries of gross violations of a new East-West accord on press
freedom and said their propaganda techniques and state-controlled
media resemble those of Nazi Germany.
   Canadian Ambassador William Bauer, addressing a 35-nation
conference monitoring compliance with the accord, said some of the
signatory states remained ``locked in a dark age of information
where the only `correct' facts are those put out by the ruling
party.''
   ``It is particularly poignant to observe that today, on the
100th anniversary of the birth of Hitler, the techniques of press
and information control which characterized his regime are still
being applied by some European governments,'' he added.
   Bauer, head of the Canadian delegation, said later he was
referring to Romania, East Germany, Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia. He
described Romania as a ``sort of joke'' as a signatory to an accord
of press freedom and free speech.
   Romania's chief delegate, Ian Mitaan, accused Western critics of
``deplorable attempts at flagrant interference in the internal
affairs other countries.''
   Romania was the most reluctant signatory to the January accord
on press and other freedoms. It was signed in Vienna after a
35-nation Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe.
   Bauer's criticisms came on the third day of a month-long London
conference known as the Information Forum.
   On Wednesday, the chief U.S. delegate, Leonard Marks, also
singled out Romania, Bulgaria, East Germany and Czechoslovakia as
having done nothing to implement the accord.
   In Romania, journalists and other users of typewriters have to
get their machines licensed and give police a record of the
typefaces. It is the country most frequently accused of ignoring
the January agreement.
   Western delegates have repeatedly praised the Soviet Union for
its policy of glasnost, or greater openness. They also have said
two other reformist communist states, Hungary and Poland, have made
significant improvements in allowing free speech but still have a
way to go.
   Hungary has announced widespread political reforms, including
plans to allow multiparty elections. In Poland, the government this
month signed a political accord with the free trade union,
Solidarity.
   Addressing the conference Thursday, Laszlo Demus, the chief
Hungarian delegate, called for an end to ``uncritical
self-adulation and idolization of leaders'' in state-controlled
media in Europe.
   ``If anything is redolent of the Middles Ages and alien to our
present-day Europeanism, it is this,'' said Demus.
</TEXT>
