<FIRST>r w AM-PlutoniumPlant     04-20 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plutonium Plant,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Groups Seek to Force Environmental Study on New Defense Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two environmental groups said Thursday they
would sue the Energy Department to force a government study of the
environmental risks posed by the planned startup of a new plutonium
processing plant in California.
   The department said it has not yet decided whether such a study
is necessary.
   The Natural Resources Defense Council and the Western States
Legal Foundation, in a letter to Energy Secretary James D. Watkins,
said they would sue the department if it failed to prepare an
environmental impact statement for the Engineering Demonstration
System before putting the plant into operation.
   The groups said the plant could begin running as early as this
summer, although Janie Shaheen, a department spokeswoman, said no
decision had been made on the timing of startup.
   In the letter to Watkins, the groups said an environmental
impact statement is required by the National Environmental Policy
Act. Ms. Shaheen said the department's field office in San
Francisco was considering the matter and ``will shortly be making
that decision.''
   The environmental groups said the proposed new plant, at the
department's Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, is intended to
demonstrate a new plutonium processing technology for use at the
department's proposed Special Isotope Separation plant in Idaho,
which would convert fuel-grade plutonium to weapon-grade plutonium.
   The groups said that because of the larger population in the
vicinity of the Livermore site, the Engineering Demonstration
System presents more potential health and safety risk than the
Idaho site, near Idaho Falls, for which an environmental impact
statement was prepared.
   ``It is reckless to think an (environmental impact statement) is
not needed for a facility which vaporizes sizeable quantities of
plutonium _ a potent cancer-causing substance _ in a highly
populated area subject to earthquakes,'' said Jim Werner, project
engineer at the Natural Resources Defense Council.
   Werner's group has a suit pending against the Energy Department
to force it to complete an environmental impact statement on the
proposed restart of three defense nuclear reactors in South
Carolina. The department has begun the environmental assessment
there but contends it is not required to complete it before
restarting the reactors, which make a radioactive gas used in
nuclear warheads.
</TEXT>
