<FIRST>r a AM-CaponeHouse     04-20 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capone House,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capone Landmark Would Further Chicago's Gangster Image, Italians
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An amateur historian has withdrawn his bid to
make Al Capone's home a historic landmark, a move hailed Thursday
by an Italian-American leader who said, ``This is not the kind of
image we want to be presenting to the world.''
   Capone's modest, two-story brick house on Chicago's South Side
was nominated for listing on the National Register of Historic
Places in January. Rejected by local groups, the nomination was
appealed by Mark Levell, a computer repairman.
   He withdrew his appeal Wednesday, saying, ``I still think the
house has tremendous historical interest, but I have no intention
of offending anyone, and some people left me no doubt that they
quite clearly are offended by it.''
   Levell, who is half-Italian, has made an extensive study of
Prohibition-era crime history.
   Other Italian-Americans failed to share Levell's interest in the
house, said Robert Allegrini, executive director of the
Italian-American Committee.
   ``No one man has done so much harm to the good name of his
ethnic group as Al Capone has done for Italian-Americans. This is
not the kind of image we want to be presenting to the world,'' said
Allegrini.
   The proposal had been opposed by Italian-American groups, the
Chicago Sun-Times and a local neighborhood council. The Chicago
Landmarks Commission, Illinois Historic Sites Council and a city
report had also recommended against the house's memorialization.
   Critics ``complained that I was trying to honor a notorious
criminal, but I never said anything about `honor,''' Levell said.
``The Prohibition gangsters were part of this city's history. ...
They were colorful men, but I never suggested them as role models
for anyone.''
   Levell said Capone lived in the house from 1920 to 1928, but
later moved into the Lexington Hotel for security. He said Capone's
mother and several of his brothers remained in the house after
Capone moved out.
   Capone, who was sent to Alcatraz on federal tax violations, died
of syphilis in 1947.
</TEXT>
