<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Space     04-20 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Space,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Vows to ``Keep America First in Space''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, vowing to ``keep America first
in space,'' made good on a campaign promise and signed an order
Thursday re-establishing the National Space Council.
   At a ceremony with council members, Bush said that 20 years ago
``an entire generation of Americans was inspired by the space
program. We must continue on the path we've blazed in earlier
decades with a renewed dedication.''
   Bush designated Vice President Dan Quayle as chairman of the
council. Other members include the secretaries of State, Treasury,
Defense, Commerce, Transportaton, the budget director, the head of
NASA, the White House national security adviser and the chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   Bush said the action fulfilled a campaign promise he made 18
months ago at the Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala.
   ``I pledged then and I'm proud now to re-establish the National
Space Council,'' Bush said.
   The council had been disbanded in the mid-1970s.
   The president re-established the unit with an executive order.
The council was told to review U.S. space policy and to make
recommendations for long-range goals and activities.
   Thursday's ceremony was held in Quayle's office in the Old
Executive Office Building.
   ``Under his able leadership, I'm confident that the space
council will bring coherence and continuity and commitment to our
efforts to explore, study and develop space,'' Bush said.
   Quayle welcomed the former vice president back to ``your former
office,'' and said: ``Mr. President, we take your charge with a
great deal of seriousness.''
   ``Space is certainly the frontier _ it is a frontier that we
understand and we're going to be there,'' Quayle said.
   Bush has called for a $2 billion, or 19 percent, increase in
spending on space programs the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. He
has proposed a build-up in the rate of space shuttle flights to
nine in 1990, and has voiced support for on-schedule construction
of the manned space station Freedom.
   ``Space is vitally important to our nation's future and to the
quality of life here on Earth,'' Bush said. ``It offers a
technological frontier creating jobs for tomorrow.''
   ``Space is the manifest destiny of a new generation and a new
century,'' he continued. ``I plan to sign this executive order with
one objective in mind: to keep America first in space.''
   ``It's only a matter of time before the world salutes the first
men and women on their way outward into the solar system. All of us
want them to be Americans.''
</TEXT>
