<HEAD>Board Vote On Holocaust Postponed _ For Passover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The school board was set to declare a
week in May as Holocaust Week, but ruffled some members' feelings
when it scheduled the vote for Passover.
   The board postponed the matter Wednesday night after learning
its two Jewish members couldn't attend the meeting. Passover, a
Jewish holiday celebrating the freeing of the Israelites from
slavery in Egypt, began at sundown.
   With five of nine members absent, the board rescheduled the
meeting for Tuesday.
   ``There have been several different occasions when important
functions were scheduled on holidays,'' said board member Fannie G.
Krevsky, who is Jewish. ``I just felt that enough was enough.''
   Board President Clarice L. Chambers said the district ``has
always been sensitive to our Jewish community, even in the
assistance in the restoration and cleanup of the recent desecration
of the Kesher Israel Synagogue'' in Harrisburg by vandals.
   She said she didn't know until this week that Passover began
Wednesday evening.
   ``My calendar has it beginning on Thursday,'' she said. ``In the
future, we will make every attempt to set our meetings when they
are not in conflict with religious holidays.''
