<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia     04-20 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Resistance Leader Seeks Arms Aid for Leverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While seeking U.S. military aid, Cambodia's
non-communist resistance still prefers a peaceful political
solution to the Southeast Asian country's problems, resistance
leader Son Sann said Thursday.
   President Bush's administration is considering providing some
weapons assistance and the proposal has backing in Congress, Son
Sann said after meeting with administration officials.
   Hopefully, he said, the weapons would never be used but they are
needed to press the communist side to negotiate an acceptable
agreement and ``to send a signal to the Khmer Rouge and Vietnamese
that we can become stronger.''
   The war- and occupation-ravaged country has had enough bloodshed
and ``we don't want a settlement leaving any Cambodian party back
in the jungles'' for more fighting, said the 77-year-old former
premier.
   The State Department said earlier this week that increased U.S.
help should be provided the non-communist resistance but no
decision has been reached on composition of the aid.
   Son Sann said he is taking to Southeast Asia a new suggestion
for the U.N. Secretary General and his representatives to take a
dominant role in organizing and supervising free elections for a
future Cambodian government.
   Son Sann leads the smallest of four Cambodian factions involved
in complex negotiations involving the superpowers and other
permament members of the U.N. Security Council, the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations and Vietnam, which invaded Cambodia in 1978
and which has promised to withdraw all its forces in the coming
months.
   The other Cambodian factions are led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk,
former head of state; Premier Hun Sen of the Vietnamese-installed
Peoples Republic of Kampuchea regime in Pnomh Penh and the Khmer
Rouge, blamed for the deaths of more than 2 million Cambodians
during a 1975-78 reign of terror.
   Son Sann is heading for London and Paris before returning to
Bangkok. In Bangkok he plans to brief Sihanouk in preparation for
what he described as a crucial May 2 meeting in Jakarta, Indonesia,
between Sihanouk and Hun Sen.
   ``It will be very bad,'' if the two sides remain deadlocked, he
said, urging that Hun Sen consider Sihanouk's proposals without
continuing to insist that his government conduct the proposed
elections.
   Son Sann said he is taking to Sihanouk a suggestion of Rep.
Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Foreign Affairs Asian
subcommittee, for U.N. Secretary General Xavier Perez de Cuellar to
organize an interim government for Cambodia with a special U.N.
representative in charge of verifying a cease-fire and organizing
and supervising elections.
   Hun Sen has earlier rejected a proposal for a Cambodian
government of all four factions to conduct the elections.
   A PRK-Vietnamese proposal for the 35-year-old Indochina Control
Commission of India, Poland and Canada to supervise the elections
is unacceptable to the non-communists because India, one of the few
countries to recognize the Hun Sen government ``is not neutral,''
Son Sann said.
   A successful Sihanouk-Hun Sen meeting would be followed by a
mid-May working session in Paris of envoys of all four factions,
and a June summit of the faction leaders, Son Sann said.
   Final stage of the settlement process, he added, would be an
international conference on Cambodia at which the accords should be
guaranteed by the United States, France, Britain, China and the
Soviet Union.
   Vietnam has announced 50,000 of its soldiers remain to be
withdrawn from Cambodia. Son Sann estimated the number of
Vietnamese remaining as 70,000-80,000 military personnel, plus
hundreds of thousands of settlers, many disguised as Cambodians.
   The Khmer Rouge, he said, have 35,000 fighters and Sihanouk's
forces number 18,000. Son Sann said his own faction counts 10,000
activists, plus unorganized, latent support from most of the nation.
</TEXT>
