<DOCNO> AP890420-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Georgia     04-20 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Tear Gas Could Have Caused Injuries, Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Highly concentrated tear gas could have caused the
symptoms that prompted some officials to charge that soldiers used
nerve gas in a violent clash with protesters in Soviet Georgia, a
Foreign Ministry spokesman said Thursday.
   ``It would be unwarranted if we were to talk about nerve gas,''
spokesman Yuri Gremitskykh said at a news briefing, despite reports
in the government newspaper Izvestia that protesters had been
injured by an aerosol with an effect like atropine, a nerve poison.
   At least 20 demonstrators died April 9 when soldiers were
ordered to clear a crowd of pro-independence demonstrators.
Witnesses say the troops attacked with shovels, clubs and gas, and
chased down fleeing demonstrators to beat them to death. Georgian
activists claim several deaths were caused by the gas.
   Gremitskykh cited media reports that tear gas had been used
against the demonstrators, and he told reporters that highly
concentrated tear gas could have caused the injuries that Georgian
Health Minister Irakly Menagarishvili blamed on a substance like
atropine.
   Atropine is a poisonous crystalline alkaloid that in large doses
can induce nerve paralysis and delirium. It can cause death through
combined cardiac and respiratory failure.
   Gremitskykh said the cause of death must be established by
medical experts. There has been no official account of the number
of protesters poisoned by the gas.
   Meanwhile, another group of Moscow intellectuals joined the
condemnation of the decision to send troops to clear peaceful
demonstrators.
   April, a group of progressive writers, adopted a resolution
protesting ``the cruelty of the army and the brutal methods of
authorities,'' said a member, Marina Pristavkin.
   The group's resolution was written by noted poet Yevgeny
Yevtushenko, she said. Several members also signed an open letter
written by human rights activist Andrei Sakharov condemning the
confrontation in Tbilisi.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, a native of
Georgia and its former Communist Party chief, has called the clash
in Tbilisi a blow to President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's efforts to
reform Soviet society. Shevardnadze was sent to Tbilisi after the
clash in an effort to try to restore order.
   The republic's leadership assumed responsibility for the clash
and the Communist Party leader and premier resigned.
   Protests began in early April in reaction to demands by the
small Black Sea area of Abkhazia to be separated from Georgia, but
turned into massive protests by groups demanding Georgian
independence. Soldiers were ordered into Georgia on April 7.
   Georgia has been closed to foreign journalists, but Gremitskykh
announced that small groups of reporters would be allowed to visit
Tbilisi beginning Sunday.
   Official reports Thursday said Tbilisi remained calm but that a
Soviet army officer was beaten severely by assailants Wednesday
night, two nights after a curfew was lifted.
   Krasnaya Zvezda, the Defense Ministry newspaper, said the
officer was attacked in the area of Tbilisi's military hospital as
he was on his way home. He suffered a brain concussion and was in
serious condition, the paper quoted doctors as saying. It said the
unidentified attackers managed to get away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
