<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Energy,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Conducts Swearing-in of DOE Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle conducted the
swearing-in of the Energy Department's No. 2 and No. 3 officials
Thursday and said the White House was eager to see the department
quickly overcome its many internal problems.
   After administering the oath of office to Henson Moore, the
deputy energy secretary, and John C. Tuck, the undersecretary of
energy, Quayle reiterated in a speech to department employees that
President Bush was committed to keeping the department. Former
President Ronald Reagan once pledged to dismantle it.
   ``The Department of Energy is here to stay _ there is no
question about that,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle told Energy Secretary James D. Watkins that Bush was
counting on him to resolve a wide array of department problems.
Quayle was not more specific, but Watkins has identified his chief
tasks as modernizing the nation's nuclear weapons complex and
putting together a new national energy policy.
   ``You have a tremendous challenge ahead of you, but knowing you
and the spirit and the type of people that you have surrounded
yourself with, those challenges will not be difficult,'' Quayle
said.
   Moore, in a reference to recent publicity about the department's
failures, said some people are describing it as being ``the
last-place team'' among the 14 Cabinet departments.
   ``I assure you, Mr. Vice President, that's not going to be the
final ranking when the season is over,'' he said.
