<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1952EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-InsuredStudents     04-20 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insured Students,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>School's Plan to Raise Money from Students' Deaths Enlivens Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Boston University proposal to raise money by
taking out life insurance policies on students drew mixed reviews
Thursday, with some terming it a ghoulish scheme and others
applauding its money-making potential.
   BU President John Silber has proposed taking out policies on
students and alumni and collecting the benefits when they die.
   ``It's very much in the discussion kind of stage. Numbers and
fine points are to be worked out, if ever,'' said Tom Cashman, vice
president of public affairs.
   Some students were aghast at the idea of the school benefiting
from their deaths, even though the program would be voluntary.
   ``I have a feeling he hasn't thought this through. It's going to
make it a Dracula kind of school,'' said Drew Kodjak, a graduate
student at BU's law school.
   ``I have to give him credit. It's a great idea,'' said Steven
Cagnetta, also a law student. ``It just doesn't sit right.''
   Silber discussed the proposal publicly last week before a group
of scholarship students. The university newspaper, the Daily Free
Press, later published an account of his remarks. Silber was not in
his office Thursday.
   Cashman said he has received some positive calls from donors
interested in the proposal.
   ``It's not as negative as some of our reviewers want to cast
it,'' he said. ``It's an opportunity for individuals who are
concerned about the longterm financial health of the university 50,
60 or 70 years down the line to make a contribution that far
exceeds what they otherwise would be able to do.''
   Money to buy the policies probably would come from a
fund-raising drive and students would neither pay nor receive money
for participating.
   The plan calls for purchasing 1,000 policies worth $350,000 at a
cost of $5,500 each, with BU listed as policy owner. The school
would then wait 10 years before buying more. Eventually, the
original 1,000 policies would be worth $350 million, several times
the original outlay.
   Insurance officials said the idea seemed to be a new development
in the traditional method of deferred giving. Other universities
have suggested their alumni make their alma mater part of their
estate plans, including naming schools as beneficiaries of life
insurance policies.
   At St. Louis University in Missouri, a plan under which an
alumnus makes a gift and then allows the school to take out a life
insurance policy under his name has created a future endowment of
$16 million, said the Rev. J. Barry McGannon, vice president for
development.
   But he said the BU program appears to be of far greater scope
than other plans.
   Silber has said he wants to raise $1 billion by the year 2000.
   ``It's a gimmick, of course. It's a twist on what we've heard
of,'' said Ben Isaacs, spokesman for the American Council of Life
Insurance in New York. Some corporations already are starting to
ensure their employees, but Isaacs said he hasn't heard of colleges
doing so. ``We think this may be a developing thing.''
   ``I think it sounds inventive and interesting,'' said Paul
Miller, vice president of the Council for Aid to Education in
Washington. ``I'd like to know more about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
