<FIRST>r w AM-US-Panama 420   04-20 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama, 420</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Decries Panamanian Move to Require Visas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Noriega's new plan to require
visas for U.S. citizens visiting Panama is an attempt to avoid
international scrutiny during next month's elections, the State
Department charged on Thursday.
   ``Noriega's latest action is an effort to insulate Panama's
electoral process from any credible degree of public scrutiny,''
said department spokesman Richard Boucher.
   The Noriega regime has announced that as of April 21, Americans
may no longer travel to Panama by simply filling out a tourist
card. The card was given to tourists at the airport of their point
of departure.
   The opposition, which has expressed fears the polling will be
rigged by the government, has invited hundreds of foreigners to
visit Panama for the national May 7 election.
   The key race involves a Noreiga-backed candidate for president
against an opposition leader.
   Boucher added that Noriega's officials have also begun to screen
visa applications in third countries ``in an effort to deny travel
to Panama of election observers, journalists and other persons
interested in covering the Panama electoral process.''
   Noriega is under indictment in Florida on drug smuggling
charges. The United States has maintained that it cannot have
normal relations with the Panamanian government until Noriega steps
down.
   The spokesman contrasted the new visa restriction with ``the
recent Salvadoran election and the upcoming Paraguay election where
election observers, press and diplomatic scrutiny have been
actively and openly welcomed.''
   The spokesman said the election would provides an opportunity
for Panamanians ``to move forward to a resolution of the continuing
political and economic crisis. A fraudulent election will only
perpetuate Panama's problems.
   ``A legitimate regime has nothing to fear from an honest
election and from the unfettered presence of observers and of the
press,'' Boucher said.
   The requirement could create headaches for U.S. citizens who
want to visit Panama because most Panamanian consulates in the
United States are not recognized by Noriega's regime. The rule
states that U.S. citizens must have visas stamped by ``Panamanian
consulates recognized by our government.''
   Only the consulate in Tampa, Fla., is said to be recognized by
Noriega's followers.
   The majority of diplomatic offices in the United States have
remained loyal to the ousted president, Eric Arturo Delvalle, who
has moved to Miami.
   In February, 1988, Delvalle attempted to fire Noriega from his
post as defense chief, but within hours he was deposed by the
legislature dominated by Noriega followers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
