<FIRST>r w AM-ForeignSales     04-20 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Sales,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Sale Approved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government has agreed to sell Greece
60 tanks worth $26 million and 16 Harpoon missiles, missile
containers and contracting services worth $19 million, the Pentagon
said Thursday.
   In addition, the government plans to sell 250 Maverick missiles,
their support equipment, publications and training and technical
assistance to Spain at a cost of $48 million.
   The foreign sales are subject to congressional approval.
   The M48A5 tanks are no longer in production and will come from
excess stock. The department, in a statement, said Greece needs the
tanks to upgrade its tank fleet and increase its military defense
capability.
   The prime contractor of the Harpoon missiles will be
McDonnell-Douglas Astronautics Co., of St. Louis, Mo., the
department said.
   A prime contractor on the missile sale to Spain will be made
after the competitive bidding process.
