<FIRST>r a AM-People-Brown     04-20 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Brown,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Godfather of Soul' James Brown Gives Jailhouse Interview</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soul singer James Brown has awed fellow inmates at
the State Park Correctional Center in South Carolina and is still
giving them autographs four months after his arrival, The Boston
Globe reported Thursday.
   Brown, 55, is serving a six-year sentence on a charge of
aggravated assault and failing to stop for police during a chase
across the George-South Carolina border that left his pickup
riddled with 26 bullets last Sept. 24.
   He is working on kitchen detail in the mornings. But in the
evenings, the fabled ``Godfather of Soul,'' whose gold records
include ``Please Please Please'' and ``Papa's Got a Brand New
Bag,'' is conducting the prison choir.
   ``They've come a long way since Mr. Brown took over,'' inmate
Gregory Harrison said.
   ``He seems to be doing all right to me. He mingles with the
fellas. It's real fascinating to me. I never thought I'd meet James
Brown in real life. I'm sorry it had to be in here.''
   ``I'd like to go back to gospel,'' Brown, a former gospel
singer, told the newspaper in an interview from the prison in State
Park, S.C. ``Really I never left. Or it never left me. The public
may not know it, but the Sex Machine first did it to death for the
Lord.''
   Brown sees a double standard in the fact that no politicians
have come to his aid. He said he went to Vietnam for Lyndon
Johnson, helped quell he riots in America in the 1960s, sang at
Richard Nixon's inauguration party and lent his fame to various
antidrug pronouncements.
   ``Politics and reality is so different now that reality doesn't
have anything to do with politics anymore,'' Brown said. ``All the
people in Watergate, they out of jail, now, right?''
   Brown's attorney, George Hill, has advised him to divorce his
fourth wife, Adrienne, who is due to stand trial shortly on drug
possession charges, thinking that a divorce might be a step to
earlier parole, the newspaper said. But Brown refused.
   ``I'm not going to court for a divorce,'' Brown said. ``I love
my wife.''
</TEXT>
