<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Walesa 1stLd-Writethru a0602 04-20 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0602,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Meets Pope; Hails His Support of Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUB 6th graf, `It was...' with four grafs UPDATING with Polish
developments. Picks up 7th pvs, `During his...' with minor editing to trim;
ADDS 2 grafs at end, Walesa won't run in elections.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa on Thursday lauded Pope John
Paul II as a ``great Pole'' who kept the Solidarity labor movement
alive, and knelt at his feet in an emotional reunion.
   The labor leader briefed the pope on the political accords in
Poland that led to the restoration of Solidarity's legal status on
Monday after nearly eight years of suppression by the communist
government.
   ``My batteries are recharged, and now I am ready to lift any
weight,'' Walesa said after the 30 minutes of private talks in the
pope's library.
   John Paul, who had given his warm endorsement of Solidarity
during Walesa's visit to the Vatican in 1981, said he was praying
for the success of the political reforms in his homeland.
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro quoted the pope as saying he
hopes that Poland ``has a new possibility and that the
transformations in the social, political and economic life of the
entire society can take place.''
   About 10,000 students rallied in at least five Polish cities
Thursday to demand greater academic freedom and registration of the
still banned Independent Students Association, a Solidarity
spokesman and Poland's state radio reported.
   The association is due to gain restoration of its legal status
according to the round-table agreements reached on April 5.
   A Warsaw provisional court declared the independent farmers
union Rural Solidarity legal Thursday, three days after
relegalizing Solidarity.
   Thursday's meeting was the fourth meeting the pope and Walesa.
They also met during John Paul's pilgrimages to Poland in 1983, the
year Walesa won the Nobel Peace Prize, and 1987.
   During his visit in 1987, the pope stressed the need to keep the
spirit of Solidarity alive. The Soviet bloc's first independent
trade union was crushed by martial law in December 1981 and
outlawed in October 1982.
   The Roman Catholic Church is a major force in Poland and church
representatives participated in the negotiations that produced the
reforms.
   Earlier Thursday, visiting the Rome hospital where the pope was
treated after being shot by a Turkish gunman in 1981, Walesa said
Solidarity couldn't have survived without the pope's support.
   ``Here the life of Solidarity was saved because here the life of
a great Pole, the Holy Father, was saved,'' he said.
   ``One day history will say how important was the contribution of
this great Pole and this great man to the affirmations of the
ideals of Solidarity,'' Walesa said. ``I can't imagine my battle
and the life of Solidarity without the pope.''
   When he arrived at the pope's private library, he knelt at John
Paul's feet. The pope pulled him up and embraced him, saying, ``We
have to show how you greet the pope and how I greet you. I greet
you with all my heart.''
   After the private discussions, the two men were joined in the
library by Walesa's wife, Danuta, and five Solidarity aides and the
bishop of Gdansk, birthplace of Solidarity.
   Speaking later on Vatican TV, Walesa said the political and
economic reforms in the Soviet Union could be beneficial for the
rest of Eastern Europe.
   Monsignor Bronislaw Dabrowski, secretary general of the Polish
bishops' conference, spoke of the changes in Poland in the eight
years since Walesa's first visit to the Vatican.
   Today, he said, Polish union leaders are working with the
government to rebuild the country. ``In these years, the government
and the unions have matured.''
   Walesa, invited to Rome by Italy's trade union leaders, has said
he was seeking Western help for Poland's economic crisis. He met
with union leaders Thursday evening and will confer with top
government officials on Friday.
   During his visit to Gemelli Hospital, he blmed the Communist
government for Poland's ``economic disaster'' but said he is ready
to work with the government to overcome the difficulties.
   ``Poland wants to join Europe,'' he said. ``It is important to
translate the political victory into practical accomplishments.''
   Asked whether he would run in Poland's upcoming elections,
Walesa replied, ``No, I have other things to do, and there are
other candidates who are better.''
   The accords provide for a freely elected senate with veto power
over the existing single-chamber parliament. The legislature will
elect a president.
</TEXT>
