<HEAD>Senate Confirms Coverdell as Peace Corps Director</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul D. Coverdell, the Republican leader of
the Georgia Senate for the past 14 years, has been confirmed by the
Senate as the new director of the Peace Corps.
   The Senate approved President Bush's nomination of Coverdell by
a voice vote late Wednesday. He replaces Loret Miller Ruppe, who
has been director since 1981, the longest tenure since the agency
was begun in 1961.
   ``The Peace Corps represents America's sense of concern for
humanity throughout the world,'' Coverdell said in a statement
Thursday. ``Our volunteers prove every day that citizen service can
and does work.''
   The Peace Corps has about 6,000 volunteers in 65 countries
throughout Asia, Africa, Latin America the Caribbean and the
Pacific. They are involved in such fields as engineering, health
care, education, forestry, agriculture and community development.
