<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     04-20 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Multicandidate Elections Since 1946</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters on Thursday chose nine new
parliamentary deputies from 20 candidates _ the first time
Czechoslovak voters have had a choice in an election since 1946.
   The official news agency CTK gave scant details of the
elections, which have not been marked by any of the fervent
campaigning that accompanied last month's first multicandidate
elections in seven decades in the Soviet Union.
   Results were not expected before Friday.
   Regional organization of the Communist-dominated National Front
narrowed down the candidate list from 106 to 20 for the seats in
nine electoral regions, CTK said.
   It did not name any of the candidates, who must all be members
of the National Front, which includes all political parties and
official social organizations.
   Several of the elections were to replace parliamentarians who
resigned or were fired in a government shake-up in October.
   Seven of the districts are in Bohemia and Moravia, and two in
Slovakia, CTK said.
   A simple majority of 50 percent is required to win a seat, it
said.
</TEXT>
