<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 2039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Kemp-Evictions     04-20 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kemp-Evictions,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Says Parental Role To be Considered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp, who has
encouraged efforts to evict drug dealers and users from public
housing, said Thursday that authorities will have to consider the
role parents played in drug activity by their children before
evicting entire families.
   Kemp said that in some cases parents may be unable to control
older, physically strong children who are engaged in drug activity.
In those cases, he said, ``I don't think Mom and Dad should be
punished'' by eviction.
   But he said there are cases where mothers or other heads of
families are participants in drug enterprises, sometimes with their
children.
   ``Let the tenants and the PHAs (public housing agencies) throw
them out,'' Kemp said. ``On the first, first _ one, one _ time
you're caught doing, dealing, engaging in drug traffic, I would
say, out.''
   Kemp, secretary of Housing and Urban Development, has offered to
drop HUD requirements that public housing agencies hold hearings
for tenants before they can be evicted for drug-related activity.
He said the hearings may be waived if local laws provide tenants
with due process in the courts.
   Kemp this week announced HUD actions aimed at further easing the
eviction process for local public housing agencies, which operate
federally subsidized housing projects. Among the steps HUD is
taking is to make illegal drug abuse or drug dealing a specific
violation of leases for HUD-subsidized housing.
   Kemp spoke at a seminar sponsored by Sen. Tim Wirth, D-Colo.,
for Colorado constituents.
   Asked how the eviction policy would be applied in cases of
families with children, Kemp said each case would depend on the
role of the parents.
   ``I think on a case-by-case basis you've got to find out whether
the parents were involved and knowingly allowed drugs to be either
sold or manufactured or dealt or used in that apartment, public
housing, or whether they were overcome by a situation,'' Kemp said.
   ``If they were overcome by the circumstances of having one of
their children involved without them having any culpability, I
would say they shouldn't lose their apartment,'' he said.
   ``If a mother, believe it or not, is involved in drugs, she
ought to be _ I don't want to make her homeless, but I don't want
her polluting public housing. And I've got a home for her or him or
whoever ... jail,'' he said.
</TEXT>
