<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Soviets     04-20 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviets,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Moscow Solicits Israeli Investments In Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio Moscow on Thursday solicited Israeli
investment in Soviet companies, saying the lack of diplomatic ties
between the two countries was not an obstacle to trade.
   The offer was made during the station's nightly 30-minute
Hebrew-language broadcast, said Israel radio monitor Mickey Gurdus.
   In the past, Radio Moscow has used the broadcasts mainly for
commentary sharply critical of the Jewish state.
   In the proposal presented Thursday, the radio station named a
Soviet company for foreign trade, Belka, and provided its address,
telephone and telex numbers in Moscow, Gurdus said.
   ``They said they are ready to initiate the contacts, and later
represent Israeli companies because it's quite expensive to
maintain offices in the Soviet Union,'' Gurdus said.
   ``They said they made the offer even though there are no
diplomatic ties, and are ready to discuss any offer,'' he said.
   The Soviet Union severed diplomatic ties after Israel captured
lands of Moscow's Arab allies during the 1967 Middle East war.
   In the past two years, relations have improved, mainly because
the Soviet Union hopes to play a greater role in the Middle East.
The two countries have swapped consular delegations and stepped up
cultural exchanges.
</TEXT>
