<FIRST>r w AM-US-Ethiopia 280   04-20 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Ethiopia, 280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopia Seeking to Improve Ties With US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet-backed government of Ethiopia asked
the United States to accept its ambassador in Washington in an
apparent move to upgrade relations, it was reported on Thursday.
   ``The Ethiopians have expressed an interest in improved
relations, a subject that has been under consideration by both
governments for some months,'' department spokesman Richard Boucher
told reporters.
   The spokesman said the United States was ``continuing to
review'' the request, but that nothing more had been decided.
   At present, the two countries are represented only by a charge
d'affaires in each other's capitals.
   An official familiar with developments in the African nation,
who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the request was made last
month.
   The Ethiopians asked to send Tibabu Bekelena, a diplomat who is
now the country's deputy foreign minister, as the ambassador, said
the official.
   It appeared unlikely that the United States would move quickly
on the request.
   The bid comes after more than a decade of poor relations between
the two nations that stemmed from the 1974 revolution that removed
Emperor Haile Selassie and brought Lieut. Col. Mengistu Haile
Mariam and his leftist supporters to power.
   And due to congressional unhappiness with the human rights
situation in Ethiopia, economic assistance to the nation is barred.
   In its most recent report on human rights, the State Department
charged Ethiopia with a ``deplorable'' human rights record.
   Humanitarian aid, however, is allowed and last year the U.S.
government provided some $110 million in food, primarily to aid
those starving due to the conflict with rebel factions in the
northern provinces of Eritrea and Figure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
