<FIRST>u a AM-Shoreham-NRC 2ndLd-Writethru a0682 04-20 0871</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shoreham-NRC, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0682,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shoreham Nuclear Power Plant Wins License</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts one graf after 4th graf bgng: Asked if ... to UPDATE
with state, LILCO reax. Edits 5th graf to conform and picks up 6th graf
pvs bgng: The vote ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission awarded
a full-power operating license to the controversial Shoreham
nuclear power plant Thursday in a gesture that may ultimately prove
symbolic.
   The commission voted 4-0 to grant the license, capping years of
hearings that produced reams of testimony and cost millions of
dollars. It is the first U.S. nuclear plant to be licensed on the
basis of a utility-formulated emergency plan, rather than one
created by the state and local governments.
   After the vote, NRC Chairman Lando Zech told reporters that the
commission had fulfilled its duties without regard to the issue of
whether Shoreham would ever achieve full power.
   Asked if he thought it was a waste that the plant might never
operate, Zech said, ``As the chairman of the regulatory commission,
that's not my responsibility. As an American citizen, I would call
it a waste.''
   Richard Kessel, head of the State Consumer Protection Board,
called the license ``virtually meaningless.'' But Joseph McDonnell,
a Long Island Lighting Co. vice president, said the license is a
``prerequisite for establishing a national nuclear policy.''
   LILCO, which owns the 809-megawatt reactor, has agreed not to
bring the plant up to full power pending a vote by shareholders to
scrap the $5.5 billion plant.
   The vote, sometime before June 15, will make or break a deal
under which LILCO would sell Shoreham to New York state for $1 in
exchange for a decade of annual rate increases. The state would
then oversee the decommissioning and dismantling of the plant that
was once touted as the solution to Long Island's energy shortages.
   LILCO was forced to draw up its own emergency evacuation plan
after New York state, Suffolk County and the town of Southampton on
Long Island withdrew support for the plant, contending that the
zone around Shoreham could not be safely evacuated in case of an
accident, given Long Island's large population and the dearth of
roads leading away from the plant.
   The opposition kept Shoreham's bid for a license tied up before
the commission for years, and led the NRC to change its rules in
late 1987 to allow utilities to formulate evacuation plans assuming
state and local governments would cooperate in the event of a true
emergency. The same assumption is also being applied in the case of
the Seabrook, N.H., nuclear plant.
   At a hearing Monday, the NRC staff certified Shoreham safe and
ready to operate. The NRC's director of nuclear reactor regulation
said Long Island's geography, roads, climate and other features did
not ``render emergency planning at Shoreham fundamentally more
difficult than at other sites.''
   Even if the shutdown plan is ratified, Shoreham almost certainly
will not die quietly. Energy Secretary James Watkins has said that
to dismantle Shoreham ``would be utterly irresponsible,'' and the
department says it will try to block transferring Shoreham's
license to the Long Island Power Authority, an entity set up by the
state Legislature to take over the plant.
   Shoreham, located about 90 miles east of New York City, was
conceived in 1965 and completed in 1984, more than 10 years behind
schedule and almost 75 times over its original $75 million budget.
The plant loaded fuel in January 1985 and received a 5 percent
low-power testing license in July 1985.
   LILCO's applications for 25 percent and full-power licenses
stalled before NRC licensing boards and appeal boards as the state
and local governments contested countless aspects of emergency
planning.
   Last year, New York's Legislature formed the Long Island Power
Authority to attempt to take over the plant. LILCO defeated a LIPA
takeover bid last March but New York Gov. Mario Cuomo was
determined to see the plant closed. He negotiated a plan in May
under which LILCO would sell the plant to New York state for $1 in
exchange for guaranteed rate increases of about 70 percent over the
next 10 years. That plan fell apart, however, when the state
Legislature refused to vote on it before a Dec. 1 deadline.
   Later that month, a federal jury found LILCO guilty of
racketeering by lying to the state Public Service Commission in
order to win some $600 million in unjustified rate hikes in the
1970s. The company was faced with paying damages of roughly $1.8
billion, enough to bankrupt it.
   In February, LILCO agreed to a $400 million settlement of the
case _ $390 million to go to ratepayers and $10 million for
attorneys' fees.
   On Feb. 28, Cuomo announced that the state and LILCO had
negotiated a new settlement which did not require the Legislature's
approval. The second deal did not have built-in rate increases, but
the Public Service Commission set the hikes, of up to 5 percent a
year, when it approved the pact last month.
   The shareholders have the final say on the deal to scrap the
plan, and LILCO Chairman William Catacosinos has said the board
will recommend that they accept the deal.
</TEXT>
