<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-20 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms Over Plains, Record Heat In Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms developed with hail and high wind Thursday
over the southern Plains, while temperatures in the Southwest
soared to record highs of as much as 102 degrees.
   Thunderstorms intensified late in the morning over southern
Kansas and northern Oklahoma.
   Hail as big as golf balls covered the ground near Anthony in
south-central Kansas, the National Weather Service said. Smaller
hail was reported in north-central Oklahoma.
   Wind gusted to 51 mph at Dalhart, in the Texas Panhandle, and
visibility was cut by blowing dust before a thunderstorm moved in.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered across Florida,
especially over the southern part of the state. Light rain extended
across eastern sections of the Carolinas and into southern Georgia.
   Elsewhere, showers crossed sections of the upper Mississippi
Valley, and light rain fell along the coastal of the Pacific
Northwest.
   Unseasonably warm weather prevailed over much of the Southwest
with record high temperatures at a number of locations, and
temperatures on the Plains rose as high as 90 as far north as
Nebraska.
   Tucson, Ariz., had its earliest 100-degree reading on record
Wednesday when the temperature reached 101 degrees. On Thursday,
the city rose to a record 102 degrees, its 10th record this month.
   Other record highs Thursday were 77 at Alamosa, Colo., and 81 at
Colorado Springs, Colo. Denver tied its record of 83 and Pueblo,
Colo., tied its record of 90.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 40
degrees at Grand Marais, Minn., to 102 at Tucson, Ariz. Thursday's
low for the 48 contiguous states was 22 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Friday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
across Florida, with showers over the northern and central
Appalachians. Showers and a few thunderstorms also were forecast
from the Pacific Northwest to the northern and central Rockies.
   Highs in the upper 40s and 50s were predicted over the Great
Lakes, New York state and New England; in the 60s along the Pacific
Coast and inland from the Northwest, and along the mid Atlantic
Coast and the central Appalachians; in the 90s over the
northwestrern half of Texas and southern New Mexico; in the 90s to
around 100 in the desert Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s across
most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
