<HEAD>Sailors' Remains Flown To United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Battleship-Explosion, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to add details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROOSEVELT ROADS NAVAL STATION, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy
commander who was aboard the USS Iowa during the explosion inside a
gun turret said Thursday the Navy has imposed a moratorium on
firing 16-inch guns pending an investigation of the disaster.
   Vice Adm. Jerome Johnson, commander of the U.S. 2nd Fleet,
praised his crew for ``their sensitivity and heroic effort'' during
the disaster Wednesday.
   The coffins of the 47 sailors who died in the explosion were
saluted by an honor guard, then carefully loaded each onto a cargo
plane as the dead began their final trip home.
   The sailors' remains were airlifted by helicopter from the Iowa,
anchored offshore from this base on Puerto Rico's eastern coast, to
a temporary morgue in a hangar beside the airstrip. The harbor was
too shallow for the ship to dock at the base.
   From there, each metal coffin was wrapped in a U.S. flag and
then taken by van to the cavernous rear door of the plane. The
camouflaged C-5 Galaxy cargo plane then left for Dover, Del.
   The 47th coffin was met at the rear of the plane by a Navy and
Marine Corps color guard of two men with rifles and three bearing
the U.S., Navy and Marine flags.
   Standing in the 86-degree heat, an eight-man honor guard of
sailors in white dress uniforms saluted each coffin as it arrived,
and then, serving as pallbearers, lifted the coffins into the huge
cargo hold.
    Johnson said the death toll was based on a roll call after the
accident.
   ``There are 47 missing or dead,'' Johnson said. ``We are in the
process of identification of the bodies.'' He said relatives would
be notified before a list was made public.
   He said the accident occurred during the loading of the number
two turret during a routine gun practice Wednesday and the fire was
contained within two hours. He did not estimate the extent of the
dollar damage to turret, but he said the rest of the ship escaped
harm.
   ``I can tell you the fire and explosion was instantaneous.
Because it was instantaneous, we have no other injuries,'' Johnson
said at a Roosevelt Roads news conference.
   Eleven crewmen inside the turret escaped, from a magazine area
at the bottom of the seven-story-high turret, he said.
</TEXT>
