<FIRST>r i AM-BabyFood-Razor     04-20 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Food-Razor,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Razor Blade, Glass Found In Baby Food in Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A piece of razor blade, bits of glass, thumbtacks
and caustic soda have been found in jars of baby food in southern
England, police said Thursday.
   They said the five incidents involved jars of pureed baby food
made by H. J. Heinz Co. and occurred over a nine-day period between
April 7 and 15.
   ``Whoever is responsible must have a very sick mind,'' said a
company spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said Heinz was certain the tampering was taking place outside
its British premises, where it produces 96 million jars of baby
food a year. The company knew of no person or group with a grudge
against it, he added.
   In Oxford, police said a 9-month-old girl chewed on a piece of
razor blade concealed in pear-flavored yogurt and was treated at a
hospital for a cut mouth.
   Inspector David Wise of Thames Valley Police said a warning
stamped on rolled-up plastic tape was found in the bottle but the
police would not reveal the message while the hunt continued for
the perpetrator.
   ``The warning indicated that the contents of the bottle were
contaminated. The chain store where it was bought has withdrawn all
similar bottles from sale and recalled those that were sold,'' Wise
said.
   Police said the first incident was at Rayleigh, east of London,
where a mother found two thumbtacks, caustic soda and a warning
tape in a chicken and vegetable puree. The other finds were on the
south coast, two in Southampton and one in Worthing.
</TEXT>
