<FIRST>r w AM-FarmExports     04-20 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Exports,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator, Budget Office Disagree on Farm Program Suspension</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration says a major
agricultural subsidy called the Export Enhancement Program has not
been suspended, but a farm state senator said Thursday that's not
how it appears to him.
   ``We maintain that a suspension is in place,'' said Sen. Robert
Kerrey, D-Neb., in a letter to the Office of Management and Budget.
   He said that while a new wheat initiative under the program is
pending at the budget office, officials there have instructed the
Department of Agriculture not to send them completed documents
proposing sales under the program for other commodities such as
vegetable oil, rice and broilers, until the administration
completes a broad review.
   A spokeswoman at the budget office said the program has not been
suspended and that two applications have been processed this year.
The spokeswoman, who spoke only on condition she not be quoted by
name, said she did not know how many applications were awaiting
processing.
   She said a meeting would be held in about two weeks to review
the effectiveness of the program.
   The Export Enhancement Program subsidizes U.S. commodity sales
overseas to make them less expensive for foreign buyers.
   Kerrey said Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter gave
assurances that it was not suspended while it underwent a general
review.
   Kerrey called the program ``perhaps the single most effective
tool for securing progress in trade negotiations'' and urged Budget
Director Richard Darman to ``end the EEP suspension now in place.''
   Earlier in the week, Thomas O. Kay, administrator of the U.S.
Foreign Agricultural Service, told a Senate subcommittee that the
program was no longer ``budget neutral'' and that the budget office
had ordered it suspended.
   ``All that is at issue at the moment is any future allocations
that might be made'' under the program, Yeutter said earlier this
week. Those will be considered on a case-by-case basis ``primarily
because of our stocks (of grain) condition and the weather
conditions that now prevail.''
</TEXT>
