<FIRST>r w AM-AircraftGrounding     04-20 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aircraft Grounding,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subsonic Planes Grounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force Logistics Command has
temporarily grounded its fleet of subsonic, single-engine attack
aircraft, citing small cracks found in the trailing edges of wings,
the Pentagon said Thursday.
   The fleet of 365 A-7D and K model aircraft used by the Air Force
and Air National Guard will be restricted until an inspection of
the wing area is completed, the Defense Department said in a
statement.
   The cracks were discovered during routine maintenance by the Air
Force Air National Guard, the statement said.
   The A-7 Corsair II was originally designed for the U.S. Navy.
The A-7D model of the aircraft, designed for the Air Force
primarily for an air-to-surface attack role, has been in service
since December 1968. Production ended in December 1976.
   The A-7K model, a two-seat version of the A-7D, has been used in
combat operations and training.
</TEXT>
