<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 2101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CatastrophicCare     04-20 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catastrophic Care,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Revised Estimate Suggests More Money Being Collected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A revised congressional estimate suggests the
government may be collecting more in taxes than had been previously
projected in Medicare's program to cover catastrophic illnesses,
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen said Thursday.
   The Texas Democrat, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee,
wrote to Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady to ask whether the
Treasury Department agrees with revised estimates by the
Congressional Budget Office and legislative tax staff experts that
the government will have $4.9 billion available in excess funds in
1989-93.
   ``The Congressional Budget Office concludes that the surplus in
the catastrophic care funds is twice as large as originally
estimated; two times bigger than needed to provide adequate reserve
and contingency margins,'' Bentsen told reporters.
   ``According to preliminary estimates this would mean a cut of at
least 16 percent in the supplemental premium revenue'' could be
made, said Bentsen.
   The law requires everyone eligible for Medicare who pays at
least $150 a year in federal income taxes to pay an extra premium
based on that tax liability, with the maximum such supplemental
premium this year of $800 per beneficiary _ or $1,600 per couple,
if both spouses are eligible for Medicare.
   Bentsen's letter suggested that the cap on the supplemental
premium could be reduced to $500 for this year if the revenue
estimates are correct.
   Lawmakers have been flooded with mail from the elderly
protesting the tax paid by beneficiaries. Bentsen said that ``it
was never our intention that the beneficiaries pay more than needed
to operate this program in a prudent, responsible fashion.''
   ``This could be potentially good news for Medicare beneficiaries
particularly for those paying the supplemental premium,'' said
Horace Deets, executive director of the American Association for
Retired Persons.
   ``AARP always believed that the benefits in the catastrophic
health care law were important to older Americans. We're even more
delighted to hear that beneficiaries may pay less for the expanded
Medicare coverage,'' Deets added.
   ``There are two reasons for us to interpret this as
encouraging,'' said Eric Shulman, legislative director for the
National Council of Senior Citizens.
   ``One is that hopefully this new revenue will yield tangible and
significant reduction in premiums. The other is that it may open
the door to some reconsideration of the financing mechanism,'' said
Shulman.
</TEXT>
