<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     04-20 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Government Contributes Indelible Ink for Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government on Thursday
donated 11,000 bottles of purple ink to be used to prevent voters
from casting more than one ballot in national elections set for May
1.
   The donation, made through the Agency for International
Development, followed a request from the Paraguayan government.
Opposition politicians had cited widespread election irregularities
during the 34-year rule of Gen. Alfredo Stroessner.
   In February 1988, when Stroessner was elected to his eighth
presidential term, the number of votes in favor of the ruling
Colorado Party exceeded the number of registered voters in 39 of
220 districts.
   The May 1 presidential and congressional elections are the first
since Stroessner was toppled in a coup Feb. 3 by Gen. Andres
Rodriguez.
   ``This is a donation from the government of the United States
for the benefit of national democracy,'' said Electoral Board
president Expedito Rojas at a ceremony attended by representatives
from seven of the eight parties participating in the election.
   The purple dye lasts on the finger for several days. The 11,000
bottles are enough to mark 4 million people. Another shipment was
expected later this week.
   The donation represents part of ``the continued commitment of
the goverment to encourage and contribute to democracy in
Paraguay,'' a statement from the U.S. Embassy said.
</TEXT>
