<FIRST>r i AM-India-Sikhs     04-20 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Sikhs,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Militants Kill 15, Booby Trap Bodies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants disguised as policemen
killed five people and booby-trapped two of the bodies with
explosives, seriously injuring a villager who tried to identify the
corpses, police said Thursday.
   The police said about 10 extremists, dressed as policemen,
killed two Sikhs and three Hindus Wednesday near the village of
Saeed Kuliyan in Punjab state. The village is 125 miles west of
Chandigarh, the state capital.
   Explosives planted under two of the bodies went off when a
villager, Darshan Singh, turned the corpses over, police said. The
booby trap was apparently meant for policemen, said police
officials in Chandigarh, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Two senior police officials who had accompanied Darshan Singh
were unhurt, police said. The villager was hospitalized with
critical facial injuries, they said.
   Sikh militants are known to kill fellow Sikhs who do not support
their quest for a separate homeland in the rich farming state of
Punjab.
   Meanwhile, news reports said 10 other people were killed
elsewhere in the state since Wednesday.
   Extremists armed with Chinese-made assault rifles shot and
killed five Sikhs in the Amritsar district, Press Trust of India
news agency said.
   It quoted a senior police official, S.P. Singh, as saying that
the killings were a result of rivalry between two groups of
extremists.
   PTI said five more people were killed in other parts of the
state by the extremists.
   The latest deaths raised to 577 the number of people killed in
the state since the beginning of the year by the militants. The
extremists were blamed for more than 2,400 killings in the state
last year.
   Sikhs comprise 2 percent of India's 880 million people but are
in a slight majority in Punjab. Sikh militants launched their
separatist campaign in 1982, alleging discrimination by the
country's Hindu majority, who make up 80 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
