<FIRST>r a AM-MissingGirl     04-20 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Girl,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missing Girl, 12, Says She Spent Month in Dark, Unheated Storeroom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old girl missing for more than a
month told her parents and authorities she had been living in a
dark, unheated storeroom at the urging of her 16-year-old boyfriend.
   Amanda Wells was listed in good condition Thursday at St.
Joseph's Hospital, where she was taken Wednesday suffering from
malnutrition and dehydration. The girl told police she ate only a
peanut butter sandwich every other day while living in the
storeroom of her boyfriend's apartment building.
   Kenneth Wells said his daughter, who ran away from home March
17, dropped from 125 pounds to about 106 pounds during the 33-day
ordeal. Her body temperature was 95 degrees when she turned herself
in early Wednesday. Normal body temperature is 98.6 degrees.
   Authorities charged the girl's boyfriend, Jerry E. Leonard Jr.,
with first-degree custodial interference, a felony, and endangering
the welfare of a child, a misdemeanor. City Judge Jeffrey R.
Merrill entered an innocent plea on Leonard's behalf and released
him to Onondaga County's pretrial release program.
   Amanda ran away from home after her parents said they wanted her
to stop dating Leonard because of his age. The two began dating
when they were 15 and 11, the girl said in an affidavit to police.
   ``I would go and see him behind their backs. We were in love
with each other, and we both wanted to keep dating,'' she told
police.
   The girl said every other day she would eat a peanut butter
sandwich her boyfriend brought her. She showered twice during the
period, when Leonard's father was not home. She slept between two
upright mattresses and went to the bathroom in a jar.
   The girl said her boyfriend told her that if police found her
she would end up in a detention center until she was 18 and he
would be in jail for the rest of his life.
   ``I was scared of what he told me, so I made sure I didn't get
caught,'' she said in the affidavit. ``After a month of sleeping in
the storeroom and being hungry because I had little food, I finally
left and went home.
   ``I figured whatever the police did to me, it couldn't be any
worse than what Jerry is doing to me,'' she said.
</TEXT>
