<HEAD>Three Deaths Reported In Clashes Between Opposition, Authorities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators protesting what
they call the fraudulent re-election of President Didier Ratsiraka
fought with police in clashes that left three people dead and about
60 injured, news reports said.
   The French news agency Agence France-Presse said the violence
broke out Wednesday afternoon after a rally called by an opposition
coalition.
   It said several hundred demonstrators, mostly young, burned
vehicles and looted stores in the center of Antananarivo, the
capital of the Indian Ocean island nation. The agency quoted
informed sources as saying young children were among the injured.
It said authorities gave no indication how many people were
arrested.
   The report cited what it called a provisional official count of
the casualties. The count could not immediately be confirmed.
   In a previous round of clashes following an opposition rally
Sunday, the government-controlled radio said 13 people were hurt,
including three policemen, and 20 people were arrested.
   Ratsiraka, chosen by the military to rule in 1975, was
re-elected to a third seven-year term on March 12 with about 62
percent of the vote. The three opposition parties challenged the
outcome in the island nation's Supreme Court, saying the voting was
rigged.
   The opposition leaders are proposing formation of a provisional
government, including representatives of the military, students and
churches, to rule while new elections are prepared.
   Ceremonies marking the beginning of Ratsiraka's third term were
scheduled later Thursday.
