<FIRST>u a AM-Battleship-Families 1stLd-Writethru a0663 04-20 0831</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Battleship-Families, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0663,0853</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Chaplins Inform Iowa Victims' Families</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9, `The parents ..., with 9 grafs to UPDATE with
comments from other families. Picks up 10 graf: `About 250 ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NK1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teams of Navy chaplains and officers went
from father and mother to wife to sister or brother Thursday, 47
times over, to break the news about who was killed aboard the USS
Iowa.
   ``It's the hardest thing we do,'' said Cmdr. Doug Palmer, acting
base chaplain for the sprawling Norfolk Naval Base that is home
port for the stricken battleship.
   ``I've done it many times and I'll never get used to it,'' said
Palmer, who supervised 52 chaplains called into duty Wednesday
after a powerful explosion ripped through a gun turret on the Iowa
during training exercises near Puerto Rico.
   Navy policy is for each family that loses someone on sea duty to
be visited by a chaplain and a Navy officer who offer assistance
and counseling.
   Jack E. Thompson Sr. was told about the death of his 22-year-old
son, Jack Jr., by Navy representatives in Greeneville, Tenn., where
the young man had been a star football tackle in high school.
   ``He came to me after he graduated from high school and said,
`Daddy, I'd only go to college to play ball,' '' Thompson recalled.
``I told him if that's the only reason, he should go to the Navy.
That makes me feel a little bad.''
   ``He enjoyed the travel. He'd been everywhere _ Italy, France,
Norway, Germany, England, the Persian Gulf,'' said his wife, Leasa.
But she said her husband was an outdoorsman who looked forward to
getting out of the Navy and building a log cabin in Tennessee.
   Dellar Romine said the grim news of her son, Harold Earl Romine
Jr., 19, came with a knock on the door of her Bradenton, Fla., home
early Thursday morning.
   ``About the time I woke up, this knock came at the door,'' she
said. ``I just knew that was it.''
   The parents of Ernest Hanyecz, 27, of Bordentown, N.J., said
they stayed up all night trying fruitlessly to get information from
the Navy about their son's death before an official called them
Thursday morning.
   ``As long as they play their war games, there will be more
deaths and innocent people will die,'' said Ernest Hanyecz Sr., who
said his son joined the Navy 10 years ago at age 17.
   Relatives of another victim, Stephen J. Welden, 23, of Oklahoma
City, said his posting to a battleship had been almost a lifelong
dream.
   ``He had served four years in the Navy and had signed up for
another four years on condition he serve on the Iowa,'' said
Welden's younger brother, Bill, 22.
   ``He was very happy,'' said Welden's mother, Mary. ``He loved
what he was doing. He was where he wanted to be.''
   Scott A. Holt, 20, of Terre Haute, Ind., had telephoned his
grandparents, Keith and June Woodsmall of Riley, last week, just
before the Iowa set sail for the training exercise.
   ``He said they were going to leave port tomorrow morning and go
down to Puerto Rico and shoot the big guns,'' said Mrs. Woodsmall.
   About 250 relatives of Iowa crewmen spent the night in a
gymnasium on the base, but most left after the fatality
notifications were completed about 3 a.m., said Lt. Cmdr. Mike
Todd, a base spokesman.
   Rear Adm. Jimmy Pappas, the base commander, said those who found
out a family crewman survived were ``overjoyed with tears.''
   Family members of the dead were called aside individually and
told, he said.
   ``It's the greatest tragedy any of us can suffer,'' Pappas said.
``It's the most difficult thing you have to do'' to tell someone
that a loved one has been killed.
   Palmer said he knew of no complaints by families over the time
it takes to notify relatives. But occasional outbursts are natural
in such stressful situations, he said.
   ``The people come in and they don't know, `Am I the unlucky
one?''' he said.
   A memorial service for the victims will be conducted Monday on
the base. Pappas said the dead included one officer and 46 enlisted
personnel and that most of the victims were single and from 18 to
22 years old.
   Hundreds of people called the base's family services office to
volunteer food, money, child care, Palmer said.
   Pappas said even the Internal Revenue Service called to help
with expedited tax refunds or waivers of scheduled audits.
   He said the tragedy would have an emotional impact on the base,
but other sailors ``know they've got to go on and do their jobs.''
   Liz Hengerer, whose husband serves aboard a submarine and who
takes part in the family support program, said Navy families stick
together in times of crisis.
   ``You know that your husbands go to sea. ... I don't know how I
would react,'' said Mrs. Hengerer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
