<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0605,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Blasts Army For High Death Toll, School Closures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `The U.N....' to restore dropped word. Pickup
7th pvs, `Under army...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. relief officials Thursday demanded that
Israel stop using gunfire to quell Palestinian protests, and Moslem
clerics urged Palestinians to defy Israeli restrictions on worship
at Jerusalem's Al Aqsa Mosque.
   In the Gaza Strip, at least 16 Palestinians were reported
wounded in stone-throwing clashes with troops.
   The U.N. Relief and Works Agency, which aids Palestinian
refugees, said 13 Palestinians, six of them younger than 15, were
shot to death by Israeli troops in the past week.
   ``We deplore this loss of life and call for a halt to the use of
lethal firepower against civilians, young and old,'' the agency
said in a statement issued in Vienna and distributed in Jerusalem.
   An army spokeswoman defended the troops, saying ``they do
everything in their power to avoid deaths.'' She said every
Palestinian death is being investigated by a senior officer.
   The U.N. agency criticism came the same day the U.N. General
Assembly voted 129-2 to condemn Israel for alleged human rights
abuses and demand it halt excessive gunfire and restrictions on
worship. The United States and Israel voted against the non-binding
resolution, and Liberia abstained.
   Under army policy, troops may fire live ammunition only when
their lives are in danger. Plastic bullets, which can be fatal when
fired from a range of less than 70 yards, may be used to break up
violent protests or stop fleeing inciters.
   At least 439 Palestinians have been killed since the December
1987 start of the uprising, most by army gunfire, according to a
count by The Associated Press. Eighteen Israelis have also died.
   The U.N. agency on Thursday put the Palestinian death toll at
442, and said nearly 25,000 have been wounded by army gunfire.
   It also protested the prolonged closure of the West Bank's 1,200
schools, including 90 run by the U.N. agency.
   The military government has kept schools closed for most of the
uprising, saying they are flashpoints of anti-Israeli violence. The
latest military order extended school closures until May 19.
   ``If they (schools) cannot reopen before the end of next month
and are not allowed to remain open through the summer months, a
whole school year will be lost,'' the U.N. agency said.
   A military government official said no date has been set for
reopening schools, calling the situation too tense for such a move.
Palestinians have alleged the school closures are a form of
punishment.
   In Jerusalem, Al Aqsa preacher Sheikh Mohammed Al Jamal called
on Moslems in the occupied territories to attend Friday noon
prayers at the mosque to challenge the Israeli restrictions.
   The police order was enacted after Palestinians stoned police in
the mosque compound following prayers on April 7, the first Friday
of the Moslem holy month of Ramadan.
   On April 14, police turned away most West Bank and Gaza Strip
Palestinians trying to reach the mosque compound, known as Haram Al
Sharif, the third holiest site of Islam after Mecca and Medina in
Saudi Arabia.
   ``We call on Moslems to perform Friday prayers at Al Aqsa
Mosque,'' Al Jamal told reporters.
   ``If the Israeli authorities prevent Moslems from entering the
mosque, they are to pray in the Old City of Jerusalem. If they are
barred from entering the city, they are to pray on the roads
leading to Jerusalem,'' he said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, the army shot and wounded 12
Palestinians during stone-throwing clashes in the Khan Yunis
refugee camp, an army official said. Arab doctors only confirmed
three casualties in the camp.
   The reason for the discrepancy was not clear. Usually, Arab
casualty reports exceed the figures confirmed by the army.
   Arab hospital officials said four other Palestinians were
wounded in clashes in the village of Beit Hanoun, the town of
Rafah, and the Nuseirat and Shati refugee camps. The army said it
was checking the report.
</TEXT>
