<FIRST>r w AM-Hastings     04-20 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hastings Hearings Set for July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators plan to start hearing evidence
against U.S. District Court Judge Alcee L. Hastings on July 10, a
special committee formed for his impeachment trial said Thursday.
   The panel made the decision in a closed-doors meeting Wednesday.
   In the meeting, the committee headed by Sen. Jeff Bingaman,
D-N.M., also set Aug. 4 as a target date for wrapping up the
presentation of evidence, according to spokesman Tony Harvey.
   Harvey said the committee decided to defer any decision on a
request from Hastings attorney Terence Anderson of Miami for
$200,000 in expenses from the government and an unspecified amount
in fees to conduct the defense of the 52-year-old judge.
   Hastings, of Miami, was named in 17 articles of impeachment
approved by the House 413-3 on Aug. 3. The document accuses him of
plotting to obtain a payoff and improperly disclosing secret
wiretap information.
   The Senate must now decide whether to convict Hastings and thus
remove him from office and stop his $89,500 annual salary.
   The committee's proceedings will be carried on Senate television
and also videotaped for viewing later by lawmakers who are not on
the 12-member panel.
   The committee will not issue any recommendation on whether to
convict Hastings but merely a report on the evidence against him.
The final decision on whether to remove him from the bench will be
made by the whole Senate.
   The impeachment trial before the Senate is not the same thing as
a criminal trial and the worst that can befall Hastings if
convicted is removal from office.
   A federal court jury acquitted him of the bribe conspiracy at a
1983 trial. But his alleged coconspirator, Washington attorney
William Borders, was convicted at a separate trial and sent to
prison.
   Harvey described the committee's target date of Aug. 4 as ``a
very firm goal and objective'' but acknowledged that the panel was
not absolutely bound to stick by it under any circumstances.
   A witness list submitted to the committee indicated the Hastings
camp plans to call more than 108 persons, including former Attorney
General Griffin Bell as well as an assortment of FBI agents,
alleged organized crime figures, political operatives and others.
</TEXT>
