<FIRST>r i AM-Guadeloupe-Protests     04-20 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guadeloupe-Protests,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Police and Pro-Independence Protesters Clash in Guadeloupe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIETTE SAINTON</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   POINTE-A-PITRE, Guadeloupe (AP) _ Police clashed with several
hundred demonstrators Thursday in the north coast town of Port
Louis over the arrests of seven pro-independence activists in this
French Caribbean island.
   The demonstrators set up huge roadblocks across the main roads
leading to and from the town. Although the violent clashes had
ceased by noon, banks, schools, stores and all government offices
remained closed.
   The political unrest began following the arrests Tuesday of
seven pro-independence activists or supporters of the tiny Popular
Union for the Liberation of Guadeloupe.
   The seven are charged with bomb attacks in January 1988 on a
bank and the homes of five French European residents, including a
lawyer, a doctor and an army officer.
   Among those arrested was Jean Barfleur, a prominent member of
the Popular Union and a member of the town's city council.
   The group said in a statement broadcast by radio stations
Wednesday that the arrests are a ``new maneuver by the French
government to repress the freedom of the independence movement.''
   Police did not say how long the seven would be detained or
exactly what they were charged with.
   A police statement said the arrests were ``closely connected''
to the creation of a new ``revolutionary organization'' based in
Port Louis, one of the few towns in this island of 340,000 where a
large number of people support independence from France.
   Police gave no details on the alleged organization.
   One of the alleged bombers is still at large, but local news
reports say he can be identified because he lost two fingers in the
explosion in front of one of the bombing targets. The fingers
allegedly were recovered by the police.
   A number of unions and organizations, including the Guadeloupean
Communist Party, have denounced the arrests.
</TEXT>
