<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 2257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brite     04-20 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brite,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Savannah Police Department's horse
patrol helps sweep crime from the streets, but the
tourism-conscious city realizes the animals leave something behind
that itself must be swept up.
   So police have developed a plan of action for when one of their
steeds heeds nature's call.
   ``We're not going to let the city become unsightly,'' said Lt.
Mickey Browne, commander of the traffic unit, which includes the
horse patrol.
   At the first sign of trouble, Browne said, the mounted officer
is to radio his location to a police traffic unit. The traffic
officer then picks up a community-service worker, one of the
misdemeanor offenders assigned to pick up litter downtown, and
takes him to the scene.
   To make the process even more efficient, Browne said, police are
trying to time the horses' digestive cycles to determine when
cleanup is more likely to be needed.
</TEXT>
