<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Chess     04-20 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Chess,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ljubojevic, Kasparov Tie First, Kasparov Defeats Spassky in Final
Game</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World chess champion Garri Kasparov and
Yugoslav Grandmaster Ljubomir Ljubojevic tied for first place in
the fourth Chess World Cup tournament Thursday when Kasparov
defeated former world champion Boris Spassky in the final round.
   Kasparov, 26, and Ljubojevic, 38, each finished with 11 points
out of a possible 16. Soviet Grandmaster Valery Salov came in third
with 10 points, and Viktor Korchnoi, a Soviet defector who now
plays for Switzerland, came in fourth 9{ points.
   The world cup, a series of six tournaments staged over two years
and featuring a total prize fund of $1.2 million, is widely
regarded as the second most important chess event after the world
championship.
   Ljubojevic, who went into the final round a half point ahead of
Kasparov, agreed to a rapid 10-move draw with British Grandmaster
Nigel Short.
   This enabled Kasparov to tie for first with a win over Spassky.
   For 7{ years, Kasparov has won or tied for first place in every
chess event in which he has participated. If Ljubojevic had won his
final game, Kasparov's run would have been broken.
   ``I'm very pleased with my game today, but I think Nigel was a
little impolite because he didn't play,'' Kasparov said moments
after his victory.
   Kasparov had expected Short, who had the advantage of the white
pieces, to play for a win against Ljubojevic.
   With his victory, Kasparov remains within striking distance of
Bobby Fischer's record as the highest-ranked player in history.
   Tournament organizers said the winners each would earn $17,500.
   They said Kasparov, who has better tiebreakers, would receive
the trophy for first place in the tournament, but Ljubojevic will
finish a half-point ahead of Kasparov in the world cup calculations.
   This is because one of the competitors, Spanish Grandmaster
Miguel Illescas, is playing as a representative of the host nation
and is not one of the 25 top grandmasters eligible for the world
cup.
   Results against Illescas are removed from the standings before
the world cup calculations are made. Kasparov, who defeated
Illescas in the 16th round, will have a point removed from his
score in the world cup standings, while Ljubojevic, who drew with
Illescas in the eight round, will only drop half a point.
   Kasparov won the second and third tournaments, held last year in
Belfort, France and Reykjavik, Iceland, and currently is leading
the series. Former world champion Anatoly Karpov, who won the first
event in Brussels, is close behind in second place.
   It is not clear if this result will affect Kasparov's final
world cup placing. Each grandmaster plays in four of the six
competitions, but only their best three results will be counted.
   The fifth tournament in the series will be staged in the Dutch
port city of Rotterdam in June. The final event, featuring a
Kasparov-Karpov clash is scheduled for August, in Skelleftea,
northern Sweden.
   Many of Thursday's other games were agreed drawn quickly by
grandmasters exhausted by three weeks of top-flight competition.
   Korchnoi, playing with the advntage of the white pieces, agreed
to a draw with Salov after only 10 moves, while the game between
British Grandmaster Jonathan Speelman and Johann Hjartarson of
Iceland was drawn in 15 moves.
   Short and Robert Huebner of West Germany finished in a tie for
fifth place with nine points. Huebner and Alexander Belyavsky of
the Soviet Union battled for six hours before finally agreeing to a
draw.
   Predrag Nikolic of Yugoslavia drew his game with Soviet
Grandmaster Artur Yusupov and finished eighth among the seventeen
competitors with eight points out of 16.
</TEXT>
