<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 2306EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StreetGangs     04-20 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Street Gangs,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warning To Street Gangs Issued Under New Street Terrorism Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police handed citations to thousands of gang
members Thursday, branding them members of criminal organizations
in the first step of enforcing a new law aimed against street
terrorism.
   ``Up until this law, it was not a crime to belong to the Crips,
it was not a crime to belong to the Bloods, or any of these other
criminal Hispanic street gangs,'' District Attorney Ira Reiner said
at a news conference.
   What's illegal, Reiner said, is doing anything to help pursue
the gang's criminal objectives.
   ``If you belong to one of these gangs, and you know what they're
about, and that's easy enough to prove, and you do any act in
furtherance of their criminal activity, then you have committed a
felony by virtue of your membership in that gang,'' Reiner said.
   For example, the law allows the prosecution of a cited gang
member who only lends a car that is used in a drive-by shooting,
because he has been formally told the gang is a criminal street
gang.
   Gang violence claimed more than 350 lives across the nation's
most populous county last year. Many victims are innocent
bystanders caught in the crossfire.
   ``You are hereby notified that the Venice Shoreline Crips Gang
is a criminal street gang,'' read a sample citation shown to
reporters. Those served with the notice printed in English and
Spanish are asked to sign a receipt.
   Officials said the notices should be easy to serve because of
gang members' high visibility on their home turf, law officers'
familiarity with them, and the gang ethic which forbids them from
denying membership in their ``set.''
   Reiner was joined at the news conference by City Attorney James
Hahn, whose office also will be able to enforce the law as
misdemeanor offense.
   His office previously filed a civil lawsuit against the Playboy
Gangster Crips, claiming they were a nuisance. But that action only
brought short jail stays through contempt of court actions until
legal challenges defeated it.
   Reiner acknowledged that the California Street Terrorism
Enforcement and Prevention Act will be subject to legal challenges
and won't cure the region's gang problem.
   The new law took effect Jan. 1, but the Los Angeles County
Sheriff's office and police from Los Angeles, Compton, Long Beach,
Pomona and Pasadena reviewed the targeted gangs to make sure they
met the law's criteria.
   The departments had prepared 3,700 notices for Thursday. Those
being served include ``a mixture of various offshoots of the
Bloods, Crips, and Hispanic street gangs, the dirtiest gangs in the
area,'' said district attorney office spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons.
   Under the law, the gang has to consist of three or more members
and engaged in at least two or more crimes enumerated in the law:
assault with a deadly weapon, robbery, homicide or manslaughter,
sale or possession of narcotics and controlled substances, shooting
in an inhabited dwelling or vehicle, arson, or witness intimidation.
   Reiner said the law was written to avoid the pitfall of previous
efforts to link relationships with undesirable characters as
criminal activities, known as status offender laws, which were
struck down by the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Prosecutors will have to show that defendants were active gang
members, that they knew of the gang's criminal activity and engaged
in an act that furthered that activity _ all of which keep the law
a constitutional distance from guilt by association, Reiner claimed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
