<FIRST>r a AM-Brown-HoaxFight     04-20 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brown-Hoax Fight,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown University Gunfight Play Too Real For Restaurant Patrons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trembling man entered a restaurant,
sat across from another man and began arguing. He pulled a pistol
and talked about his brother's hospitalization, drugs, money and
the police.
   The argument _ which nearly ended in a shootout _ was just a
play. But a patron at Louie's restaurant was not amused.
   The first performance of ``Jokereye,'' a play by Brown
University junior Craig Picone, almost started a real fight
Saturday when a Louie's patron who also is a Brown student _
realized the confrontation was a hoax and angrily confronted the
actors and director.
   Dave Ronick, miffed by the performance, said although the
theater group posted notices in Louie's windows, they failed to
indicate the time and ``certainly didn't say anything about the use
of guns in Louie's.''
   ``I directed it with realism in mind,'' said Jason Neulander, a
Brown sophomore.
   He said he decided to move it off the traditional stage after a
customer listened to the actors reading the play in Louie's and
said it sounded real.
   The play involves two armed men, Phil and Jimmy, arguing about a
drug exchange, and the waitress who serves them in a restaurant.
The actors borrowed real guns from the Brown theater department _ a
.22-caliber handgun and a .357-caliber Magnum.
   ``I wanted to see, with an unknowing audience, what happened and
how they would react,'' Neulander said.
   Ronick and a friend had briefly contemplated grabbing for the
guns and other options before a waitress told them what was going
on. Ronick said a lot of people were stunned and the use of guns in
public infuriated him.
   An English major, Ronick followed the two actors out of Louie's
and told them what he thought of their performance. He later
grabbed the director by the shirt collar.
   ``If you were in New York, you would have gotten shot,'' Ronick,
a New Yorker, told them.
   The actors were ``totally freaked out,'' said Neulander, who was
inside Louie's paying the bill when the confrontation occurred.
   The actors had anticipated anger, Neulander said. They wanted
the audience to become part of the play, to break the wall between
players and spectators, he said.
   But, he said, the actors weren't ready for a response directed
at them personally.
   ``It was poor judgment on their part,'' said Providence police
Commander Richard S. Tamburini.``It could have led to a tragedy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
