<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     04-20 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka Militants Kill Family of Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers thought to be Sinhalese
militants beheaded four members of a Sinhalese family and stabbed a
fifth to death because one was a suspected police informer,
military officials said Thursday.
   The officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said the bodies were found Thursday at Kottegoda village, about 65
miles east of Colombo, with a note beside them saying one was an
informer.
   Police said four other bodies were found in neighboring
Kamburupittiya village. The bodies, as yet unidentified, had
gunshot wounds, police said.
   It was not known if the incidents were connected.
   The violence came as state-run television repeated President
Ranasinghe Premadasa's longstanding amnesty offer to militants on
both sides who surrender.
   Sinhalese extremists began their anti-government campaign in
July 1987 to protest a government peace plan with the Tamils, who
are fighting for an independent state on the island's north and
east.
   The Sinhalese complain too much is conceded to the Tamils, who
form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. Tamils claim they
are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent
of the population.
   India sponsored the plan and later sent in troops to enforce an
arms surrender by the Tamil insurgents because of the sympathies of
its own 60 million Tamils to the rebel cause.
   The more radical Tamil groups continued their separatist fight,
begun in 1983.
   At least 12,600 people have died in the separatist campaign and
the Sinhalese backlash.
</TEXT>
