<DOCNO> AP890420-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 2254EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SovietEarthquake     04-20 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Earthquake,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Damage Reported Following Soviet Quake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake measuring 6.5 on the Richter
scale shook the Stanovoy Mountains in eastern Soviet Union on
Thursday, according to the U.S. Geological Survey.
   There were no reports of damage or casualties from the
earthquake, recorded at 5 p.m. (MDT). It was the strongest reported
in the the southeastern Siberian mountains since a quake measuring
6.6 was recorded Jan. 18, 1967.
   The Richter scale measures ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Each increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage,
6 severe damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of
widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of
tremendous damage.
   The San Francisco earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the
Richter scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on the Richter
scale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
