<DOCNO> AP890420-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 0124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-StateDepartment-Bias     04-20 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Department-Bias,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Department Admits Discriminating Against Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has admitted to female
Foreign Service officers that it discriminated against women and
they may be eligible for court-ordered relief, The Washington Post
reported.
   The admission was part of a notice sent to diplomatic posts
worldwide and posted at State Department headquarters as the latest
step in a long legal process, the newspaper reported in its
Thursday editions.
   In addition, the State Department has canceled the 1989 Foreign
Service examination, department officials said Wednesday night.
   The admission to female officials arose from a suit filed in
1976 by Alison Palmer, a now-retired Foreign Serivce officer who
claimed the department discriminated against women in hiring and
promotion.
   The State Department had won in a lower court but was reversed
three months ago by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia. The State Department is planning to appeal that decision,
the Post said.
   In the meantime, the State Department has been proceeding with a
detailed plan to notify female employees of discrimination between
1976 and 1985, the newspaper reported.
   Men got better career assignments and were generally given more
high-profile opportunities to advance their careers, according to
the notices cited by the Post.
</TEXT>
