<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-RuthBerle     04-20 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Ruth Berle,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruth Berle, Wife of Milton Berle, Dead at 67</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television pioneer Milton Berle's wife, Ruth,
who was active in Democratic politics and philanthropic causes, had
died at age 67.
   Mrs. Berle, who suffered from cancer, died Tuesday night at
Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, said her husband's publicist, Tim
Scerba.
   Her husband, known affectionately as ``Mr. Television,''
credited her with being the stabilizing influence in his life.
   ``Ruth has settled me down,'' the actor-comedian once said. ``I
call her Rocky _ my rock of Gibraltar.''
   The couple met in 1951 and were married two years later. They
adopted a son, Bill.
   Berle, 80, starred in such landmark television shows as ``Texaco
Star Theater,'' and ``The Milton Berle Show,'' and has appeared in
a number of films.
   Mrs. Berle was involved in many philanthropic causes in Los
Angeles, including S.H.A.R.E., an organization dedicated to aiding
mentally handicapped children.
   She was active in the Democratic Party and was a California
delegate to the 1968 Democratic National Convention that nominated
Hubert Humphrey for president.
   She was born in Portland, Maine, and was reared in Paterson, N.J.
   A veteran of World War II, she served in the Women's Army Corps,
rising to the rank of captain and company commander by the war's
end.
   She began working in public relations in New York in the 1940s,
doing work for such motion picture studios as Samuel Goldwyn
Productions, United Artists, and RKO.
   Besides her husband and son, she is survived by her mother,
brother, sister-in-law, stepdaughter Vicki Walton and two
stepgrandsons.
   The family planned a private burial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
