<FIRST>a a AM-BristolBay-Fishing Adv24   04-20 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bristol Bay-Fishing, Adv 24,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, April 24, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fishing Only Reason Bristol Bay Villages Cling to Edge of Bering
Sea</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Spill-Bristol Bay</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DILLINGHAM, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Today the small villages clinging to
the edge of the Bering Sea are springing to life with anticipation:
it's almost salmon season again, the high point of the year.
   Everything in Ekuk and Chignik, Aleknagik and Igiugig, and the
other 26 tiny settlements scattered around Bristol Bay takes on a
sense of urgency as Aleuts, Indians, Eskimos, and whites prepare
for the commercial fishing season.
   Mending nets, checking engines, painting hulls _ men, women, and
children whose entire annual income depends on their success on the
sea are now scrambling to be ready for that momentous day when the
salmon run.
   ``You forget everything else until after fishing season,'' said
Dillingham Mayor Joe McGill, a commercial fisherman in Bristol Bay
since 1947. ``That's all that matters. Dillingham goes from a
sleepy little town to a crazy metropolis.''
   The blazing summer Arctic sun now rises higher in the sky,
melting the bay's icepack and hundreds of inches of snow on boats
in the storage yard. This town of 1,570 becomes a hub for boat
repair, transportation, and speculation about the season ahead.
   Wills they had money.''
   The series also stars Bernard Hepton as a man whose life is
ruined when Gorse seduces his lady friend; Rosemary Leach as his
girlfriend; Fiona Fullerton as a wealthy debutante; Abigail McKern
as the daughter of a wealthy automobile dealer, and Judy Parfitt as
a war widow.
   Havers is best-known for his feature film roles, but he also
appears on television in his native England.
   His most recent movie is ``Farewell to the Kind,'' which
co-stars Nick Nolte. He also starred in ``Chariots of Fire,'' ``The
Whistle Blower,'' ``Empire of the Sun,'' ``A Passage to India'' and
``Burke and Willis.''
   Prior to coming here, he had completed a TV miniseries in
Australia called ``Naked Under the Sun.'' He was returning to
England to star in another series, ``The Long-Haired Boy,'' as a
World War II fighter pilot. Other TV roles include ``Nancy Astor,''
``Edward, the King,'' ``Churchill: The Wilderness Years,'' ``Death
of the Heart,'' and the Noel Coward ``Star Quality'' series.
   Havers is also planning a documentary on the Whirling Dervishes,
a mystical Islamic order found chiefly in Turkey. They picked up
their name because they whirl and dance to the music of a reed pipe
as part of their worship ceremony.
   ``I've known about them for a long time and I've always wanted
to do something on them,'' he said. ``I have financing from an
independent outfit and it'll probably be for BBC. I have permission
from the Turkish government to film them. You might find them all
over the world. It's like a secret sect. To become a Whirling
Dervish you have to study for two years.''
   Havers has also been cast to play David Niven in ``The Moon's a
Balloon,'' based on Niven's memoir. It's been temporarily shelved.
   ``Too many producers and not enough direction,'' said Havers.
``We'll sort that out later.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend, April 28-30</NOTE>
