<DOCNO> AP890420-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-RacialTolerance Adv23   04-20 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Racial Tolerance, Adv 23,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prejudice Remains, but Polls Indicate Increasing Racial Tolerance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-White Resentment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For all their vitriol, racial hate groups in the
United States are swimming against a steady tide of public opinion:
While prejudice remains, polls show, it has been declining steadily
for years.
   Groups such as the loosely organized neo-Nazi skinheads, who
were assembling with white supremacists in Idaho this weekend,
represent a minuscule minority with no trend in broader opinion
behind them, pollsters said in interviews last week.
   ``You always have kook groups around,'' said Tom Smith, director
of the long-running General Social Survey at the National Opinion
Research Center. ``I don't see any sign that they're tapping a vein
of discontent.''
   Still, even as polls track general declines in racism, they do
find lingering prejudice, particularly among older whites in the
rural South. And whites overall remain far more sanguine than
blacks about race relations.
   ``There's no doubt that there is a lot of racism in American
society,'' Smith said. ``To say that we are a racially color-blind
society is nonsense. But to say there's hasn't been enormous
progress is also misguided.''
   He pointed, for example, to support for busing to achieve racial
balance in public schools. Thirty-four percent of American adults
polled by NORC supported busing in 1988 _ a minority but well up
from 16 percent in 1976.
   Similarly, while 23 percent said last year that they favored
laws against interracial marriage, that was down from 30 percent in
1980. Other measures, from willingness to vote for a black for
president to acceptance of racial diversity in schools and
neighborhoods, also show increasing tolerance.
   Pollsters note, however, that expressions of tolerance can be
misleading. While most whites say they would vote for a qualified
black for president, for example, most also say no black has such
qualifications now.
   ``Generally the trend has been helpful. A lot of folks out there
think racism is wrong and would like to believe it's a problem
that's going behind us,'' said Steve Ralston, deputy director of
the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund. ``But blacks still
feel the effects of racism very much.''
   In a recent Harris poll, for example, 70 percent of whites said
most blacks received equal pay for equal work, while only 40
percent of blacks agreed. In a Media General-Associated Press poll,
57 percent of whites said blacks and other minorities had the same
opportunities as whites, but only 28 percent of blacks agreed.
   ``Across the board, whites think blacks are treated better than
blacks think blacks are treated,'' said Ron Bass, a pollster for
Louis Harris and Associates. ``Whites think blacks have made a lot
of progress in terms of attaining equality. Blacks don't feel that
way at all.''
   Polls, however, do not support the thesis that white Americans
are growing disenchanted with government efforts to address past
discrimination. While such programs have never been broadly
popular, said Smith, support for them has held steady or increased,
not declined.
   In NORC polls, for instance, support for more spending on
``improving the conditions of blacks'' rose from 26 percent in 1978
to 38 percent a decade later, while those who wanted less money
committed to the effort fell from 27 percent to 17 percent. The
bulk each year said spending was about right.
   Questions on affirmative action are among the most sensitive,
because of a resistance among Americans to the perception of
preferential treatment for any group, Smith said. A Harris poll
asking if respondents favored ``affirmative action programs in
employment for blacks, provided there are no rigid quotas,'' found
74 percent in support. But the same question using different
language in a Media General-Associated Press poll _ should blacks
and other minorities ``receive preference in hiring to make up for
past inequalities'' _ found 79 percent opposed.
   Nevertheless, when the question has been asked over time, Smith
said, polls have not found any growing opposition to affirmative
action.
   Even with the poll results, Ralston, of the NAACP Legal Defense
and Educational Fund, said he was concerned about anecdotal reports
that could indicate increased racial intolerance, ranging from
racially divided voting in Chicago's mayoral election to the 1986
racial attack in the Howard Beach neighborhood of New York City.
   Gauging from the sentiments in surveys, ``The trend is in the
right direction,'' Ralston said. ``But we've got a ways to go yet.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890420-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1605EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Davis Adv23   04-20 1153</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Davis, Adv 23,1177</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Legendary Actress to Receive Lincoln Center Honor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The red brick apartment house just south of
the Sunset Strip is so handsomely crafted and so venerable by
California standards it has been designated a national monument. So
has the lady on the fourth floor.
   Bette Davis has been accorded almost every honor possible for a
film actress: two Academy Awards, the American Film Institute and
Kennedy Center awards for lifetime achievement and more. One has
been missing, and that will be corrected April 24 when she is
honored by the Film Society of Lincoln Center.
   ``This is sort of the last big one I haven't received, and I'm
very pleased. It took me a long time to receive the Kennedy Center.
So I say, better late than never. I must say I've never gotten
blase about honors. It's great, it's wonderful,'' she said.
   The apartment is spacious yet bears little evidence of her
studio years. The exception is a large painting of Davis, around
1950 when she made ``All About Eve.'' The room was fragrant with
floral bouquets sent for her 81st birthday April 5. ``It was a
wonderful family day, lots of flowers, lots of calls,'' she said.
   The actress looked stylish in a black top and black skirt filled
with yellow daisies. Half a lifetime after the portrait on the
wall, her face shows evidence of severe illness. Yet her ash-blonde
hair is as lovely as ever, and she retains a regal beauty. The
voice still crackles with no-nonsense authority, and she still
unapologetically smokes cigarettes.
   In a recent interview, she sat in an easy chair, leaning against
a small pillow bearing the legend in needlepoint: ``No Guts, No
Glory.'' Is that a Davis motto?
   ``Oh, yes. Totally,'' she declared. ``It's the truth. To dare to
be hated _ that takes guts.''
   Her recent history has borne out her credo. She survived a
mastectomy and a disfiguring stroke. She weathered an attack by
daughter B.D. Hyman in the 1985 book, ``My Mother's Keeper.''
Davis' own book, ``This 'n' That'' (1987) was rejected by a
publisher, but she advertised it in Publisher's Weekly, found
another publisher and had a best seller.
   Last year, she left ``Wicked Stepmother'' in the middle of
filming to have dental work in New York. Claiming differences with
the director, she didn't return, and the thriller was finished
without her.
   She shrugs off such matters and talks more positively about
other things, such as the miracle year of 1939, the greatest
outpouring of movie classics in Hollywood history. Astonishingly,
she starred in four memorable films that year: ``Dark Victory,''
``Juarez,'' ``The Private Lives of Elizabeth and Essex'' and ``The
Old Maid.''
   This is also the golden anniversary of ``Gone With the Wind,''
``The Wizard of Oz,'' ``Wuthering Heights,'' ``Stagecoach'' and
``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington.'' Why such a creative explosion?
   ``I don't know,'' Davis said. ``I did about 10 films in a row,
starting in 1939, and I was pretty tired when it was all over. But
that series of films made this career permanent. Many of them were
based on great plays. There are no plays anymore. (Today's films
are about) diseases and nonfiction.
   ``I'll feel very happy, too, that I was a black-and-white-era
woman. Oh, yes. It gave you so much more variety; color is so
`pretty.'
   ``They wanted to make `(Whatever Happened to Baby) Jane' in
color. I said, `I won't make it if it's in color.' I couldn't
possibly have worn the makeup in color. ... The shadows and the
lights and all of those great cameramen, like Ernie Haller! I
happened to see `All This and Heaven, Too' the other night. Ah! I
was a lucky woman. The women of today don't have such cameramen. I
don't think people care anymore.''
   Is she appalled by the coloring of film classics?
   ``It's worse than appalled. It's heartbroken. I saw `Dark
Victory' in color. The bright pink blouse and the bright blue
skirt, and all the faces and the sets are pink. So all the good
taste of the set people, the wardrobe people, the actors is
ruined.''
   She was born Ruth Elizabeth Davis in Lowell, Mass., and like
Katharine Hepburn, her life has been instilled with Yankee
indomitability. After minor stage work, she landed in Hollywood
with a Universal contract, making her film debut in 1931 with ``Bad
Sister.'' She was fired for having ``as much sex appeal as Slim
Summerville,'' the studio's tall, skinny comic.
   The young actress was headed back to the stage when an offer
came from Warner Bros. The studio used her for leg art and ingenue
roles until she was loaned to RKO for ``Of Human Bondage'' in 1934.
Her portrayal of the slatternly waitress was galvanizing. Her first
Oscar came the next year for an inconsequential film,
``Dangerous,'' consolation prize for losing in 1934. She won again
for ``Jezebel'' in 1939.
   Jack Warner realized he had a major star, and Davis' roles
became more formidable. But she was dissatisfied with how she was
treated, and she tried to break her contract by fleeing to England.
Warner won a suit to force her return.
   ``Jack was gracious afterward,'' she recalled. ``If you lose a
case, you have to pay both lawyers' fees. He did not make me pay
his lawyers. He was very, very good when I came home. I got better
directors, better scripts.''
   She remained at Warners for 18 years, leaving after the
disastrous ``Beyond the Forest'' in 1949. Her next movie was ``All
About Eve,'' another of her 10 Academy nominations. She has
continued working in films, television and lectures, always in the
patented Davis style and despite tragedy.
   Personal disasters have not prompted Davis to abandon her
65-year passion for acting. Her greatest hope is to make a film on
the life of the late beauty tycoon Helena Rubinstein. ``I've got a
good script, and I'll do it,'' she said with customary resolve.
   She also would like to resume ``The Bette Davis Show,'' a
traveling act featuring exchanges between the star and the audience
and clips of her movies. She recalled her favorite story:
   ``I was appearing for three nights at the Palladium in London. A
woman at the back of the theater screamed at me: ``Miss Davis, have
you had your face lifted?'
   ``I got down on my knees in back of the footlights and said,
`Come here!' This poor woman and the whole audience was worried.
She didn't know whether I was going to punch her or say, `God damn
you' or what. So I faced her over the footlights and said, `If I
had, wouldn't I look a lot better?'''
   She gave the hearty Bette Davis laugh, blinked those Bette Davis
eys and lighted another cigarette.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
