<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Ellington Adv23   04-20 1060</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Ellington, Adv 23,1102</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>In an Ellington Mood: 90th Anniversay of Duke Ellington's Birth</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I love you madly.''
   _ Duke Ellington, to his audience at every perfomance.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By MARY CAMPBELL</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His mistress was music and his passion jazz. And
his genius was the ability to easily execute his ideas, whether
with a full orchestra or a mere piano.
   Edward Kennedy ``Duke'' Ellington was one of the greatest
American composers of the 20th century, a band leader, arranger and
pianist who helped hone jazz into a fine art for half a century. He
would have been 90 on April 29, and friends, family and fans are
commemorating the anniversary of his birth with concerts and
remembrances.
   His son, Mercer, who now leads the celebrated Ellington Band,
says his father would have been especially delighted about being
honored in Washington, D.C., his home town.
   Mercer will lead celebrations in both Washington and New York,
where his father and his band became famous at the Cotton Club
starting in 1927. Duke remained in New York and perfected his
compositions. He died there at age 75 on May 24, 1974.
   On April 27, Mercer will participate in a symposium at the
Smithsonian Institution and lay a cornerstone. The house where Duke
Ellington was born has been torn down. When the developer was told
the significance of the site, he named his new structure the Duke
Ellington Building.
   On April 28, the Ellington Band will play at the Beacon Theater
in New York. The first half will be ``A Drum Is a Woman,''
choreographed by Mercedes Ellington, the oldest of Mercer's four
children. She danced in ``No! No! Nanette!'' and ``Sophisticated
Ladies,'' a musical of Duke Ellington tunes, on Broadway and now
heads her own company, DancEllington. The Anne Swain Clark Singers
also will participate.
   ``A Drum Is a Woman,'' an allegorical history of jazz, was first
performed on the U.S. Steel Hour on CBS-TV in 1957, with Talley
Beatty dancing the part of Caribee Joe opposite Carmen de Lavallade
as Mme. Zzaj (jazz spelled backwards). Duke narrated.
   ``That was a project he and Orson Welles had,'' Mercer said.
``Orson put him on a fabulous salary and they would party like mad
dogs. The boss asked, `Where is the music?' Orson got fired. `A
Drum Is a Woman' was some of the work from that project. It was
made into a record album and from the album it went onto TV.''
   They also will perform ``Ansellia'' (a black orchid), which
Mercer composed for Mercedes when she was 7.
   The band returns to Washington for a parade across the Duke
Ellington Bridge on April 29 and a concert at the Smithsonian. The
Smithsonian will also have showings of ``Paris Blues'' and
``Anatomy of a Murder'' and a month-long exhibit of Ellington
memorabilia and the art of Gaye Ellington, his granddaughter.
   On April 30, the band will squeeze into the Cates Restaurant and
Jazz Club in Washington. They'll have to play from memory, Mercer
said, because the club is too small to hold bandstands as well as
the musicians.
   The Ellington Band has released a new Musicmasters recording,
``Music Is My Mistress,'' taken from the title of Ellington's 1973
autobiography. It's a followup to ``Digital Duke,'' on GRP Records,
which won a Grammy in 1988. Musicmasters also has a new ``Four
Symphonic Works by Duke Ellington,'' which are ``Harle,'' ``Black,
Brown and Beige,'' ``New World a Comin''' and ``Three Black
Kings,'' by the American Composers Orchestra, conducted by Maurice
Peress.
   Mercer, a graduate of the Juilliard School, has lived through
the traumas of growing up the son of a famous father. He's now
secure as the keeper of the flame and is freer to be himself.
   ``I'm not fending off anything anymore. If you can wind up being
as close to him as possible, you're still going to be different and
your own person,'' he said.
   Mercer's best-known composition is ``Things Ain't What They Used
to Be.''
   ``When I go to write music, I'm sometimes surprised they come
off close to what Duke's sound would have been,'' he said. ``That
comes from the hours I spent doing his copying. I absorbed
different things and didn't realize it. I've been going through the
music for the Smithsonian (which has the Duke Ellington archives)
and I understand it better now than I did then.
   ``For instance, I was going through the numbers he wrote for
`Jump for Joy' _ `I Got It Bad and That Ain't Good,' `Brown-Skinned
Gal in the Calico Gown,' `Chocolate Shake.' I saw the entr'acte,
`Giddy Bug Gallop.' I realized this was something too amazing even
to hope to understand when I first heard it. Now I know what it is.
We (the band) are getting ready to do it ourselves.''
   ``Jump for Joy'' played to sold-out houses in Los Angeles in
1941 but never moved to Broadway. ``In certain quarters it wasn't
too popular,'' Mercer said. ``It was blatantly against racial
prejudice. There were threats to bomb the theater.''
   ``Queenie Pie,'' an opera Ellington composed for television but
was never broadcast, has been produced in Philadelphia and
Washington and is slated for Broadway next fall starring Patti
LaBelle. ``Queenie Pie Reggae,'' including steel drums, is on the
new album.
   Duke wrote the reggae. ``He didn't jump into a fad but he always
touched on it,'' Mercer said. ``He'd make sure he wasn't left out,
not having a say about what was happening. `Black Swan' was a
disguised form of `Take the A Train' as a cha-cha. He took `Creole
Love Call' and made it rock 'n' roll and called it `Neo-Creole.' He
wrote `Octaclock Rock,' after Harold Ashby got in the band.''
   From his first hit in 1930, ``Mood Indigo,'' Duke Ellington
wrote and composed thousands of works including popular songs,
suites, tone poems and three song cycles meant to be sung as sacred
concerts.
   ``The sacred concerts were sincere,'' Mercer said. ``It was also
another way for him to really be intelligent and get away with it.
Modern religious music is open enough to allow newer thoughts.
   ``He has done things with music which is not necessarily jazz.
As his friend Bob Bach (the late TV producer) said, `Duke is beyond
category.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890420-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1527EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv23   04-20 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 23,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Vice Presidency According to Quayle</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The question is always more enticing than the
reply because there is only one right answer for a vice president.
And Dan Quayle gave it.
   ``No,'' Quayle said, he would not disclose the issues on which
he had differed with President Bush. ``Sorry.''
   Vice presidents who did otherwise have been sorrier. Spiro T.
Agnew came quickly to regret the misgivings he expressed about the
first gestures in what became President Richard M. Nixon's opening
to China. Hubert H. Humphrey had to back off his own effort to
chart an independent and slightly different Vietnam policy during
the 1968 presidential campaign.
   Harmony is the vice presidential rule, and the president picks
the tunes.
   ``I'm not going to get into private conversations that I have
with the president, what kind of influence and how I think I can
influence his decisions,'' Quayle told the American Society of
Newspaper Editors. ``It wouldn't be appropriate and I've decided
not to do it, and if I did engage in it I would lose my
effectiveness.
   ``So I'm just not going to enter into that kind of discussion.''
   That's right out of the vice presidential textbook according to
Bush, who kept his own counsel for eight years as No. 2 to Ronald
Reagan. He joined the ticket in 1980 as a defeated Reagan rival for
the presidential nomination. He was not a popular choice among many
of Reagan's conservative allies.
   So there was a premium on loyalty from the start, and Bush
delivered. It paid double dividends as Bush became Reagan's
political heir, and sometimes took shelter from potentially
embarrassing questions in the vows of privacy and silence he said
his job demanded.
   Quayle, by contrast, came to the Bush ticket as a rookie in
national politics, got a faltering start and still is working to
shake the lightweight image shaped by his detractors, not all of
whom are Democrats.
   That's no easy task in a job Nelson A. Rockefeller described as
``standby equipment.'' The prescribed duties are largely
ceremonial: Quayle jokes that Bush offered to designate him funeral
czar, since the vice president often gets the duty when foreign
leaders die.
   The president has done a lot more than that to help the vice
president prove himself. Bush has given Quayle a White House role
much like his own. He sent the vice president on the first foreign
assignment of the new administration, to Latin America, and Quayle
is about to begin a 10-day mission to Australia and Southeast Asia.
   They have shared platforms and sometimes audiences, in one-two
appearances that are unusual for presidents and vice presidents.
   Bush and Quayle both will address the members of The Associated
Press in separate appearances in Chicago on Monday. The president
is to speak at the AP annual meeting, the vice president two hours
later at the annual luncheon of the news cooperative.
   Both will answer questions, as they did two days apart at the
Washington meeting of the American Society of Newspaper Editors.
   Quayle heads a revitalized National Space Council, a vice
presidential assignment dating back to the time when John F.
Kennedy couldn't figure out what to do with Lyndon B. Johnson.
   He also will run a new Council on Competitiveness, which will
seek ways to improve the U.S. position in world trade.
   Perhaps most important, Bush has given Quayle a daily White
House role much like his own. ``I meet with the president every
morning,'' Quayle said. ``I have the right to go into his office
any time I want to. I can have a one-on-one meeting any time. I
have them periodically.
   ``I have a weekly scheduled luncheon where the president and I
sit down and have 60 minutes together to go over various things.
   ``What do we discuss? We discuss everything... I inject my
opinions, my ideas to him ... so it's not just one area that's
carved out for myself, there are various things.''
   Quayle said all of that is on the model of the Bush vice
presidency.
   ``Now, obviously, I'm a different individual than President Bush
and obviously in a period of time you will have the Quayle model of
the vice presidency,'' he said.
   ``We're just starting.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun, April 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
