<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     04-20 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0786</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate approved a record $157 billion
bailout and reform bill for the savings and loan industry after
toughening provisions that would require S&amp;L owners to put more of
their own money at risk to stay in business.
   The 564-page bill was approved Wednesday on a 91-8 vote two
months after President Bush called for emergency legislation to
stop the hemorrhaging of the federal S&amp;L insurance fund from the
failure of 500 thrifts, more than 200 of them in 1988, and another
350 at or near insolvency.
   The legislation would represent the biggest government financial
rescue in history, dwarfing by five times the combined costs of the
New York City, Penn Central, Chrysler and Lockheed bailouts of the
1970s and early 1980s.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the biggest futures markets proposed
sweeping changes that would double surveillance and limit a
controversial trading practice in response to a federal fraud probe
that has tainted Chicago's financial industry.
   The most imporant restriction in a report Wednesday by the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange's Special Committee to Review Trading
Practices would be limits on dual trading, a controversial practice
that enables a trader to trade his own account at the same time he
handles customers' accounts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration urged the Supreme
Court to protect the nation's children by upholding a federal law
that would shut down the $2 billion ``dial-a-porn'' industry.
   Congress was justified when it passed a law last year banning
all sexually explicit telephone dial-up message services to
``protect children from hearing patently offensive speech,''
Justice Department lawyer Richard Taranto contended Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices spurted to a three-year high
amid a series of bullish indicators, including a North Sea gas
explosion and an industry report that showed U.S. production fell
to its lowest level since the 1960s.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Wednesday, the May price of
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, jumped
$1.10 to $22.61 a barrel, the highest level since Jan. 17, 1986,
when the near-term contract finished at $23.53 a barrel.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner told
the Senate that industry plans for dealing with an Alaskan oil
spill had been a ``zero'' as one senator said the initial response
to the March 24 disaster reminded him of ``the Keystone Kops.''
   Most witnesses before the Senate's environmental protection
subcommittee _ from federal officials to Alaska's governor and
industry executives _ said Wednesday that plans for dealing with a
spill of oil from the Alaskan pipeline had not imagined an accident
on the magnitude of the 10-million-gallon spill that soiled
pristine Prince William Sound.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. announced a
20.6 percent increase in first-quarter profit, thrust ahead by an
expensive restructuring last year that produced its first annual
loss.
   The phone giant achieved the improved results despite intense
competition across its range of businesses, Robert E. Allen,
chairman and chief executive, told shareholders Wednesday at the
company's 104th annual meeting.
  
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Securities and Exchange
Commission suggested the agency still might pursue action against
the head of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and other top executives of
the investment firm.
   SEC Chairman David Ruder, testifying before a House subcommittee
Wednesday, said he expects the agency's enforcement division to
``pursue the activities of all the Drexel officials who were in
responsiblity'' during the time when major securities violations
allegedly were committed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. is requiring bidders
for its retail brokerage to promise they won't hire any of the
unit's 1,100 brokers for one year if a deal falls through, Wall
Street sources said.
   Also Wednesday, the head of a state securities committee
monitoring Drexel said dumping the retail brokerage could save
Drexel the embarrassment of having its securities licenses stripped
in many states.
