<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 0232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel Bjt   04-20 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel, Bjt,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firms Balking At Drexel Retail Brokerage Auction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s decision to sell
its retail brokerage operation could save the firm the
embarrassment of losing its securities licenses in dozens of
states, a securities regulator says.
   In addition, Wall Street sources said Wednesday that Drexel is
requiring bidders for the brokerage to promise they won't hire any
of the unit's 1,100 brokers for one year if a bidder's deal falls
through.
   The move to abandon the retail brokerage, which has been part of
the firm for nearly all of its 157 years, followed Drexel's
settlement last week of civil fraud charges with the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
   Drexel has contacted securities officials in all 50 states to
prepare for a wave of litigation expected to follow the pact and
the firm's pending guilty plea and $650 million settlement of
felony charges with the Manhattan U.S. attorney's office.
   Most states bar securities trading by anyone convicted of or
admitting to a felony or facing an SEC injunction, said Susan
Bryant, who heads a panel of state regulators monitoring the Drexel
case. The states are expected to try to revoke Drexel's state
securities licenses.
   But Bryant said that by dumping its retail division, which has
43 offices in 19 states, the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico,
Drexel may eliminate some state civil action to strip its trading
licenses.
   ``In most states the focus is on ... the need to protect the
consumer, so the negotiations with Drexel may actually change a
little bit,'' said Bryant, Oklahoma's securities administrator.
``The things that might have been required to protect the consumer
may not be necessary.''
   One firm said Wednesday it refused to join the bidding for the
brokerage operation because of the strict terms being applied by
Drexel, which announced the proposed sale Tuesday as part of a
major restructuring amid negative publicity following two major
securities fraud settlements.
   Drexel said it contacted about eight firms about buying the
division but three _ Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. and Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. _ said they're not interested.
   ``We declined because we questioned the appropriateness of this
auction process for a financial services company where clients and
professionals are the key assets,'' Dean Witter said in a statement.
   Drexel is forcing any firm that wants to examine the retail unit
to sign a letter stating it won't ``directly or indirectly solicit
the services'' of anyone in the division for one year, said a Wall
Street source who declined further identification.
   Firms that submit to the pact can review a package of
information provided by Drexel today and Friday and must submit a
bid by Saturday, the source said. Analysts have placed the value of
the department at $50 million to $200 million.
   The requirement is designed to block other firms from raiding
Drexel's 1,100 brokers _ many of whom vented their anger at Drexel
Chief Executive Frederick H. Joseph during a session on the firm's
internal communications system after the announcement.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder denied that there was a one-year
moratorium on hiring Drexel brokers but refused to provide further
details on the agreements. He said four or five firms have agreed
to the bidding conditions.
   Officials at other firms said many Drexel brokers had contacted
them looking for jobs before the announcement, and several firms
were reported Wednesday to be negotiating with brokers.
   ``Putting them up on the auction block with no firm bidder
disclosed gives them great incentive to pursue their individual
fortunes,'' one Wall Street executive said. ``Probably as we speak
there's some very active cherry-picking going on.''
   Drexel's retail unit accounts for about 10 percent of the
private firm's business. At its peak, the department had 1,300
brokers, but Drexel didn't replace defectors or retirees because of
the October 1987 stock market crash and the government probes, a
Drexel spokesman said.
   Drexel said it also is abandoning its business in municipal
securities, over-the-counter stocks, and research and transactions
in foreign securities. The restructuring will cut Drexel's
9,100-member work force by about a third.
   A deal to buy the brokerage would include Drexel's retail
offices, stockbrokers and, presumably, the accounts that go with
them. Drexel has not said whether it will lay off the 1,200-member
support staff in the unit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
