<DOCNO> AP890420-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 0236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Judge     04-20 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Judge,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Delays Ruling On Drexel-SEC Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drexel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legal tactic Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. used
to battle civil securities fraud charges last year has come back to
haunt the investment giant and delay final settlement of the case.
   On Wednesday, a federal appeals court refused to modify a stay _
originally requested by Drexel _ that temporarily bars lower court
approval of the deal to settle the biggest securities fraud case in
history.
   The unanimous, three-judge appeals panel ruling prevents U.S.
District Judge Milton Pollack, whom Drexel unsuccessfully tried to
disqualify, from approving last week's settlement between Drexel
and the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruling also cast a shadow
over a final resolution of criminal charges against Drexel, the
fifth-largest investment firm in the nation.
   The plea bargain Drexel struck last December with federal
prosecutors in the criminal case, requiring the firm to plead
guilty to six felony counts and pay a record $650 million in
penalties and fines, is contingent on the SEC settlement.
   In Washington, SEC Solicitor Paul Gonson said, ``We are
disappointed with the Court of Appeals declining to permit the
(lower) court to enter this consent decree, which we feel is in the
public interest.''
   Gonson, who oversees SEC appeals, said the commission has
``decided to take further judicial action'' possibly as soon as
today, although he declined to give details.
   Deborah Corley, a spokeswoman for U.S. Attorney Benito Romano,
said the Manhattan federal prosecutor's office would have no
comment on the ruling.
   Sources close to the case, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said it was unclear whether the 2nd Circuit decision prohibited the
SEC and Drexel from seeking a different district judge's approval.
If it did bar such an alternative, final approval of the settlement
could be delayed for months, they said.
   The SEC's sweeping civil action last September accused Drexel,
its former junk bond chief, Michael Milken, his brother, Lowell,
and others of insider trading and other securities violations.
   But Drexel battled to get Pollack to excuse himself from the
case for an alleged conflict of interest.
   Drexel lawyers maintained that Pollack should be disqualified
because his wife stood to make millions from a leveraged buyout
that Drexel had helped to finance.
   Pollack refused to step down from the case and the 2nd Circuit,
which stayed further district court proceedings pending its
decision, upheld Pollack in November.
   Drexel eventually gave up its objections to Pollack but the stay
was extended when the Milkens and other defendants sought to argue
the issue before the U.S. Sumpreme Court.
   The Supreme Court has not decided whether it will hear the
appeal.
   Last week, Drexel and the SEC moved to modify the stay, to allow
Pollack to rule on the settlement, claiming it was ``in the public
interest and important to the protection of investors'' for the
deal to go into effect.
   Gary Lynch, the SEC's director of enforcement, said the Drexel
deal was ``one of the most important'' cases ever brought and to
delay its implementation would delay payment of $350 million into a
fund to compensate investors hurt by Drexel's illegal activities.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Bruce Baird made it even plainer to the
2nd Circuit, saying additional delay could cause the five-year
statute of limitations ``to bar prosecutions'' stemming from the
Drexel probe.
   But the 2nd Circuit said allowing Pollack ``to consider and
possibly to approve this settlement would be to allow a change in
the status quo as it concerns the interests of Michael and Lowell
Milken before the Supreme Court has disposed of the case.''
   As part of its settlements with both the SEC and the U.S.
attorney's office in Manhattan, Drexel is required to fire Michael
Milken and suspend his brother, and not engage in business
transactions with either man.
   The Milkens, who were not part of either settlement, were named
earlier this month in a massive federal racketeering indictment
seeking more than $1.8 billion in forfeitures. The Milkens have
pleaded innocent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890420-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesRules Bjt   04-20 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Rules, Bjt,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merc Proposes To Ban Most `Dual Trading,' Improve Surveillance, Auditing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed ban on most forms of ``dual trading,''
extensive background checks of new members and expansion of
disciplinary committees are proof that the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange wants to preserve integrity, officials said.
   ``We said there would be no sacred cows, and there were none,''
said Susan Phillips, former chairman of the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission and a member of the Merc's Special Committee to
Review Trading Practices.
   Committee Chairman John Geldermann said the urgency of
Wednesday's recommendations was necessary to maintain investor
confidence since disclosure three months ago of a federal
investigation into suspected fraud at the Merc and the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Dual trading, allowed by virtually every financial exchange,
enables a trader to trade his own account at the same time he
handles customers' accounts.
   Many consider the practice susceptible to abuse because it
allows unscrupulous traders to allocate profitable deals to their
own accounts and dump losing trades on customers.
   Proponents of dual trading argue that the practice increases
liquidity because traders can continue doing business when they
don't have outside orders.
   But the Merc committee, with few exceptions, recommended that
dual trading be banned from futures contracts in cases where market
volume is great enough to ensure liquidity.
   The committee also recommended:
   _More extensive screening of membership applicants.
   _That members of a broker association should not be allowed to
execute personal trades against orders by members of the broker
group.
   _The addition of one non-Merc member to all major disciplinary
committees. ``The criticism is that we're too clubby,'' said Merc
policy chief Leo Melamed. ``This would enable the public to view
the process and see we are open-handed.''
   _Daily computerized trade information for members covering all
activity from the previous day.
   The panel also recommended the Merc's full-time floor
surveillance team be doubled to eight staff members.
   The recommendations will be submitted to the Merc's board of
governors, and a decision is expected within 60 days.
   ``The outside members of the committee felt that the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange has acted in good faith in enforcing its
existing rules and procedures, and tightening them when
necessary,'' said Ms. Phillips, a vice president at the University
of Iowa.
   ``But the rules and procedures have not kept pace with the rapid
expansion of new products and trading volume during the past few
years,'' she said.
   Melamed said many of the recommendations contained in the report
were under consideration earlier.
   ``But the time frame was compressed as a result of the (federal)
investigation,'' he said.
   Merc officials appointed the nine-member committee in late
January.
   Some observers viewed the committee as part of the futures
industry's effort to hold the line against further government
regulations.
   The FBI investigation centers on allegations that as many as 100
brokers at the world's two largest futures exchanges may have
systematically cheated investors out of millions of dollars through
illegal trading practices.
   No indictments have been handed down yet, but as many as 200
subpeonas reportedly have been issued to traders and firms at the
exchanges. Published reports have said FBI agents posing as traders
at the Merc and Board of Trade secretly recorded conversations in
the pits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
