<DOCNO> AP890420-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 0837EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GTE-HomeShopping     04-20 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GTE-Home Shopping,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>GTE Annual Meeting Runs Smoothly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GTE Corp. and the Home Shopping Network
have exchanged another round of barbs as they prepare for a court
battle over a $1.5 billion damages lawsuit.
   On Wednesday, the day GTE held its annual meeting, the Home
Shopping Network announced that it had filed a complaint on April
10 against the telephone giant with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
   The letter accused GTE of failing to fully disclose the
potential threat it faces from the $1.5 billion lawsuit filed
against it by HSN.
   GTE vice president Edward C. Schmults issued a release at the
annual meeting that labeled the complaint as ``totally unfounded.''
   Home Shopping's lawsuit in Florida state court contends GTE had
provided it poor telephone equipment. As a result, HSN claims it
lost thousands of customers. In addition, the lawsuit claims GTE
knew its equipment was inadequate and fraudulently kept the
information secret from HSN.
   Home Shopping Network is distributed nationally on cable
networks. It offers merchandise for sale, which viewers can
purchase by calling telephone numbers displayed on television
screens.
   GTE has denied any wrongdoing in its past dealings with HSN. It
also has filed a countersuit, charging HSN with business libel and
slander.
   Responding to HSN's latest claim, Schmults said, ``It is obvious
that this latest HSN action is just another unconscionable example
of HSN's attempting to litigate the case outside the courtroom and
unfairly influence prospective jurors.''
   A trial is expected to start on June 5 at a court in Clearwater,
Fla., where HSN is based.
   In the lawsuit, HSN is seeking $500 million in actual damages
and $1 billion in punitive damages.
   Fernando DiFilippo, HSN general counsel, dismissed Schmults
comments as ``GTE's standard public relations response.''
   ``Instead of responding that our allegations are unfounded, they
ought to go back and review them,'' he said.
   The battle of words on the lawsuit overshadowed other business
at GTE's annual meeting. The gathering was the first to be presided
over by James L. Johnson, who was named chairman and chief
executive officer one year ago.
   ``As most of you are aware, the financial results were excellent
for us,'' Johnson said of 1988. ``We made further progress in the
continuing the efforts to enhance our long term profits.''
   The company reported a record income of $1.2 billion in 1988,
9.5 percent higher than 1987. The company also had record revenues
of $16.5 billion, 6.7 percent higher than the $15.4 billion logged
in 1987.
   On Tuesday, the company reported a first-quarter income of $329
million on sales totaling $4.1 billion. Earnings and revenue both
were up 15 percent compared to the 1988 figures.
   In response to a shareholder question, Johnson defended GTE's
decision last July to sell a 30.1 percent interest in US Sprint to
United Telecommunications Inc. for $585 million. US Sprint is a
long-distance telephone service formed in 1986 by GTE and United
Telecommunications.
   ``It was a win-win situation. They won, we won. We think it was
a good decision,'' Johnson said.
   GTE, which still holds a 19.9 percent share of US Sprint, lost
$1.5 billion in developing the network, said Charles R. Lee,
president and chief operating officer. GTE intends to eventually
sell the rest of its Sprint ownership, he said.
   GTE, based in Stamford, provides telephone service to 31 states,
Canada and the Dominican Republic. GTE also is a major military
telephone contractor, ringing up more than $2 billion worth of
Defense Department contracts in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890420-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 0906EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Pennwalt     04-20 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Pennwalt,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pennwalt Earnings Up 12 Percent in First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp., which agreed to a friendly
takeover a month ago to escape hostile pursuers, announced a 12
percent increase in first-quarter earnings.
   The pharmaceutical company on Wednesday reported earnings of
$46.3 million, or $3.54 a share, on revenue of $279.9 million,
compared with earnings of $41.2 million, or $1.08 a share, on
revenue of $264.4 million a year ago.
   The quarter's per-share earnings included $1.21 from the sale of
Pennwalt Italia SpA, a chemical operation sold last month.
   Pennwalt has streamlined in the past year while trying to hold
off Centaur Partners, a New York investment firm. A month ago,
Pennwalt and the French oil and chemical company El Aquitane agreed
to a takeover worth more than $1 billion.
   Sales in the industrial and intermediate chemicals group
increased 13 percent and earnings increased 30 percent, the company
said.
   ``All three of the major divisions making up this group _
fluorochemicals, inorganic chemicals and organic chemicals _
contributed to these outstanding results,'' said Edwin E. Tuttle,
chairman and chief executive officer.
   The earnings report came one day after Elf Aquitane announced it
had extended its tender offer of $132 per share for three weeks,
unitl May 19. The company said it needed the additional time to
comply with the Federal Trade Commission's request for information
and documents involving the proposed takeover.
