<FIRST>r f PM-Coleco-Hasbro     04-20 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coleco-Hasbro,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hasbro Announces Agreement To Buy Most Of Coleco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AVON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coleco Industries Inc. says it favors its own
reorganization plan despite Hasbro Inc.'s announcement of an
agreement with a group of Coleco's unsecured creditors to seek to
acquire most of the financially troubled toymaker.
   Hasbro said Wednesday it would seek permission from a federal
bankruptcy court judge to file a joint reorganization plan for
Avon-based Coleco, which earlier this month announced an amended
reorganization plan it hoped would satisfy its unsecured creditors.
   In a statement Wednesday, Coleco said the Hasbro proposal
``appears to be less favorable'' than the amended reorganization
plan Coleco proposed April 6.
   Under Hasbro's proposal, the Rhode Island-based toymaker would
purchase Coleco's assets by giving Coleco $85 million in cash and a
warrant worth an estimated $5 million to acquire 1 million shares
of Hasbro's stock over the next four years, said John T. O'Neill,
Hasbro's chief financial officer. A warrant offers the right to buy
stock at a certain price.
   O'Neill said Hasbro is looking to acquire property rights and
some of Coleco's inventory but that the final determination of what
Hasbro will assume would be detailed in the reorganization plan.
   Coleco said it has been developing the amended plan with ``a
substantial group'' of unsecured creditors for several weeks and
that Coleco management believes it ``will be of greater benefit to
all creditors and shareholders than the Hasbro proposal.''
   On April 6, Coleco said that under the amended plan, unsecured
creditors, who are owed more than $400 million, would receive stock
in the company, giving them about 37 percent of Coleco.
   Coleco Chairman Morton E. Handel also said at the time that the
unsecured creditors would receive other securities, cash, notes and
debt instruments worth about $40 million. The amendment also called
for secured creditors to convert their current claim of about $80
million into Coleco common stock, giving them 60 percent ownership.
   The Coleco board of directors called that plan ``a substantial
improvement for the unsecured creditors'' over a plan filed in
January, which unsecured creditors said did not offer them enough.
   Once one of the nation's largest toymakers, Coleco filed for
protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal
bankruptcy laws in July 1988 and in February announced it was
considering selling the company.
   At the same time as it announced its amended reorganization
plan, Coleco said it had dropped plans of a sale. It reaffirmed
Wednesday that it wants to remain independent.
   Barry J. Alperin, an executive vice president at Hasbro, said
Hasbro indicated its interest in buying Coleco when Coleco
announced it was exploring a sale.
   ``We were disappointed that Coleco failed to follow that course
of action, but are pleased to be working with the unsecured
creditors committee to seek the permission of the bankruptcy court
to acquire the company,'' Alperin said.
   O'Neill said a petition asking the bankruptcy court for
permission to file a joint reorganization plan would probably be
filed Thursday. If it is accepted, Hasbro officials hope to
complete the acquisition by the end of July, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890420-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 0937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Pickens-Koito     04-20 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pickens-Koito,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koito Denies Pickens Immediate Board Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover specialist T. Boone Pickens, now the
largest shareholder in a major Japanese auto parts maker, failed
Thursday in his bid for an immediate seat on its board, the company
president said.
   In a meeting with president Takao Matsuura and other officers of
Koito Manufacturing Co., Pickens outlined his desire to participate
in the management of the company and requested a seat on the board,
but company officials declined to give him an immediate answer,
Matsuura told reporters.
   ``It is necessary to build a trusting relationship first. In
Japan, it is not possible to just say, `I'm a major shareholder'
and get a seat on the board right away,'' said Koito director
Tamotsu Aoyama.
   Koito officials are discussing whether to offer Pickens a board
seat.
   ``We don't necessarily understand his interest in managing our
company,'' Aoyama said. ``Mr. Pickens is known for his
qualifications in the oil business and in corporate buyouts, not in
manufacturing.''
   In a speech in Tokyo Wednesday, Pickens argued that companies
should be responsible first to their shareholders and only
secondarily to their management and employees _ an idea that flies
in the face of Japanese business culture.
   Pickens holds a 20.2 percent stake in Koito, which makes
headlights and other parts for Toyota Motor Co. Toyota owns 19.1
percent of the company.
   Pickens also has denied he is interested in greenmail, the
practice of seeking profits by buying up a company's shares until a
friendly shareholder steps in to buy them back at a premium.
   Koito and Toyota, its previous largest shareholder, had been the
victim of greenmail attempts by Azabu Motor, the auto retailer and
investment company from which Pickens bought his Koito stake,
analysts said.
   Pickens assured Koito's managment that he intended to be a
long-term shareholder and was not merely speculating, company
officials said.
   Matsuura said Pickens was welcome to buy more shares if he
intends to be a ``stable shareholder'' _ which in Japan means one
interested primarily in maintaining a business relationship rather
than reaping dividends or capital gains and who doesn't sell even
when the share price drops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
