<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Conrail     04-20 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Conrail,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conrail Reports 25 Percent Increase in First Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conrail reported a 25 percent increase in
first-quarter income, citing an increase in rates and an
improvement in the railroad's mix of freight.
   The railroad earned $60 million, or 88 cents a share, on revenue
of $872 million, compared with $48 million, or 69 cents a share, on
$831 million a year earlier.
   ``We are pleased with Conrail's first-quarter financial
performance,'' Stanley E.G. Hillman, Conrail's acting chairman,
president and chief executive officer, said Wednesday.
   ``An improving traffic mix and moderately higher freight rates
were the key reasons for the significantly high income,'' he said.
   Traffic was up in automotive parts and new vehicles, 14.6
percent; coal, 5.6 percent; intermodal, up 2.2 percent; and food
and grain, up 1.3 percent.
   Traffic dropped in forest products, down 8.2 percent; metals and
related products, down 4.3 percent; and chemicals and related
products, down 1.3 percent.
   James A. Hagen had been selected Conrail's new chairman,
president and chief executive officer. Hagen will assume his new
post May 18.
