<DOCNO> AP890420-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CincinnatiStockExchange Adv23   04-20 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cincinnati Stock Exchange, Adv 23,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Exchange of Tomorrow: 20 People Working Quietly in Downtown
Cincinnati</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Electronic Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's the only completely computerized U.S.
securities market and the only one that didn't get overwhelmed
during the October 1987 crash, while rivals in New York, Chicago,
Philadelphia and elsewhere foundered.
   But the Cincinnati Stock Exchange, a high-tech office couched in
the century-old Dixie Terminal Building overlooking the Ohio River,
remains relatively obscure and unknown to the broad investing
public. It's an identity problem that angers and frustrates the
exchange's president.
   ``It's time New York and the others recognized the time has
come,'' said Richard B. Niehoff, a third generation stockbroker who
left the family business, Weil Roth &amp; Irving, in 1979 to head the
Cincinnati market.
   Cincinnati was a small regional market handling mostly local
stocks and over-the-counter offerings until 1976 when the governors
voted to automate. They have updated and expanded several times,
the last in 1985.
   ``I saw back in the 1970s that this was where the market was
going. We had a membership here and New York and Philadelphia and I
could see this just wasn't going to keep on working,'' Niehoff said.
   ``I figured it would take about half a generation, about 10
years, when people would start feeling comfortable about punching
into a computer and that's about what it is taking,'' he said.
   Cincinnati has teamed up with the Chicago Board Options Exchange
and Reuters Holdings PLC to link the two exchanges with thousands
of computers around the world for trading 24 hours a day.
   The system is not expected to be operating until 1990. It will
need approval by the Securities and Exchange Commission. Meanwhile,
the trading hours will remain 9:30 a.m. until 4 p.m. Eastern time.
   The prospect of Cincinnati emerging as a key link to a world
trading market with immediate access to European and Asian
exchanges seems incongruous for this river city, known primarily to
outsiders as the home of Pete Rose's red-legged baseball team and
soap giant Procter &amp; Gamble Co.
   The exchange itself is a second-floor office staffed by 20
people, more than half of them hunched over computer terminal
screens in a silent, high-tech trading room, watching the automated
execution of orders placed electronically by buyers and sellers
nationwide. The staffers are watching for any unusual stock
activity that might indicate insider trading or other abuses.
   Niehoff said Cincinnati can handle up to 45 stock transactions
per second, far faster than the shouted orders and signals on Wall
Street.
   He noted that while the big exchanges have partly automated,
they still require personal contact between buyer and seller,
slowing everything.
   ``The big brokers like Merrill Lynch, PaineWebber and others
have already set up their own automated systems and have bigger
trading rooms than New York. If you put them all together they'd
make the New York Stock Exchange look like a second rate
ballroom,'' said Niehoff.
   End adv for Sunday, April 23
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890420-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-MemphisCotton Adv23   04-20 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Memphis Cotton, Adv 23,0801</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, April 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Times Have Changed in What Used to be World's Biggest Cotton Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Electronic Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MX3 of April 19</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the U.S. cotton business still is
handled by Memphis merchants, but the days are past when buyers and
sellers packed into the downtown Cotton Exchange to haggle over
prices or trade gossip.
   The big chalkboard, 50 feet long and 10 feet high, still
dominates one wall of the ``trading room,'' a high-ceilinged
flashback of brass fans and gracefully arched windows.
   But the real trading information comes by computer now, and most
of the exchange's 98 members have their own.
   ``They don't necessarily need to come to the floor now,'' said
Reta J. Martin, secretary of the exchange. ``It's just a
convenience for them to come in here and visit and talk.'
   The Cotton Exchange building, a 12-story, blond stone affair at
the corner of Front Street and Union Avenue in downtown Memphis,
was built in 1924 and is on the National Register of Historic
Places.
   The exchange itself was formed in 1873, and though the mechanics
of trading have changed, it still serves its original purpose of
organizing the city's cotton business.
   ``If a guy says I'll give you 61 cents a pound for your cotton
based on Memphis Cotton Exchange rules, everybody knows what you're
talking about,'' said W. Neely Mallory Jr., president of the
exchange. ``It sets a standard of rules by which cotton is traded.
It also tries to assure the fair treatment of one merchant with
another.''
   Exchange membership has dropped from 175 to 98 over the years,
largely because of bigger firms absorbing smaller ones, Ms. Martin
said.
   The business in Memphis is ``spot cotton,'' or cotton for
immediate delivery, though many members of the exchange deal in
futures trading too. A TV monitor mounted in a wall below the big
board carries figures from the Chicago futures market.
   Ron Cole, chief of the market news branch of the U.S. Department
of Agriculture in Memphis, said it's hard to get solid figures on
how much business the city's cotton merchants conduct, though they
obviously handle the majority of domestic spot sales.
   ``These firms are not willing to tell the government or anyone
else how much business they do,'' Cole said.
   The USDA keeps up with cotton production, he said, but a crop
can be bought and sold many times.
   Jess Barr, an economist with the National Cotton Council, said
all but two or three of the nation's largest cotton dealers are
members of the Memphis exchange.
   Bill Day, an exchange member for 40 years, estimated that 75
percent of the domestic spot cotton market is handled by Memphis
companies.
   ``This is my office,'' Day said, on one of his daily visits to
the trading room. ``I've got an office next door but I only go
there to pick up the mail.''
   Day, who describes himself as semi-retired, said the Memphis
exchange included a trading pit for cotton seed and soybean futures
in the 1950s, and two dozen representatives of Chicago futures
brokers worked the floor in the 1960s.
   The trading room still has a bank of telephone booths and a
dozen small windows once staffed by Western Union operators.
   Though some of the bigger companies are now in suburban business
centers, many exchange members still operate on Front Street, the
city's ``Cotton Row'' where bags of cotton samples called snakes
often are piled along the sidewalks.
   Robert Gardner, whose family company Gardner &amp; Son Inc. is on
Cotton Row, said smaller firms still rely on the exchange for
market information.
   ``I can come in here and find out some prices and what's been
selling recently, who might be buying and who might be selling,' he
said. ``But when you're an international grain company, you don't
need to come down here.''
   The trading room generally draws a dozen or so visitors for
brief visits each day, Ms. Martin said.
   In its heyday though, it drew packed crowds to watch the three
``walkers'' who manned the brass-railed walkway of the big board,
updating market figures from New York, Chicago and New Orleans as
well as Memphis.
   The exchange building too has changed from when it primarily
housed merchants, shippers and others in the cotton business. The
building was sold in 1983 to Memphis real estate developer Henry
Turley who refurbished it with an emphasis on brass, etched glass
and stone. It now houses a range of business offices, through the
exchange still holds the bottom floor.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, April 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
