<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Textron     04-20 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Textron,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Net Income Up Sharply In First Quarter, But Extraordinary Losses
Blamed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textron Inc. reported first-quarter
earnings Thursday that were about 64 percent higher than those of
the previous year, when two extraordinary expenses held the
company's performance down.
   For the three months ended April 1, 1989, Textron's net income
was $63.3 million, or 73 cents per share, compared with $38.7
million, or 43 cents per share, during the comparable 1988 period.
   The company's first-quarter 1988 income before the extraordinary
losses was $68.4 million or 76 cents per share. The extraordinary
losses were caused by an arbitrator's $20 million award against a
subsidiary and some early debt retirement.
   B.F. Dolan, chairman of the Providence-based conglomerate, said
increased shipments and profits at Textron's Bell Helicopter
subsidiary were offset by increased costs on other programs and the
completion last year of a military contract for aircraft wings.
   Earnings from Avdel PLC, a British fastening systems
manufacturing business that Textron bought in early 1989, were not
included in the report because the Federal Trade Commission has
ordered Textron not to exercise control over the company until it
considers the antitrust ramifications of the deal.
   Textron did list a $3.9 million interest expense stemming from
its acquisition of Avdel.
</TEXT>
