<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Caterpillar     04-20 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Caterpillar,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caterpillar Posts 19 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caterpillar Inc., a major manufacturer of
earth-moving equipment, Thursday said its first-quarter income rose
19.5 percent, reflecting higher domestic and international sales.
   The company said after-tax earnings came to $141 million, or
$1.39 a share, up from $118 million, or $1.16 a share, a year
earlier.
   Sales were $2.63 billion, an increase of $280 million, or 12
percent, over $2.35 billion in the corresponding 1988 quarter.
   Stronger demand and some rebuilding of dealer inventories were
responsible for the higher volume, the company said.
   ``Dealer sales increased significantly in most industrial
countries,'' the company said in a prepared announcement.
``Interest rates were relatively stable, and business profits
remained high. As a result, machine owners increased replacement
purchases,'' Caterpillar stated.
   ``In the developing countries, higher commodity prices resulted
in improved demand for Caterpillar products. In addition,
construction activity rebounded in some developing countries,
primarily in the Far East,'' Caterpillar said.
   Caterpillar's worldwide employment at the end of the first
quarter totaled 61,052 people, an increase of 494 from the end of
1988.
