<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-20 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed On Weather Uncertainty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
reflecting a mixed bag of weather forecasts for key U.S.
crop-growing areas.
   Corn and wheat futures were slightly lower while soybeans and
oats were mostly higher.
   The National Weather Service issued a six-to-10-day forecast
late Wednesday that predicted above-normal rainfall next week in
the corn-and-soybean country of the western Midwest and the
winter-wheat fields of the central Great Plains, two areas where
drought conditions have persisted for nearly a year.
   But many private forecasters still foresee very little
precipitation for the western Corn Belt, where farmers are just
beginning their spring planting.
   A 10-day-old dockworkers' strike in Brazil, the world's
second-largest soybean producer, is increasingly supportive for the
soybean market. But weather ``is the single biggest influence
overall,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader in Chicago with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.10{ a bushel; corn was unchanged
to 1\ cents lower with May at $2.73 a bushel; oats were } cent to
