<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Autos     04-20 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Autos,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM 1st Quarter Earnings Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. on Thursday reported that
continuing strong performance overseas helped push first-quarter
earnings up 42.2 percent over last year, when the company realized
benefits from a one-time accounting change.
   The nation's largest corporation said it earned $1.55 billion,
or $2.37 a share, during the January-March period this year,
compared with $1.09 billion, or $1.56 a share, during the same
period last year.
   GM sales during the first three months of this year, excluding
its vehicle-financing arm and other financing operations, rose 11.9
percent to $29.6 billion from $26.44 billion during the same time
last year.
   Earnings and sales figures for last year reflect the accounting
change GM adopted Jan. 1, 1988. The per-share earnings figures for
both periods reflect a 2-for-1 stock split which was effective
March 31, 1989.
   GM said its overseas earnings during the first quarter this year
exceeded the record first-quarter amount earned last year. GM also
said its North American operations, which had been lagging
recently, contributed significantly to first-quarter profits.
   The company also said that during this year's first quarter, it
cut costs by about $1 billion. That brings to $9.5 billion the
company said it has cut in a program aimed at slashing $12.5
billion to $13 billion by the end of 1990.
   GM also said its sales to dealers were up 6.2 percent in the
first quarter compared with last year. But there has been
speculation that GM will have to trim production during the second
half of the year because of lower-than-expected first-quarter sales.
   At the end of March, GM, Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. began
new incentive programs designed to shrink inventories while keeping
production levels up. The effects of the incentives, which normally
eat into profits, aren't clear yet.
   Ford is expected to issue its first-quarter earnings next week,
and Chrysler a week after that.
</TEXT>
