<FIRST>r f PM-Dunkin'Donuts     04-20 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dunkin' Donuts,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Acquires 6.6 Percent of Dunkin' Donuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Toronto-based investment bank has acquired 6.6
percent of Dunkin Donuts Inc. in a possible bid to gain control of
the doughnut chain, a bank official said today.
   Kingsbridge Capital Group, an affiliate of Unicorp Canada Corp.,
filed papers with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission
Wednesday as required when companies acquire more than a 5 percent
position in another company, said Kingsbridge spokesman Eric Evans.
   The merchant bank also announced plans to continue buying stock
in Dunkin' Donuts, which is based in Randolph, Mass. Dunkin' Donuts
stock is traded over the counter.
   As of today, Kingsbridge has spent $13.4 million in buying
422,000 shares of Dunkin' Donuts, 6.6 percent of the shares
outstanding as of Feb. 28.
   A spokesman for Dunkin' Donuts did not immediately return a
telephone call seeking comment.
   In its SEC filing, Kingsbridge listed as its options, ``among
other possibilities, to purchase additional shares or dispose of
some or all of the shares then held, seek control of (Dunkin'
Donuts) through a tender offer, merger, recapitalization, proxy
contest or otherwise, or seek possible improvements in the
profitability and market value,'' of Dunkin' Donuts.
   Kingsbridge plans to file a formal report with the Federal Trade
Commission and the Antitrust Division of the U.S. Department of
Justice under federal antitrust laws laws that relate to
acquisition of more than $15 million but less than 15 percent of
outstanding shares.
   Because of antitakeover provisions in the bylaws of Dunkin'
Donuts and a shareholder rights plan, Kingsbridge said in its SEC
filing, Kingsbridge has no immediate plan to acquire 15 percent or
more of Dunkin' Donuts.
</TEXT>
