<HEAD>Digital Reports Continued Fall In Earnings, Blaming Slow U.S. Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp.'s profit fell 16 percent in its latest
quarter, depressed by continued slow U.S. sales, the world's second
biggest computer maker said Thursday.
   Investors were prepared for the bad news and the stock was up
37{ cents a share at $99.37{ in midday trading on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   For the third fiscal quarter ended April 1, earnings fell to
$256.4 million, or $2.05 a share, from $305.1 million, or $2.33 a
share, on revenue of $2.8 billion, the Maynard, Mass.-based company
said.
   Revenue rose 10.7 percent to $3.13 billion from $2.82 billion a
year earlier.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, earnings fell 16.1
percent to $759.4 million, or $5.94 per share, from $904.6 million,
or $6.83 per share for the same nine months in 1988. Revenue rose
13.7 percent to $9.25 billion from $8.14 billion a year earlier.
   Digital, No. 2 in size behind International Business Machines
Corp., has suffered lagging earnings, and its stock price is about
half its peak of $199 a share in August 1987.
   Foreign business accounted for 57 percent of Digital's business
in the last quarter.
   Analysts said the company's U.S. results are suffering from
customer confusion over its new products and predicted the domestic
business would recover eventually.
   ``It looks a lot worse than it really is,'' said Terry Shannon,
an analyst at International Data Corp.
   Laura Conigliaro, a Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. analyst,
said the company had done a good job of reducing costs. But she
said, ``It certainly smacks you in the face'' how sluggish U.S.
sales were.
