<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv22   04-20 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 22 ,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release AMs Saturday, April 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S Leads World in Service Exports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hidden in the U.S. trade deficit statistics is
an area of strength that seldom if ever is revealed by traditional
measurements: The United States leads all other nations in the
export of services.
   Very little is ever said about this, simply because the usual
measurements emphasize goods. It is the same throughout the economy
_ you hear about the industrial production index but never about a
service production index.
   In spite of this, the majority of the American labor force and
most of the capital is utilized in the service sector. It isn't
true that America is doing less manufacturing, but it is true that
it is becoming more service oriented.
   Services? Think of all the services you buy _ medical, legal,
recreational, educational, transportation. Government is a service.
The tax preparer is a dispenser of services. Your insurance agent
and stockbroker are servicers.
   Among the service categories are transportation, communication,
electric, gas and sanitary services; wholesale trade; retail trade;
finance, insurance and real estate; personal and social services;
and public administration.
   Recognition of the importance of services is slow to develop,
however, not so much among the mass of Americans but among public
servants and their agencies. There is, for example, no official
services production index.
   That gap in economic measurements is now being corrected, not
solely by government but by the Coalition of Service Industries,
formed in 1982 by independent dispensers and users of services.
Public awareness is the goal.
   In pursuing that goal, they have just issued a report on the
international trade in services, written by economists Allen Sinai
and Zaharo Sofianou of the Boston Company Economic Advisors Inc.
Among the findings:
   _By country, the largest service exporter is the United States,
which accounted for 17.4 percent of total world service exports in
1987, followed by the United Kingdom, with a 12.4 percent share.
   _The United States had a favorable service export trade balance
of $19.7 billion in 1987. Canada, Japan and Australia had service
export deficits.
   _By country, the United States is not only the world's largest
service exporter and importer, but through 1987 had the world's
largest service trade surplus.
   In terms of public understanding, service exports and imports
don't break down as neatly as do domestic services, but they are
services nevertheless. Being intangible, they certainly cannot be
classified as goods. Sinai and Sofianou defined them as activities
involving the international transfer of money in return for
non-tangible benefits.
   And those benefits?
   The first category is shipment charges, including freight fees
and often the insurance costs of exporting merchandise. Next is
``other transportation,'' which is the price for transporting goods
for other countries.
   Travel is a big and rapidly growing item. Income on investments
made abroad is an important item. Interest income on foreign
securities is a major item, as is income from government services.
   A large category, ``Other Private Receipts on Services,''
includes a miscellaneous assemblage of services provided to
foreigners, including advertising, business and legal help.
   In such areas does the United States excel, even if it has been
unable to correct its imbalance of trade in goods. Unfortunately,
the news isn't all good: While it leads the world in service
exports, that lead is deteriorating.
   In 1981, the United States had a service export trade balance of
$42.1 billion, more than double the figure for 1987. Japan,
meanwhile, reduced its services trade deficit from $13.5 billion in
1981 to to $5.9 billion in 1987.
   Even more significant is the improvement in service trade
balances of developing nations. In 1981 they had a $108.5 billion
deficit. After remaining above $100 billion through 1984, the
deficit fell to $69.9 billion in 1987.
   The main factor contributing to the deterioration of the U.S.
position, Sinai and Sofianou said, is the higher payments to
foreigners for their holdings of U.S. securities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, April 21.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890420-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Europe-InterestRates     04-20 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Europe-Interest Rates,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Central Bank Hikes Key Rates, Others Follow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's central bank, citing continued
high monetary growth, unexpectedly raised key interest rates
Thursday, spurring other European banks to follow suit.
   The moves pushed the U.S. dollar to its lowest levels since
early March.
   The Bundesbank said it raised the discount rate 0.5 percentage
point to 4.5 percent and the Lombard rate to 6.5 percent from 6.0
percent to further curb above-target monetary growth. High
money-supply growth could fuel inflation.
   The Lombard rate is used for emergency funding and typically is
higher than the discount rate.
   The Bundesbank noted in a statement that ``monetary expansion in
the Federal Republic continues to be stronger than justifiable in a
stability-oriented policy.''
   The moves were followed by the Dutch central bank, which raised
its discount rate half a point to 5.5 percent. The Austrian
National Bank raised its discount and Lombard rates half a point to
5.0 percent and 6.5 percent, respectively.
   An official in France said the government isn't planning to
tighten its credit policy to match the Bundesbank's move. ``We
aren't dependent on the Germans,'' an Economics Ministry official
said, but he did not rule out a French rate hike if the franc's
stability were endangered or if inflationary pressures surface.
   Although the Swiss National Bank last week boosted its discount
rate half a point to 4.5 percent and the Lombard rate one point to
7.0 percent, financial markets were taken by surprise by Thursday's
apparently coordinated interest-rate action.
   The dollar fell more than 1.5 pfennigs to 1.8430 marks, its
lowest level since it finished at 1.8368 marks on March 1 in New
York.
   ``I don't think anyone expected this,'' said a foreign exchange
trader at a large Frankfurt bank. ``The market was totally relaxed.
There was no tension, no speculation, no pressure at all. The
Bundesbank has been saying for the last two months that there's no
inflation angst, that they'll keep close tabs on inflation, but at
the moment there's nothing to worry about.''
   Indeed, Bundesbank Vice President Helmut Schlesinger said as
recently as last week that the central bank saw no need to raise
interest rates at present.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
