<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-BankAmerica     04-20 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-BankAmerica,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>BankAmerica First-Quarter Earnings Leap 152 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BankAmerica Corp.'s turnaround continued in
the first quarter this year with record earnings of $275 million, a
152 percent increase from $109 million a year ago, the company
reported today.
   The parent of Bank of America, which lost $955 million in 1987
but rebounded last year to post a profit of $726 million, marked a
milestone in its recovery in the quarter when it reinstated a
dividend on its common stock.
   Earnings per common share were $1.38 in the first quarter, up
146 percent from 56 cents in the same period a year ago.
   ``Growth in net interest income, improved credit quality,
control over operating expenses, and the hard work and excellent
performance of our employees were key factors in the quarter's
achievements,'' said A.W. Clausen, BankAmerica chairman.
   Earnings in the first quarter included $46 million of Brazilian
cash interest payments, which increased net income by $38 million.
   The bank also benefited from higher interest rates as its net
interest margin climbed to 4.60 percent in the quarter, up from
3.66 percent for the same period last year.
   The provision for credit losses was $110 million for the
quarter, compared with $115 million for the same period last year
and $1.1 billion in all of 1987.
   Noninterest income, mostly from fees and commissions, in the
first quarter was $436 million, up $12 million from the first
quarter last year.
</TEXT>
