<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange fell
sharply Thursday following news that the West German central bank
raised its key discount rate by half a percentage point to 4.5
percent.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 22.6
points, or 1.1 percent, at 2,064.4. The index plunged as much as
33.5 points at late afternoon as the impact of the West German rate
move rippled through the market. At its best, the index was up 6.1
points shortly after the opening.
   Volume fell to 542.2 million shares from Wednesday's 663.7
million shares.
   The interest rate rise knocked the pound down against the
Deutsche mark, renewing fears that British interest rates might
soon be headed higher as well.
   ``Given where we see the currency at the moment, investors will
certainly be more worried about a rise in (British bank) base
rates,'' said Bill Smith, a market analyst at Prudential-Bache
Capital Funding (Equities) Ltd. in London.
   However dealers noted there was scant selling pressure to push
prices lower. Prices recovered from their lowest levels as
institutional investors entered the market to buy up some stock at
bargain prices.
