<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Chemicals     04-20 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Chemicals,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Earnings Up 46.6 Percent In 1st Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Chemical Co. said Thursday its
first-quarter earnings rose 46.6 percent over the same period last
year, based partly on a strong increase in the company's core
chemical sales.
   Dow said it earned $743 million, or $4.08 a share, during the
January-March period this year, compared with earnings of $507
million, or $2.67 a share, during the same time last year.
   First-quarter sales of $4.49 billion this year set a company
record and were 12.7 percent over 1988 first-quarter sales of $3.98
billion.
   ``While rising interest rates in the U.S. may constrain the
interest-sensitive sectors of the economy,'' Dow President and
Chief Executive Officer Frank Popoff said in a statement, ``I'm
confident 1989 will be another record year for Dow based on the
quality of the first-quarter results and the continuing strength of
our global business.''
   The statement said sales in Dow's chemicals and performance
products segment rose 14 percent. Sales in Dow's plastics business
rose 11 percent and the company's consumer specialties segment
sales rose 9 percent.
   Part of the consumer products sales increase was offset by
promotional costs associated with the launch of Spiffits, a line of
toweletts premoistened with a variety of cleaning substances.
</TEXT>
