<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-20 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Close Lower On Rain Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices closed moderately lower
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade following a National Weather
Service forecast for above-average precipitation next week in the
wheat fields of Kansas.
   Corn futures finished little changed, oats were higher and
soybeans were mixed, reflecting varied weather forecasts for the
Midwest, where spring planting is beginning.
   The Kansas winter-wheat crop has suffered through a cold, dry
winter and a relatively dry spring, giving rise to fears that much
of the crop could be lost.
   Wednesday's six-to-10-day forecast from the weather service
predicted above-normal precipitation in the region during the
middle portion of next week, easing some of the crop-damage fears.
   The weather service also predicted normal to above-normal
rainfall in the Midwest next week but many private meteorologists
foresee little rain.
   In addition to weather factors, soybean prices were buoyed by
rumors of new export business and by wire-service reports of high
radiation levels in western Russia almost three years after the
Chernobyl nuclear accident, which contaminated some of the Soviet
Union's best agricultural land.
   At the close, wheat was 2} cents to 4 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.09 a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to } cent higher with May at $2.73 a bushel; oats were 1 cent
to 2 cents higher with May at $1.98 a bushel; soybeans were 3\
cents lower to 6 cents higher with May at $7.48 a bushel.
</TEXT>
