<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Drexel     04-20 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Drexel,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drexel Burnham To Close London Equity Trading Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. said Thursday it would
close its London equity trading operations as part of the
restructuring of its worldwide business.
   Drexel said it would cease researching and making markets in
non-U.S. stocks from April 28. The company said it would try to
redeploy the 40 affected people elsewhere in the Drexel group.
   Drexel on Tuesday announced a major restructuring, involving the
sale of its retail brokerage operations and cutbacks in several
other areas. The move followed Drexel's settlement last week of
civil charges of violating securities laws, which were filed by the
U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The firm blamed the restructuring on economic conditions and the
regulatory problems stemming from the SEC investigation of its U.S.
junk bond activities.
   Drexel's British equity operations are relatively small.
   Unlike some other U.S. investment firms, Drexel didn't purchase
a British brokerage in the run-up to the market deregulation of
October 1986, known as the Big Bang. Instead Drexel built up the
operations gradually, and currently makes markets in about 60
British stocks and 90 other European shares.
   Drexel said it would maintain its fixed income, commodities,
corporate finance and U.S. equity trading operations in London.
</TEXT>
