<FIRST>r f AM-JobStudy     04-20 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Job Study,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: 2.6 Million New Jobs To Be Created in 1989</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Hold for release until 6 p.m. EST Thursday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small businesses should contribute more than
half of the 2.6 million new jobs estimated to be created this year,
according to a study released Thursday.
   But Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp.'s annual survey of 5,000 firms noted
that the number of new jobs employers expect to create is down 26
percent from the 3.6 million new jobs actually created last year.
   While the slowdown had been expected, Dun &amp; Bradstreet corporate
economist Joseph Duncan said the forecast for 1989 ``is still
remarkably strong, especially in view of the substantial growth in
new jobs already achieved during the current economic expansion.''
   Since 1983, between 2 million and 4 million new jobs have been
created each year, he noted.
   Businesses with fewer than 100 employees will account for 56.6
percent of all the new jobs created this year, Dun &amp; Bradstreet
said. While firms with fewer than 20 workers said they plan to
increase employment by 3.5 percent, corporations with more than
25,000 employees expect their payrolls to increase by 0.8 percent.
   The survey showed that new positions in the wholesale, retail
and services sector should account for 56.5 percent of the overall
job gain; manufacturing jobs will account for 19.1 percent; while
finance, insurance and real estate positions will account for 8.9
percent of the year's employment gains.
</TEXT>
