<DOCNO> AP890420-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 2009EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Whittle     04-20 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whittle,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Does Not Need Support Of Education Groups, Whittle Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whittle Communications LP does not need
the support of national education groups to have a successful
satellite news program in the country's classrooms, the company
chairman says.
   Chris Whittle said the Knoxville media company will spend the
next several months deciding if it wants to try to sell the news
concept to 10,000 school boards across the country.
   Testing of the daily 12-minute news programs, called Channel
One, ends Friday at six schools. Each program includes two minutes
of advertisements.
   Whittle, speaking Wednesday to an entrepreneurship class at
Belmont College, said he's optimistic Channel One will be continued.
   After the class, Whittle said he didn't anticipate the
controversy that has arisen about the news programs. He said he was
particularly upset by people who opposed the programs before they
viewed them or talked to anyone who did.
   ``They took a position before they did their homework,'' Whittle
said.
   Channel One can work without support from national education
groups because education ``is still locally controlled,'' he said.
   But he acknowledged, ``Having them against us doesn't make our
jobs any easier.''
   Whittle Communications has offered to install about $50,000
worth of video equipment in schools to beam in the news programs.
   But groups such as the National Association of Secondary School
Principals and the National Parent-Teacher Association objected to
the commercials, saying it was unfair to subject students to paid
advertising in classrooms.
   Whittle has said it plans to review resaearch compiled during
the seven-week test and talk with teachers, administrators and
students at the six test schools before deciding if it will make
the program available nationally in the fall of 1990. The company
also must determine if there is enough advertising support to
finance a national rollout. Equipment alone for the schools could
cost more than $100 million.
   The six test schools are in Knoxville; Kansas City, Kan.;
Cerritos, Calif.; Billerica, Mass.; Cincinnati and Detroit.
   On another topic, Whittle said the company probably will turn
the unprofitable ``Tennessee Illustrated'' publication into a
quarterly, rather than continue it as a bi-monthly.
   He said a major problem with the state magazine was that ``we
misjudged the size of our market.'' Finding advertisers for a
statewide audience, he said, has been difficult.
   Whittle Communications, founded in 1970 by Whittle and several
former University of Tennessee classmates, has pioneered a niche in
publishing by using single advertisers in its magazines, videos and
other products.
   The company's magazines are not sold through subscriptions or
newsstands, like typical publications but are available for free in
places such as doctors' offices and hairstyling salons.
   The company also uses one or a small number of advertisers each
giving exclusivity in their product categories in its 40 media
products.
   Whittle announced Tuesday it will begin producing short books
with advertisements beginning this fall.
   The books will have about 20 percent advertising and will be
written by prominent figures such as David Halberstam and John
Kenneth Galbraith.
   Whittle said the company's market research showed that many
people don't have time for lengthy non-fiction books and that they
will not object to ads in books.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890420-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1656EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     04-20 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $805 Million in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 468 money market mutual
funds rose $805 million in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The increase, to $303.45 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $1.33 billion gain in the funds' assets the
previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade
group.
   The rise, from the previous record of $302.51 billion set last
week, marked the 15th straight weekly all-time high for the funds'
assets and reflected the growing attraction of interest bearing
investments due to rising interest rates.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 233 general purpose funds rose $192.3 million to $99.82
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds increased $372.2 million
to $130.25 billion, and assets of 140 institutional funds went up
$240.5 million to $73.38 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds
increased in the week ended Tuesday to 9.19 percent from 9.14
percent the previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund
Report, a trade journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 9.11 percent from 9.04 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds
lengthened to 34 days from 32 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts edged up
to 6.62 percent as of Wednesday from 6.61 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, stayed at 5.14 percent for the third straight week.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 9.34
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, the same as the
previous week. Yields were 9.51 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 9.50
percent; 9.33 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 9.32 percent; and
9.20 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 9.21 percent.
</TEXT>
