<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   04-20 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices retreated Thursday as an unexpected
increase in West German interest rates put the dollar under
pressure in foreign exchange.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had risen 90.91
points over the four previous sessions, dropped 9.53 to 2,377.38.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
599 up, 852 down and 517 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 175.97 million
shares, down from 191.51 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 208.04 million shares.
   Prices rose at the outset, but abruptly reversed course after
West Germany's central bank announced increases in its official
interest rates.
   The dollar fell in foreign exchange, and U.S. open-market
interest rates headed higher.
   Analysts cited fears that the Bundesbank's action would require
higher interest rates in this country to enable the dollar to hold
its ground against leading foreign currencies.
   Even if the dollar doesn't weaken further, many observers said
the higher rates in West Germany significantly reduced any chance
that the Federal Reserve might ease U.S. credit policy any time in
the near future.
   In addition, brokers said some traders were eager to cash in on
the market's recent gains with stocks at their highest levels in
more than 18 months.
   Digital Equipment bucked the downtrend, climbing | to 99| in
active trading. The company reported earnings for the fiscal
quarter ended April 1 of $2.05 a share.
   That was down from $2.33 a share in the comparable period a year
earlier, but still better than most analysts had expected.
   Navistar led the active list, down { at 5{. The company said it
has reduced its internal earnings forecasts for the current quarter
and the full fiscal year that ends Oct. 31.
   Weyerhaueser jumped 3\ to 30\. The company reported
first-quarter profits of 70 cents a share, up from 54 cents in the
like period last year.
   Harnischfeger gained 2| to 19\ amid takeover speculation. The
company said it had no plans for anything that would explain the
rise in its stock price.
   John Fluke Manufacturing, traded on the American Stock Exchange,
rose 3\ to 24. The company began a tender offer for 1.5 million
shares of its stock in a price range of $22 to $25 apiece.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $5.07 billion, or 0.17
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .40 to 171.30.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell .92 to 353.38, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was down .96 at 306.19.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
slipped .40 to 421.51. At the Amex, the market value index closed
at 341.33, up .90.
</TEXT>
