<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TeachersAd Bjt   04-20 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teachers Ad, Bjt,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Tell Businesses To `Think Again' Before Locating In Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of disgruntled Washington teachers
warn in a newspaper advertisement that businesses considering
expanding into the state to ``think again.''
   ``Our educational system is in decline. ... We can't guarantee
you a quality worker because our state won't pay for quality
schools,'' said the ad placed in Thursday's West Coast edition of
The Wall Street Journal.
   It placed much of the blame on Gov. Booth Gardner and the state
Legislature. A spokesman for the governor called the ad
counterproductive.
   Jon Holdaway, a vocal-arts and drama teacher at Cedarcrest
Junior High School in Spanaway, just south of Tacoma, purchased the
ad on behalf of a group called Washington Teachers United For Fully
Funded Schools.
   He said about 500 teachers helped pay $1,400 to place the ad,
which was carried in the Journal's edition distributed in 13
Western states, including Alaska and Hawaii.
   Holdaway said it was unrealistic to think the ad would change
any businessman's mind in expanding business into Washington.
However, he said, ``I do fear that in the future businesses won't
be able to get qualified workers, and that's a far greater threat
to business in our state.''
   The ad said Washington has the fourth-largest class size in the
nation, ranks 46th in textbook purchases per student and 50th in
change in teacher salaries.
   One-fourth of the state's school buildings are unsafe or
inadequate, the ad said, adding, ``Our governor and Legislature
refuse to support full funding of our public schools.''
   Gardner and the Legislature, whose annual session ends after
this week, have been considering various proposal for funding
education, none of which are considered full support.
   Teachers have criticized Gardner for refusing to appropriate
part of a $400 million state budget windfall to boost teachers'
salaries.
   ``We have an image, `Come to Washington because we have a
well-educated population,''' Holdaway said. ``But we have a
mediocre education system in this state. It used to be one of the
best.''
   Holdaway cited as his sources various studies done by the
National Education Association, the Education Writers Association
and the Corporation for Enterprise Development.
   Dick Milne, spokesman for Gardner, said the governor considers
education a priority. ``We acknowledge that there are some areas
that we would like to do better,'' he said. ``Class size is one of
those. Teacher salaries is another.''
   Senate Ways and Means Committee Chairman Dan McDonald,
R-Bellevue, defended legislative action, saying the Senate's
version of a state budget now in conference with the House contains
$512 million in enhancements for education.
   Richard Page, chief administrator of the Washington Roundtable,
which represents business interests in the education system, said
the ad does identify serious weaknesses in the system.
   ``It's a bit alarmist, but I applaud him,'' Page said. ``There
are lots of ways to quibble with his points. It's easy to say he's
off base. But the Roundtable and business in general agree there
are serious flaws in our public education system.''
   Page said, however, that Holdaway and the teachers group were
misrepresenting Washington's educational system by excluding some
of its strengths. For example, state residents have completed more
years of schooling than residents of at least 45 other states, and
its Scholastic Achievement Tests consistently are above average, he
said.
   Ronn Robinson, Gardner's education assistant, was less
understanding about the one-sided picture Holdaway painted.
   ``I think it's unfortunate that he feels impelled to take out
such an ad, which misrepresents the degree to which our schools are
(standing) compared to others,'' Robinson said. ``Our salaries are
not as bad as this ad implies.''
   Cliff Finch, legislative affairs counsel for the Association of
Washington Business, said he believed readers would not take the ad
seriously.
   ``I think the readership of that newspaper is too sophisticated
to take that (ad) at face value,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
