<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1743EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-FordOilChanges Bjt   04-20 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford Oil Changes, Bjt,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Gets Into Quickie Oil Change Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. says it had jumped into the
growing quick oil-change business, a move that could affect
thousands of small businesses nationwide.
   ``I hope it hurts him,'' service manager Harold Grass of
Fairlane Ford in Dearborn, Mich., said of a Quaker State Minit-lube
shop across Michigan Avenue from his dealership.
   Apparently, it already has.
   ``It's slowed down some,'' Minit-lube employee Ken Matchette
said Thursday.
   Even though Grass has had his quick oil-change business running
since October, he's still only getting a fraction of the business
that the Minit-lube enjoys. Fairlane Ford averages about 15 of the
fast oil changes a day, compared with 70 to 80 daily at Minit-lube.
   John Kerekanich, accessory merchandising manager for Ford's
parts and service division, said quick oil-change service
operations began in the early 1980s and have grown steadily since
then. He speculated there would be about 6,000 of them nationwide
by 1992.
   Like the smaller, stand-alone oil-change operations, he added,
no appointment is necessary, the work will be done within 15
minutes and will cost about $20.
   Grass said his dealership completes the average oil change in
seven or eight minutes and charges $19.95, $2 less than the
Minit-lube.
   Ford's pilot program began last June with five dealers in
Chicago and expanded to 25 nationwide in October, Kerekanich said.
Ford expects the program to grow to about 35 percent of its 5,600
Ford and Lincoln-Mercury dealers in the United States.
   He said not all dealers are suited for the program, which will
require a separate area in the service bay and a separate billing
area _ the main reasons Chrysler Corp. hasn't gotten into the
business.
   ``Our feeling is that there are some difficulties that have not
been resolved yet in terms of being able to match the
convenience,'' of the drive-through operations, Chrysler spokesman
Tom Houston said. He said the company did a survey of dealerships a
few years ago and found no overwhelming desire for such a
corporation-sponsored service.
   General Motors Corp. spokesman Duane Poole said the nation's
largest automaker is looking into the matter, but did not
anticipate a decision soon.
   Kerekanich said a Ford dealer could invest up to $22,000 to
start the quick oil-change operation, depending on the available
facilities. Grass converted an unused car-wash bay, cutting his
initial costs. He also said he has hired two people just for the
oil change operation.
   Kerekanich also said Ford is encouraging its dealers to offer
the service to all makes and models of cars, something that Grass
has declined.
   ``Sorry ... Ford and Lincoln-Mercury vehicles only,'' he said.
</TEXT>
