<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-NWA     04-20 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-NWA,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>NWA Reports $12.6 Million First-Quarter Profit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Northwest-Davis, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NWA Inc., parent of Northwest Airlines
and the target of a hostile takeover, Thursday reported its largest
first-quarter profit of the decade.
   Billionaire oilman Marvin Davis on Thursday launched a
$90-a-share hostile tender offer for NWA. The company's board of
directors earlier rejected a similar offer as inadequate.
   First-quarter net earnings of $12.6 million, or 43 cents a
share, marked the first time in four years NWA has posted
first-quarter net earnings, the company said.
   The $12.6 million profit compares with a net loss of $43.5
million in the first quarter of 1988.
   ``These results counter our traditional financial performance in
a cyclical industry where the first quarter, with its lower travel
demand, has typically resulted in net losses,'' said Steve
Rothmeier, NWA chairman and chief executive officer. ``In fact, our
earnings for the first three months of 1989 are outstanding
first-quarter results.''
   First-quarter revenue increased 19.3 percent to $1.48 billion
from $1.24 billion a year earlier.
   The quarter was marked by double-digit growth in both passenger
and freight revenue, the company said.
   ``Hand-in-hand with these solid financial results is growing
evidence of the quality of our customer service,'' Rothmeier said.
   ``The most recent government statistics reveal Northwest as the
nation's second most on-time airline, exceeding the industry
average on-time performance by 8 percentage points,'' he said.
</TEXT>
