<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 1812EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     04-20 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All three measures of the nation's money supply
rose in early April, the Federal Reserve Board reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose
$500 million in the week ended April 10 to a seasonally adjusted
$781.5 billion from $781.0 billion the previous week.
   The central bank said a broader measure called M2 rose $2
billion to a seasonally adjusted $3,084.3 billion from $3,082.3
billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, rose $7.7 billion to a seasonally
adjusted $3,966.3 billion from $3,958.6 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   The Fed in February reaffirmed a provisional target for 1989 of
3 percent to 7 percent growth in M2 and 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent
growth in M3. The Fed has not set a target for M1 growth since
early 1987.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,073.8 billion, a 1.9
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous
13 weeks. M3 averaged $3,942.3 billion, up 3.7 percent, while M1
fell 0.9 percent to an average of $786.0 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window, excluding extended credit,
averaged $997 million a day in the week ended Wednesday, up from
$227 million the previous week and the highest since borrowings
averaged $1.37 billion in the week ended Jan. 4.
   The Fed said the heavy borrowings in the latest week were due
mostly to a surge in borrowings Wednesday night reflecting a
scarcity of funds in the federal funds market, wherte banks loan to
each other ovbernight.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $287.5 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, down from $288.0 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
