<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     04-20 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Advance On German Rate Hike, Fusion Speculation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold and silver futures prices rose moderately Thursday on New
York's Commodity Exchange after surprise increases in two key West
German interest rates knocked down the dollar.
   Meanwhile, platinum and palladium prices surged on the New York
Mercantile Exchange on renewed speculative buying linked to recent
nuclear-fusion experiments.
   On other markets, petroleum prices were broadly mixed; wheat
prices fell while most other grains and soybeans advanced; and
livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Gold settled $2.20 to $2.60 higher with the contract for
delivery in June at $389.30 a troy ounce; silver was 2.2 cents to
2.6 cents higher with May at $5.787 a troy ounce.
   The rise in gold and silver prices corresponded with a drop in
the dollar's value against other major currencies following
increases of 0.5 percent in the West German discount rate and West
Germany's equivalent of the prime lending rate.
   Currency traders responded to the increased lending rates by
buying West German marks and selling U.S. dollars. A weaker dollar
promotes foreign purchases of U.S. goods, which helps the U.S.
economy and could lead to higher inflation in this country.
   Gold and silver are generally viewed as investment hedges
against inflation, so demand for the metals tends to rise and fall
with inflationary expectations.
   A sharp increase in crude-oil and unleaded gasoline prices also
fanned inflation fears and contributed to gold's rally, analysts
said.
   Peter Cardillo, commodities trading adviser with Josephthal &amp;
Co. in New York, said gold's chart patterns indicated a bullish
trend in the making. He noted that gold for June delivery had
bottomed out at $385.70 an ounce on Wednesday and $385.80 an ounce
on Thursday, indicating the market was unlikely to fall below that
area.
   ``We've formed a good bottom here and I think this market is
getting ready to surprise everyone,'' Cardillo said.
   Jitters about cold-fusion research persisted in the platinum and
palladium markets. Both metals have been used in recent experiments
in which scientists claim to have recreated in a jar of water the
nuclear reaction that powers the sun and stars.
   Platinum settled $6.70 to $8.20 higher with July at $556.20 a
troy ounce; palladium was $7.80 higher across the board with June
at $174.85 a troy ounce.
   Crude-oil and unleaded gasoline futures rose sharply on the New
York Merc on supply fears linked to the shutdown of a North Sea oil
rig Tuesday following an explosion.
   Heating oil futures prices fell, though, reflecting expectations
for more spring-like weather in the northeastern United States.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent lower to 47
cents higher with June at $21.28 a barrel; heating oil was was .40
cent to 1.04 cents lower with May at 52.29 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .75 cent lower to 1.13 cents higher with May at 74.64
cents a gallon.
   Wheat futures moved lower on the Chicago Board of Trade
following a National Weather Service forecast for above-average
precipitation next week in the wheat fields of Kansas.
   Corn futures finished little changed while oats and soybeans
were slightly higher, reflecting conflicting weather forecasts for
the Midwest, where spring planting is beginning.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 4 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in May at $4.09\ a bushel; corn was { cent lower to } cent
higher with May at $2.72} a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 2{ cents
higher with May at $1.98 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 5
cents higher with May at $7.47{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures finished mostly higher on firmer cash markets and
perceptions that Wednesday's steep losses were overdone.
   Frozen pork bellies fell to new life-of-contract lows for the
second consecutive day amid expectations that Friday's monthly cold
storage report from the Agriculture Department will show record
levels of bellies in the nation's commercial freezers.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent lower to .55 cent higher with June
at 71.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .25
cent higher with May at 75.62 cents a pound; live hogs were .43
cent lower to .15 cent higher with June at 45.47 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .65 cent lower to .05 cent higher with May
at 30.95 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
