<FIRST>u f AM-Dunkin'Donuts 1stLd-Writethru f0193 04-20 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dunkin' Donuts, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0193,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Acquires 6.6 Percent of Dunkin' Donuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs with closing stock price; PICKS UP 11th graf
pvs, `Dunkin' Donuts...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dunkin' Donuts Inc. said Thursday it will sell
more than a million shares of stock to employees and cut its
corporate work force 14 percent after a Toronto-based investment
bank made hostile overtures for the doughnut giant.
   Dunkin' Donuts said it would fight any takeover bid by
Kingsbridge Capital Group, a subsidiary of Unicorp Canada Corp.,
which said it acquired a 6.6 percent stake and may seek control of
the doughnut maker with more than 1,700 stores worldwide.
   ``We don't know who these people are,'' said Richard N. Hart
Jr., Dunkin' Donuts vice president and treasurer. ``Our intention,
of course, has been to still be an independent company.''
   Dunkin' Donuts _ whose ads feature a man rising in the middle of
the night because he's ``gotta go make the doughnuts'' _ announced
it was consolidating doughnut shop operations and trimming its
corporate work force by about 80 people.
   The company said it plans to sell 1.1 million shares of common
stock to employees and to continue purchasing its stock on the open
market, in two apparent antitakeover measures.
   It also said it amended its bylaws to allow stockholders to buy
twice their holdings if a single buyer acquires 15 percent of the
company.
   In papers filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Kingsbridge Capital Group said it would continue to buy Dunkin'
Donuts stock and raised the possibility of a leveraged buyout.
   Kingsbridge said its options included buying up more shares of
Dunkin' Donuts, proposing a merger, mounting a hostile takeover or
a waging proxy battle for control of the company's board.
   Kingsbridge said it has spent $13.4 million in buying 422,000
shares of Dunkin' Donuts, 6.6 percent of the shares outstanding as
of Feb. 28.
   The action sent Dunkin' Donuts stock shooting up $1.62{ to close
at $37.87{ in over-the-counter trading Thursday.
   Dunkin' Donuts owns or franchises 1,786 stores in the United
States, Mexico, Canada and Japan, with total sales last year of
$750 million, according to Wall Street analysts.
   The company reported 1988 earnings of $13.5 million, or $2.05 a
share, on revenue of $112.8 million.
   Analysts said they believe the prosperous and well-known
doughnut-maker would fight a takeover bid.
   ``Here is a company has not had a down year since 1974,'' said
Willard W. Brown, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New
York.
   ``There is no question in my mind that this company is extremely
well managed,'' he said. ``Since 1974 there have been several
recessions and they continue to make money every year.''
   The most Kingsbridge could afford to pay per share, without
selling off real estate or other major assets, would be $40 per
share, Brown said, and Dunkin' Donuts stock already is near that
figure.
   ``We can't see anything over $40. It looks real difficult to do
that,'' Brown said.
   Kingsbridge said it plans to file a formal report with the
Federal Trade Commission and the Justice Department under the
Hart-Scott-Rodino laws relating to acquisition of more than $15
million but less than 15 percent of a company's outstanding shares.
   Because of Dunkin' Donuts' antitakeover provisions bylaws and
shareholder rights plan, Kingsbridge said it has no immediate plans
to acquire 15 percent or more of Dunkin' Donuts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
