<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Giro     04-20 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Giro,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Bank To Be Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's state-run Girobank, which operates
through post offices, will be sold for 130 million pounds, or $222
million, to a savings and loan society, the government said
Thursday.
   Girobank has become the sixth-largest bank in Britain since it
was set up by the Labor Party government in 1968 to provide cheap
and easy banking in competition with the big clearing banks.
   It has 2.5 million customers doing business through the mail and
at the country's 20,000 post offices.
   Girobank's net assets are valued at around 100 million pounds,
or $171 million dollars.
   The offer from the Alliance and Leicester Building Society was
one of four bids and was accepted after the government failed to
find a satisfactory buyer last year. To prevent a reduction of
competition, the clearing banks were barred from bidding.
   The Post Office said Girobank will continue to operate through
post offices and it expects the deal to be completed by early
summer.
   Girobank is the latest state enterprise to be sold off by Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservatives, who are rolling back
the nationalization carried out by the socialist Labor governments.
   Other sales have included British Petroleum, British Gas,
airports, docks, trucking, Jaguar cars, British Telecom and British
Aerospace.
</TEXT>
