<FIRST>u f AM-TimePublisher     04-20 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time Publisher,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit News Publisher Tapped as Publisher of Time Magazine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The publisher and chief executive of The Detroit
News, Louis A. Weil III, has been selected as the publisher of the
U.S. edition of Time magazine, it was announced Thursday.
   The selection of the veteran newspaper executive to become the
12th publisher in the 66-year history of Time magazine was part of
a broader realignment of senior management within the Time Inc.
Magazine Co.
   Under the realignment, Time publisher Robert L. Miller becomes
worldwide publisher in charge of overseeing the U.S. edition of
Time magazine as well as Time International, People and Sports
Illustrated.
   Reginald Brack, chairman, president and chief executive of
Time's magazine operations, said Miller's expanded responsibilities
and Weil's appointment ``will enable us to better leverage Time
Inc.'s unique strength as the only American publisher of mre than
one weekly magazine.''
   Weil, 48, began his publishing career with the Times-Herald of
Port Huron, Mich., in 1966.
   He later rose to the position of publisher at the Journal &amp;
Courier in Lafayette, Ind., which was acquired by Gannett Co. Inc.
   In the Gannett organization, Weil became president and publisher
of the Westchester-Rockland newspaper chain, based in White Plains,
N.Y.
   He was named president of the Detroit News in 1986 and added the
titles and responsibilities of publisher and chief executive a year
later.
   In his new post, Weil will report to Miller.
   Meanwhile, Gannett announced that Robert H. Giles has been named
editor and publisher of The Detroit News.
   Giles is currently vice president and executive editor of The
News.
</TEXT>
