<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Weyerhaeuser     04-20 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Weyerhaeuser,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Up, But Timber Giant To Sell Some Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Promising a ``significantly changed
Weyerhaeuser Co.,'' the wood-products giant said Thursday it would
review its businesses, reorganizing and selling those that might do
better on their own, to increase returns to shareholders.
   While the company reported a 29 percent increase in profit
Thursday for a record first quarter, Chairman and Chief Executive
George Weyerhaeuser said that wasn't good enough.
   ``Our performance overall is not satisfactory to us in
competitive terms,'' he told shareholders.
   President John Creighton said the review of businesses, which
include pulp and paper, timber products, real estate, mortgage
financing, nursery supply and personal care products, would begin
next month.
   ``The effort is focused primarily on developing improvement
strategies and plans for achieving a leadership position in each
and every business sector in which we choose to compete,'' he said.
   The review would appear to put at risk at least part of the
century-old company's traditional timber business, especially
logging and milling. While its pulp and paper mills have been
highly profitable in recent years, it has said it would get rid of
its logging operations altogether, and give the work to contract
loggers, if its workers didn't accept what amounted to major pay
cuts.
   ``A significantly changed Weyerhaeuser Co. will emerge as the
outcome of these efforts,'' said Creighton. ``I expect it to have
fewer, and a less complex group of, businesses.''
   Weyerhaeuser reported its profit for the quarter ended March 26
was $148 million, or 70 cents a share, compared with $115 million,
or 54 cents a share, for the same quarter in 1988.
   Sales also hit a first-quarter record at $2.3 billion, up 9
percent.
   The board also declared a dividend of 30 cents per share on
common stock, payable May 30 to shareholders of record on April 28.
   Weyerhaeuser said the arctic cold front that hammered the
country in February hit the company hard, but that strength in pulp
and paper markets and in Weyerhaeuser Real Estate Co. dealings
contributed to the improvement in earnings.
   He said weak spots included Weyerhaeuser Mortgage Co., which was
buffeted by higher interest rates; nursery supply, due to the
weather; and personal care products, due to development costs.
</TEXT>
