<SECOND>AM-Earns-American Express,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amex's Profit Slips 3.7 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co. Thursday reported a 3.7
percent profit decline in the first quarter from a year earlier
when the big travel and financial services concern made $19 million
from a discontinued operation.
   The deterioration in earnings occurred despite a 21.4 percent
expansion in revenue.
   American Express said its after-tax earnings amounted to $251.9
million, or 59 cents a share, in the three months ended March 31,
compared to $261.6 million, or 61 cents a share, in the comparable
1988 period.
   Revenue totaled $5.87 billion, up from $4.83 billion a year
earlier.
   Last year's first-quarter profit included $19 million in
earnings from the Fireman's Fund Corp. and from a gain on the sale
of the insurance unit's common stock. In its bookkeeping, American
Express now treats Fireman's Fund Corp. as a discontinued operation.
   A $15 million first-quarter loss registered at American Express'
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. brokerage impaired the parent company's
bottom line. American Express owns about 60 percent of Shearson.
   Shearson, which released its financial results on Wednesday,
attributed the loss to weak activity on Wall Street, higher
interest rates and a $35.2 million pre-tax write-down of MCorp
securities held by the firm. In the first quarter of 1988, Shearson
had a $75 million-profit, or 75 cents a share, after taxes.
   The Travel Related Services division, which includes the credit
card and travelers check businesses and is the largest operation of
American Express, performed strongly in the first quarter.
   Net income in this division grew 18.5 percent to a first-quarter
record of $185.4 million from $156.5 million. The number of credit
cards in force rose 15 percent to 32.4 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
