<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Brokerages     04-20 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Brokerages,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Drop in First Quarter Earnings at PaineWebber</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PaineWebber Group Inc., one of the biggest
American brokerage houses, reported a 55.7 percent tumble in
first-quarter earnings Thursday and attributed it to a general
slump in the securities business.
   The company said earnings for the three months ended March 31
totaled $9.18 million, vs. $20.76 million in the year-earlier
quarter. Earnings per share, after deducting preferred stock
dividends, totaled 11 cents, vs. 48 cents a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenues totaled $396.97 million, a 13 percent
decline from $457.31 million in the 1988 first quarter.
   Donald B. Marron, chairman and chief executive, said the results
reflected ``the negative impact of a difficult trading environment
and sluggish investor activity.''
   Marron said the company has been attempting to cut expenses by
reducing its support staff and marginally profitable businesses. He
said the steps taken so far ``have had a positive effect on our
cost base.''
   Several major Wall Street firms have reported depressed
first-quarter earnings, raising the probability of more layoffs and
shrinkage in an industry that has never recovered from the effects
of the October 1987 stock market crash.
   PaineWebber, based in New York, is the seventh-largest U.S.
brokerage, with a capital base of more than $1.4 billion and a
staff of 12,600 people in 286 offices worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
