<FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-89 2116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DealBlocked     04-20 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deal Blocked,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceramics Company Agrees To Divest Defense-Related Assets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HASKELL, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Ceramics Inc. and federal officials
continued to work on an agreement Thursday that would allow the
company to be purchased by a Japanese firm, officials said.
   Desiree Tucker Sorini, a U.S. Treasury Department spokeswoman,
said she could not confirm published reports that General Ceramics
agreed to divest itself of defense-related operations to allow it
to be acquired by Tokuyama Soda Co. of Japan.
   The Treasury Department is part of the interagency Committee on
Foreign Investment in the United States, which is reviewing the
acquisition.
   But Ms. Sorini said the company had withdrawn its notice of sale
from the interagency panel, gaining it time to physically transfer
equipment to a new owner if it is divesting.
   Carolyn Gagas, a company spokeswoman, declined to discuss the
deal Thursday.
   Ms. Gagas referred to a company statement released Monday that
said Tokuyama Soda expects to proceed with the proposed transaction
when ``arrangements satisfactory to the government have been worked
out.''
   General Ceramics is the sole supplier of beryllium oxide parts
used in the manufacture of nuclear weapons. The company holds a
classified contract with Martin-Marietta Energy Systems Inc., the
primary contract operator of the Defense Department's vast Y-12
plant at Oak Ridge, Tenn.
   If the company divests itself of defense-related aspects of its
business, the panel is likely to recommend that President Bush
allow Tokuyama Soda to take over General Ceramics, officials have
said.
   The law under which the Bush administration stopped the
acquisition was passed in August. It gives the administration the
power to go to court to block deals that endanger national security.
   This was the first time a foreign acquisition had been blocked
since enactment of the law, said Douglas Elmets, an Energy
Department spokesman.
   The Committee on Foreign Investment is composed of
representatives of the Treasury, State, Commerce, Defense, Justice
and Energy departments and the Office of the U.S. Trade
Representative.
   Earlier this year, Bush cleared Monsanto Co.'s sale of a silicon
wafer-manufacturing division to Heuls AG of West Germany after a
similar review by the panel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
